http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.kare11.com/money/business_article.aspx%3Fstoryid%3D255755&cid=1116817306&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ kare11.com :: KARE 11 TV - Business Articles Ceridian agrees to be sold for $5.3 billion cash Ceridian agrees to be sold for $5.3 billion cash , Web Content Producer Payroll processor Ceridian Corp. said Wednesday it agreed to a buyout from investment firm Thomas H. Lee Partners LP and insurance provider Fidelity National Financial Inc. in a cash deal valued at about $5.3 billion. Under the terms of the deal, Ceridian shareholders will receive $36 for each share they own. The deal represents a 5.3 percent premium over Ceridian's closing price on Wednesday and a 17 percent premium over its closing price Feb. 12, the last trading day before the company announced it was looking into strategic options. "We believe these firms bring complementary skills which will help us build upon our leadership position as we continue to implement our strategic plan," said Kathryn V. Marinello, president and chief executive, in a statement. Ceridian announced that it was looking into strategic options after the hedge fund Pershing Square Capital Management LP pressured the company to spin off its fast-growing Comdata division, writing to the company's board that it was concerned the division would be worth more as a stand-alone company. Comdata issues and process credit and gift cards. Investors have also been hoping that Ceridian could make its human resources business more profitable. Ceridian, in its statement, said the Comdata division was kept in mind as the board evaluated several strategic alternatives. Fidelity National Chairman and Chief Executive William P. Foley II cited Ceridian's position in large, growing markets and its strong cash flow, among other factors, in explaining Fidelity's interest in the company. "We are very excited about our investment in Ceridian," he said. THL Partners and Fidelity National said they expect to bring co-investors into the transaction. Fidelity National will own less than 50 percent of Ceridian at closing. The deal is expected to close in the fourth quarter. Shares of Ceridian -- based in the Twin Cities suburb of Bloomington -- rose 47 cents to $34.19 in regular trading. In aftermarket activity, they added another $1.41, or 4.1 percent, to $35.60. The stock has ranged from $21.76 to $35.35 over the past year. Fidelity National shares rose 57 cents, or 2.1 percent, to $27.57, then lost 7 cents after hours. Earlier Wednesday, shares traded at a new 52-week high of $27.59. (Copyright 2007 by The Associated Press. All Rights Reserved.) Last Updated: 5/31/2007 6:47:40 AM Get Business News via RSS Email this Story to a Friend Athlete of the Week Land of 10,000 Stories Athlete of the Week Terms and Conditions of Use Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights 8811 Olson Memorial Hwy, Minneapolis, MN 55427 KARE-11 is a Division of Multimedia Holdings Corporation &copy;1998- KARE-11 All Rights Reserved
