http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-1&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3DaaD4rIqp59eM%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116733522&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ , May 31 12:13 , May 31 17:13 , Jun 01 01:13 Northwest Exits Bankruptcy After Paring Fleet, Jobs (Update1) May 31 (Bloomberg) -- Northwest Airlines Corp., the last U.S. carrier in bankruptcy, left court protection today after reducing operating costs close to the lowest in the industry. Northwest used its 20 months in bankruptcy to carve $2.4 billion, or 20 percent, from its annual expenses. It slashed labor spending by $1.4 billion, or 40 percent. The fifth-largest U.S. airline also reorganized regional flights, trimmed its fleet by 13 percent, and replaced older fuel-guzzling planes. ``They were pretty aggressive,&#39;&#39; said William Warlick, a Fitch Inc. analyst in Chicago. ``The proof is in the pudding, and they&#39;re going to come out of bankruptcy with lower costs than virtually all other legacy carriers.&#39;&#39; The reorganization will produce a $794 million profit in 2007 after last year&#39;s $2.84 billion loss, Northwest estimates. Last quarter&#39;s operating profit margin was 7 percent, the best among major U.S. airlines. AMR Corp.&#39;s American Airlines was second with a 4.6 percent margin. Northwest, based in Eagan, Minnesota, was the last of four large U.S. airlines to file for bankruptcy after air travel slumped in the wake of the 2001 terrorist attacks. US Airways Group Inc., filed in August 2002 and again in September 2004; UAL Corp.&#39;s United Airlines in December 2002; and Delta Air Lines Inc. about 30 minutes before Northwest on Sept. 14, 2005. Northwest lost $4.62 billion from 2001 through 2005, and listed debt of $17.9 billion in its filing. ``They had the benefit of being the last through,&#39;&#39; said Robert Mann of R.W. Mann & Co., a Port Washington, New York- based consultant for airlines and labor groups. ``On that basis, they were able to work off everyone else&#39;s set of objectives.&#39;&#39; Before the filing, Chief Executive Officer Doug Steenland hired two lieutenants with a bankruptcy background at US Airways. Chief Financial Officer Neal Cohen joined four months before the bankruptcy, and Controller David Davis came aboard five days beforehand. ``They had a lot of experience and a lot to draw on in negotiating tough deals with labor groups and vendors,&#39;&#39; Warlick said. With ``relatively good&#39;&#39; non-labor costs, the airline focused on paring personnel expenses, said analyst Philip Baggaley of Standard & Poor&#39;s in New York. Steenland and his executives trimmed the workforce by 22 percent from June 30, 2005, to 30,008 employees as of March 31. They also pushed through reductions in salary, vacation time, sick leave, health-care benefits and crew meals and accommodations. The new, lower-cost union contracts run for five to six years, providing savings for a longer period than competitors&#39; wage agreements, Northwest said. ``These guys are as tough as they come,&#39;&#39; said Darryl Jenkins, an independent airline industry consultant in Marshall, Virginia. Excluding fuel, Northwest cut its cost to fly each seat one mile to 7.7 cents last year, from 8.9 cents before it filed for bankruptcy. That compared with 7.4 cents at Delta and 9.1 cents at United, according to Northwest. Unlike Delta, which exited bankruptcy April 30 after shifting jets to international routes, Northwest didn&#39;t have to change strategy. It already had a larger share of higher-profit overseas flights than most peers. About 41 percent of Northwest&#39;s capacity last year was on international routes, second only to the 47 percent of Continental Airlines Inc., according to Cathay Financial Inc. analyst Susan Donofrio in New York. The lack of an ``open skies&#39;&#39; agreement between China and the U.S. means Northwest and United will keep their edge in Pacific passenger traffic before the 2008 Beijing Olympics, said Roger King, a debt analyst for New York-based CreditSights Inc. ``They have a pretty nice asset in the Pacific and fly along the northern tier of the U.S., which means they have less low-cost carrier competition,&#39;&#39; King said. To further trim expenses and ferry passengers to U.S. hubs including Minneapolis and Detroit, Northwest started one new regional carrier, Compass Airlines, and bought another, Mesaba Airlines. It cut its fleet to 375 planes as of March 31, compared with 433 in mid-2005, including replacing all 15 DC-10s with newer jets to save on maintenance and fuel. The reorganization didn&#39;t help labor relations. Flight attendants rejected two tentative agreements for $195 million in concessions before approving a third this week, with 51 percent voting in support. The attendants and unions for pilots and other employees have criticized the carrier&#39;s plans to distribute $297 million in shares to Steenland and other managers. Northwest&#39;s unsecured creditors will get 236 million of the carrier&#39;s new shares, of a total of 263.8 million that the carrier plans to issue. The shares rose 68 cents to $25.18 at 9:58 a.m. in New York Stock Exchange composite trading, valuing the creditors&#39; equity stake at $5.94 billion. Northwest&#39;s plan to sell $750 million in new shares beyond the stock distributed to creditors ``will bolster their balance sheet and cash further,&#39;&#39; S&P&#39;s Baggaley said. ``That&#39;s a move the other bankrupt airlines have not taken.&#39;&#39; To contact the reporter on this story: Susanna Ray in Chicago at Last Updated: May 31, 2007 10:04 EDT Related Media on Demand Neidl of Calyon Sees Northwest as `Tough Competitor&#39; Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division U.S. Economy Grows at 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Treasury 10-Year Yield at 2007 High on Chicago Business Index Increase
http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/67822.html&cid IBM lays off 1,570 U.S. workers to cut costs said it laid off about 1,570 employees on Wednesday in its computer services business in the United States, part of a plan to trim costs in the unit."> IBM lays off 1,570 U.S. workers to cut costs said it laid off about 1,570 employees on Wednesday in its computer services business in the United States, part of a plan to trim costs in the unit." align="left"> Thu, 31 May 2007 00:08:00GMT US Business News | SAN FRANCISCO (Reuters) - International Business Machines Corp. said it laid off about 1,570 employees on Wednesday in its computer services business in the United States, part of a plan to trim costs in the unit. The lay-offs bring to about 3,700 the number of jobs IBM has cut this year in its services unit, which accounts for about half of total revenue but whose profit lags the company's software business. Earlier this month, IBM eliminated about 1,300 jobs in the U.S. services business. The rest were cut in the first quarter. IBM, which had 355,766 employees at the end of 2006, said on April 17 it was cutting costs in the United States amid weaker U.S. demand for its services and products in the first quarter. IBM spokesman John Bukovinsky said he did not have information showing where Wednesday's job cuts took place. IBM, based in Armonk, New York, is trying to boost profitability in services by replacing some employees with software that can be replicated from one contract to another. This year's job cuts occurred as customers shortened or otherwise cut services contracts, Bukovinsky said. "The services business is tremendously cyclical," he said. "This is basically the result of (clients) looking over longer-term contracts and deciding they don't want the work done, or deciding they can do the work with fewer people." Bukovinsky said the jobs were not being shifted to lower-cost labor markets such as India. IBM in the first quarter paid about $55 million for job cuts. (c) Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Republication or redistribution of Reuters content, including by caching, framing or similar means, is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of Reuters. Reuters and the Reuters sphere logo are registered trademarks and trademarks of the Reuters group of companies around the world. Email this article (Click Here) Share this article on &raquo; - Obese more likely to file workers' comp | 24 Apr 2007 - GM, UAW reach deal on "jobs bank" | 24 May 2007 - U.S. business, labor debate immigration | 29 May 2007 - OSHA's George H.R. Taylor dead at 95 | 02 Apr 2007 - Productivity grows at surprising clip | 03 May 2007 Circuit City to trim HQ jobs, shift store staff YouTube signs broad licensing pact with EMI Five winners picked for big telecoms contract Home price rise slowest in a decade Texas Instruments says Q2 improvements on track The views expressed in the articles are not necessarily those of earthtimes.org and we accept no responsibility for the views or opinions expressed in the articles either direct or indirect. , All Rights Reserved.
