http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-1&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3DaJiD0VuMHAo0%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116842619&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ , May 31 12:13 , May 31 17:13 , Jun 01 01:13 WellPoint Dismisses Finance Chief, Citing Conduct (Update5) By John Lauerman and Michelle Fay Cortez May 31 (Bloomberg) -- WellPoint Inc. fired Chief Financial Officer David C. Colby, named the best health insurance CFO each of the past four years by Institutional Investor magazine, over unspecified violations of company rules. The conduct-code breaches were ``of a non-business nature&#39;&#39; and didn&#39;t involve illegality, WellPoint, the second-biggest U.S. health-insurance provider, said today in a statement. The company, based in Indianapolis, said its financial statements and forecasts are accurate. Colby, 53, left as Chief Executive Officer Larry C. Glasscock prepared to hand the top job at WellPoint to Angela F. Braly tomorrow. Colby was finance chief of WellPoint Health Networks Inc. in November 2004 when the company was bought by Anthem Inc. The acquirer took the name WellPoint and kept Colby as executive vice president and CFO. Wayne S. DeVeydt, 37, who was chief accounting officer, now succeeds Colby. ``We view Wayne as a solid choice to step into the CFO slot,&#39;&#39; said Justin Lake, an analyst at UBS Securities LLC in New York, in a note to investors today. ``That said, it will likely take the market some time to ingest the significant management turnover occurring at the company over the last several months.&#39;&#39; Colby didn&#39;t respond to an e-mail. A call placed to his office was forwarded to a spokeswoman. WellPoint shares fell $1.52, or 1.8 percent, to $82.88 at 10:23 a.m. in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. The stock had gained 18 percent in the 12 months through yesterday, underperforming a 27 percent increase in the six-member Standard & Poor&#39;s 500 Managed Care Index. UnitedHealth Group Inc., based in Minnetonka, Minnesota, is the largest U.S. medical insurance provider. An investigation of Colby&#39;s conduct by external legal counsel began in ``recent days,&#39;&#39; Glasscock said on a telephone call with investors and analysts. ``Certain concerns were raised, and we immediately began an investigation,&#39;&#39; Glasscock said. ``Based on this investigation, it was concluded that David Colby violated the company&#39;s code of conduct.&#39;&#39; WellPoint&#39;s code, available on the company&#39;s Web site, is a 25-page document that covers a variety of issues, including ethical decision-making, reporting of violations, protecting information, and maintaining the workplace environment. It sets limits on blogging and other Internet use; drugs and alcohol; possession of weapons; and political activity. Violating the code, or authorizing, failing to report, or failing to cooperate with an investigation of, a violation, can result in corrective action ``including termination of employment,&#39;&#39; the handbook says. Institutional Investor ranked Colby the top managed-care CFO in March, saying that investors ``credit Colby with helping to maintain stable financial results during the late 1990s, a tumultuous time for health insurers when public opinion of them plummeted. Many smaller companies went out of business or sought refuge in the arms of successful consolidators.&#39;&#39; The former finance chief was treated as any other employee would have been, Glasscock said. ``What&#39;s really important is that all of us read and agree to abide by the code of conduct,&#39;&#39; Glasscock said. ``We don&#39;t have double standards in the company. We have one set of standards that apply to everyone.&#39;&#39; Glasscock wouldn&#39;t say whether he thought Colby would sue the company for his dismissal. ``Obviously Dave Colby will make the decisions he thinks are appropriate for Dave Colby,&#39;&#39; Glasscock said. ``I believe we&#39;ve done absolutely the right thing based on where the facts led us.&#39;&#39; DeVeydt has been WellPoint&#39;s senior vice president and chief accounting officer since March 2005. He also assumed responsibility for investor relations and became chief of staff to Glasscock in 2006. Before joining WellPoint, DeVeydt served with PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP in many roles since 1996. ``While the circumstances we reported today are unfortunate, I&#39;m very pleased and honored to assume the role of chief financial officer,&#39;&#39; DeVeydt said on the telephone call. WellPoint announced Colby&#39;s latest recognition by Institutional Investor in a news release on Feb. 21. DeVeydt, in charge of investor relations, was listed as a contact person. To contact the reporter on this story: John Lauerman in Boston at ; Michelle Fay Cortez in Minneapolis at Last Updated: May 31, 2007 11:14 EDT Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division U.S. Economy Grows at 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Treasury 10-Year Yield at 2007 High on Chicago Business Index Increase
