of proxy materials with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Ceridian said it would hold its annual meeting no later than Sept. 21. Ceridian and the buyers said they expected that the purchase would close by the end of the year. is serving as financial adviser to Ceridian, and Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &#38; Katz is serving as legal adviser. Securities acted as financial adviser to Thomas H. Lee and Fidelity; Deutsche Bank and will finance the deal. Weil, Gotshal &#38; Manges is acting as legal adviser for Thomas H. Lee and Fidelity. Next Article in Business (14 of 30) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. COMPANY NEWS; CERIDIAN TO SEPARATE INTO TWO COMPANIES BY YEAR-END THE MARKETS: Market Place; Wild Ascent Of a Small-Cap Stock, Perhaps By Mistake COMPANY NEWS; CERIDIAN AGREES TO BUY ABR INFORMATION SERVICES COMPANY NEWS; CERIDIAN TO BUY LIFEWORKS, A RIVAL IN EMPLOYEE SERVICES Mergers, Acquisitions and Divestitures Lee, Thomas H, Partners Fidelity National Financial Incorporated Next Article in Business (14 of 30) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France Open a Complete Savings Acct from E*TRADE Bank Towers in the Fog - 1992 Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art & Design &#x00bb; Sarkozys: The French Kennedys? Phil Spector’s Long and Winding Road The Dirty Water Underground An Animated Film by Jeff Scher Artist Sets Up House(s) at the Grand Palais The New York Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-4&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/chicago-purchasing-managers-index-improves/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257B957B1EA2-6A72-421F-B6C5-CD0C4EF8FCA3%257D&cid=1116844899&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Chicago Purchasing Managers Index improves in May - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Chicago business-activity index picks up in May Last Update: 10:23 AM ET May 31, 2007 WASHINGTON (MarketWatch) -- Business activity in the Chicago region improved in May, according to a survey of corporate purchasing managers released Thursday. The Chicago purchasing-managers' index rose to 61.7% in May from 52.9% in April, the Chicago NAPM reported. The size of the gain surprised analysts. Economists were expecting the Chicago PMI index to inch higher to 54.0%. Readings over 50% indicate that more firms were expanding than contracting. The report seems to dovetail with recent data that point to a modest recovery in manufacturing after a slow patch in the first quarter. Just how slow things were in the first quarter was revealed earlier on Thursday when the government revised down its estimate of first quarter growth to a paltry 0.6%, the slowest pace in four years. The Chicago PMI has been of interest chiefly because it was seen to provide hints as to the movement in the national Institute of Supply Management index, which will be released on Friday. But economists say the Chicago report has provided little information about the national index in the last few years. Before the Chicago index was released, economists are looking for the ISM to slip to 53.5% in May, after surging to 54.7% in April. In the Chicago report, the new orders index rose to 71.1% from 56.5% in the previous month. Production jumped to 69.8% from 62.2% in April. This was the highest level of production since April 2005. The employment index rose to 57.3% from 50.5%. The prices paid index rose to 70.2 from 64.9% in April. The Chicago index covers all types of firms, not just manufacturers. In a separate report, the Commerce Department said construction spending rose 0.1% in April. In another report, the Labor Department said jobless claims fell slightly in the latest week. Greg Robb is a senior reporter for MarketWatch in Washington. Related Blog Posts & Articles U.S. April construction spending rises 0.1% Home prices rise at slowest pace in 10 years Jobless claims fall back slightly in latest week U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter 97,000 jobs added in May, ADP says Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion Jobs wants to use iPhone to put the 'baby Internet' to bed U.S. futures up after Wachovia deal, Yahoo upgrade Want to beat the market? Take the inside path U.S. stocks rise amid deal news Thursday's biggest stock gainers and decliners U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Stocks in focus for Thursday Dell seen posting 22% drop in profit as it fights H-P threat Rouleau still seeing a 'mini-bull' market to be avoided Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion Jobs wants to use iPhone to put the 'baby Internet' to bed Big drug wholesalers may get bigger, with FDA help Want to beat the market? Take the inside path Three specialty REITs to buy on a pullback U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Growing share of 'Big Three' drug wholesalers gets attention U.S. mortgage rates edge higher for third straight week Five ways unmarried partners can safeguard their finances Bristol-Myers pleads guilty in federal Plavix case Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion U.S. stocks rise amid deal news U.S. mortgage rates edge higher for third straight week U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Dell seen posting 22% drop in profit as it fights H-P threat Get the Latest MarketWatch News >> Industry: Industrial Products & Services Dow Jones Licensing Services Dow Jones Online Network: Copyright &copy; 2007 MarketWatch, Inc. All rights reserved. By using this site, you agree to the Chicago Purchasi