http://www.twincities.com/business/ci_6024065&cid TwinCities.com - Ceridian to be sold for $5.3 billion Working Q & A Ceridian to be sold for $5.3 billion Under pressure from key investor, company agrees to private buyout Article Last Updated: 05/30/2007 09:43:37 PM CDT After months of pressure from an unhappy shareholder, Ceridian Corp. said Wednesday that it will be sold for $5.3 billion to Thomas H. Lee Partners, a private-equity group, and Fidelity National Financial Inc. Ceridian, which provides human-resources and computer-processing services for business clients, will keep its headquarters in Bloomington, and Kathryn Marinello will remain as CEO, a company spokesman said Wednesday. The company employs about 1,000 people in Minnesota. After a review of "strategic alternatives" aimed at providing maximum value to the company's shareholders, Ceridian's board decided that a sale "represents the best and most certain way to achieve that goal," L. White Matthews, chairman of Ceridian's board, said in a release Wednesday. The deal will pay Ceridian shareholders $36 cash per share, a 5 percent premium over Wednesday's closing price of $34.19. In a release about the deal, Ceridian noted that the price represents a 17 percent premium over the closing stock price on Feb. 12, the day before Ceridian announced it was exploring strategic alternatives. News of the deal came after the market's close, but most of the increase already had been built into the stock. Ceridian shares went up another $1.41 to $35.60 in after-hours trading. Ceridian traces its corporate lineage back to Control Data Corp. and now is among the largest human-resources outsourcing companies. Despite steady growth, the company ran into difficulties with its largest investor earlier this year. William Ackman, who heads Pershing Square Capital Management, a hedge fund that owns 14 percent of Ceridian's outstanding shares, demanded in January that Ceridian spin off its profitable Comdata division. He publicized his demands after a face-to-face meeting with Marinello left him unsatisfied with the company's direction. Marinello had taken over as CEO last fall. Ackman also is proposing his own slate of candidates for the company's board of directors. Shareholders will vote on board members at Ceridian's annual meeting, which has yet to be scheduled. The deal announced Wednesday will get a vote from shareholders at the annual meeting as well, Ceridian said. The meeting will be scheduled "as soon as practicable following the filing and review of proxy materials," the company's release said, and will take place no later than Sept. 21. While Ceridian remained profitable, its larger human-resources division was seen as a laggard compared with the smaller Comdata division, which processes and issues credit, debit and gift cards, primarily for trucking and retail customers in the United States. In 2005, for instance, Comdata generated 28 percent of Ceridian's revenue, but 74 percent of Ceridian's operating earnings. Earlier this month, Ceridian fired Gary Krow, the president of the Comdata division, after he allegedly provided Pershing Square with confidential information. In a release earlier this month, Ackman said that Krow had told him in January that he was planning to leave Comdata because his authority had been diminished and because he disagreed with the strategic direction of Ceridian. Attempts to reach Ackman by phone Wednesday for comment on the Ceridian deal were unsuccessful. Thomas H. Lee Partners and Fidelity National will each own roughly half of Ceridian when the deal is done, and each expects to bring in co-investors. "We are extremely impressed with Kathy Marinello and the management team of Ceridian," said Scott Jaeckel, managing director of Thomas H. Lee Partners. "We fully support their vision and commitment to all of Ceridian's customers and employees." The deal will bring some uncertainty to Ceridian employees, though. In a QA e-mail sent to employees Wednesday, one question asked about any work-force reductions resulting from the deal. Ceridian answered that it will "continue to evaluate the resources required to implement the company's strategic plan and will make adjustments as necessary." Thomas H. Lee Partners has about $12 billion in equity capital invested in more than 100 businesses. Its deals have given it a stake in West Corp., Dunkin Brands, Fisher Scientific, Experian and Snapple Beverage. Fidelity National is a leading provider of title and specialty insurance. John Welbes can be reached at jwelbes@pioneerpress.com or 651-228-2175. The Pioneer Press is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. Please note: It may take several minutes before your comment appears. (From the last 24 hours) Wal-Mart cashier: I was fired for joking State alleges conspiracy in Milwaukee bribery scandal; defense says... Minnesota gas prices dip slightly No Powerball winner, jackpot goes to $25 million Minnesota authorities hunt for missing sex offender (From the last 24 hours) Wisconsin priest tells church organist she can't sell sex toys More than a ton of pot seized in Dakota County bust Typo made her rich - for 2 months A church built on faith, beer St. Paul teacher accused of sexual contact with student 3M Settles Battery Patent Suit Against Matsushita Minnesota authorities hunt for missing sex offender Campfire restrictions eased in Superior National Forest Minnesota gas prices dip slightly State alleges conspiracy in Milwaukee bribery scandal; defense says it was street slang No Powerball winner, jackpot goes to $25 million Truck's cargo: hard candy and $3 million in pot Fliers want more flights, smiles from Northwest SP hits record closeup Deal is likely a foretaste of sales to come Minnesota native to lead KPMG Ceridian to be sold for $5.3 billion Land prices flat? Go figure Coasting to high MPG About the Real Cities Network MNG Corporate Site Map
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-1&fd=R&url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/18945599/&cid=1116798859&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ ACLU sues Boeing arm over CIA renditions - Financial Times - MSNBC.com ACLU sues Boeing arm over CIA renditions By By Demetri Sevastopulo in Washington The American Civil Liberties Union sued a Boeing subsidiary on Wednesday for allegedly helping the Central Intelligence Agency transport prisoners under its extraordinary renditions programme. The ACLU lawsuit alleges that the subsidiary, California-based Jeppesen DataÂ­plan, provided the CIA with services for flights that were used to send three prisoners to secret detention facilities where they claim they were tortured. According to the ACLU complaint, Binyam MohÂ­amed, an Ethiopian, Ahmed Agiza, an Egyptian, and Abou Elkassim Britel, an Italian citizen, were all subject to the CIA renditions programme, in which prisoners are captured in one country and sent to CIA overseas secret detention sites, or to other countries' intelligence services, for interrogation. "We are filing this lawsuit on behalf of three individuals who have been repeatedly tortured, terrified, humiliated and deprived of their basic human rights," said Anthony Romero, the executive director of the ACLU. "American companies should not be profiting from a CIA rendition programme that is unlawful and contrary to core American values." President George W. Bush conceded the existence of the secret detention sites last year. The ACLU says Mr Agiza is imprisoned in Egypt, while Mr Britel is being held in Morocco. An Italian judge has dismissed all charges of suspected terrorism against Mr Britel. Dozens of members of the Italian parliament have petitioned Morocco over his release. As part of its case, the ACLU cites comments by a senior Jeppesen Dataplan executive in a New Yorker magazine article, in which he says the company "do all of the extraordinary rendition flights â€“ you know, the torture flights". The CIA and Boeing both declined to comment on the lawsuit. In a related case, the ACLU also petitioned the Supreme Court on Wednesday over the case of Khaled al-Masri, a Lebanese-born German who was captured in Macedonia in December 2003 and allegedly held until May 2004 by the CIA in a secret prison in Afghanistan. A federal court dismissed a previous lawsuit that accused George Tenet, the former CIA director, of violating human rights laws by authorising CIA operatives to capture Mr Masri. The court agreed to dismiss the case on the grounds that it could compromise state secrets. A former intelligence official told the FT that Mr Tenet's office had agreed to apprehend Mr Masri despite warnings from senior intelligence operatives that he had no connection with the "war on terror" and that his name "al-Masri", which translates as "the Egyptian," was a common name in the Middle East. The ACLU alleges that Jeppesen provided logistics services, such as flight planning, catering and hotel accommodation for crew, for more than 70 rendition flights involving two aircraft over a four-year period. The lawsuit also accuses Jeppesen of providing services for the flight used to transport Mr Masri. Copyright The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. MORE FROM FINANCIAL TIMES HIGHLIGHTS Financial Times Highlights Section Front US economic growth slows to 0.6% Bush unveils strategy on climate change Wall St builds on record levels Wachovia to buy AG Edwards for $6.8bn Draghi issues stern warning to Italian business Litvinenko was British spy, says Lugovoi Consumers fuel rise in eurozone optimism CBOT urges backing for CME deal GM scores rare victory over Toyota Morgan Stanley to buy Investa for $3.9bn Financial Times Highlights Section Front New wrinkle for tanning junkies Feds: Top spammer arrested 5 U.S.Â troops die in AfghanÂ crash Bush unveils new climate strategy Dozens slain at Iraq recruit center Harry Potter theme park set to open Divorced couple battles over frozen embryosDivo