http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-0&fd=R&url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/05/31/ap3774069.html&cid=1116817306&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Ahead of the Bell: Ceridian - Forbes.com Ahead of the Bell: Ceridian 05.31.07, 8:40 AM ET Ceridian Corp. is commanding a lower buyout premium than is typical for takeovers, analysts said Thursday, because the stock was already priced assuming the company would sell itself. Late Wednesday, the Minneapolis-based payroll and tax filing services provider said it agreed to sell itself to Thomas H. Lee Partners LP and Fidelity National Financial Inc. for $36 per share cash. The proposal represents a premium of a little more than 5 percent over the stock's closing price of $34.19 Wednesday. Ceridian's stock rose $1.26, or 3.7 percent, to $35.45 in premarket trading Thursday. "Some investors were expecting a larger premium," JPMorgan Securities analyst Tien-tsin Huang wrote in a client note. But analysts said most of the takeover premium has already been built into the shares because investors anticipated a deal. The stock closed Wednesday up 22.2 percent for the year. In December, an investment fund called Pershing Square Capital Management LP became Ceridian's biggest shareholder, with a stake that now totals 14.5 percent of the company's outstanding shares, and began agitating for change. In February, the company hired Greenhill & Co. LLC as a financial adviser to help "explore a broad range of strategic alternatives to enhance shareholder value." The Thomas H. Lee/Fidelity National offer represents a 17.2 percent premium to the stock's price before that announcement. "The sale of the company was already broadly speculated in the market and largely captured in the stock," said Goldman Sachs analyst Elizabeth W. Grausam. Grausam said rampant takeover speculation has pushed up stock prices across the sector, "leaving little room for robust takeout premiums." Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed More On This Topic ",">"); transformedStoryStr=transformedStoryStr.replaceAll(""","\""); out.write(transformedStoryStr); %--> Starting A Small Business Brought to you by the sponsors below A new book from brings the Himalaya experience home.
http://www.ft.com/cms/s/9903966c-0f0a-11dc-b444-000b5df10621.html&cid FT.com / Your money - New money calls for the personal touch Skip to main content, accesskey 's' Subscribe to FT.com or view and edit your subscription details. All times are London time Search News in the FT.com site Search Quotes in the FT.com site LATEST YOUR MONEY STORIES Rates may not yet have hit peak, say economists Buoyant markets bring Isa surprise for class of â€˜99 Your small change will still stay put Big spenders drawn to the Big Apple Insurer defends high rate of rejections Advisers face questions over who pulls the strings Think long-term for their future benefit Elderly gain access to bespoke insurance Following a new flight path Growing numbers take a punt on financial spread bets New money calls for the personal touch Published: January 5 2007 12:06 | Last updated: January 5 2007 12:06 There is a growing queue of private banks and wealth managers chasing the Â£100,000-plus investor as the numbers of these wealthy individuals looks set to break through the 2m barrier for the first time in 2007. Wealth managers and private banks are expanding to meet the demand from the growing numbers of affluent but â€œtime-poorâ€ investors who want professionals to manage their money for them and treat them as a name and not an account number. The bracket between Â£100,000 and Â£250,000 is below the traditional private banking threshold of Â£500,000 but private banks and wealth managers see this sector as the fastest-growing segment of the market. Many of the private banks, several of them acquired recently by high street banks, are targeting the newly affluent. They want to reach a new generation of high- earning clients who are growing in number by 7-10 per cent a year, according to research by business strategy consultants MDRC. The growth of wealth management and private banking is in contrast to dwindling branch networks and declining service offered by the high street banks. The private banks and wealth managers are opening new offices. Lloyds TSB has started opening private banking lounges in high street branches around the UK to offer an exclusive service to its clients. Recent openings include Richmond Upon Thames and the Law Courts in London. Many of the private banks and wealth managers promise old-fashioned personal service â€“ if they like the size of your portfolio. Lloyds TSB Private Banking has 45,000 clients and targets those with assets of Â£250,000 or more but will consider those below, especially those with potential to add to their wealth. It will also take on clients with Â£100,000 who want to use its asset management service. Independent financial advisers are targeting the affluent too and enjoy the biggest wealth management market share at 33 per cent. US-based wealth manager and stockbroker Edward Jones is expanding rapidly and already has more than 100 offices in the UK, the fastest-growing â€œmass affluentâ€ market in Europe. As the banks and wealth managers have stepped up their services, research suggests that the demographics of the sector are changing rapidly. The number of traditionally wealthy, passing family wealth between generations, is static and has been overtaken by growth in the high- earner category. Many of these are City workers enjoying high salaries and bonuses and those running their own businesses. MDRC chief executive Richard Williams says that growth in the high-earner category has reduced the average age of newly affluent investors from 55 to 47 over the past decade. Despite the growth in private banking and wealth management, one in five affluent investors remains suspicious of external wealth managers and prefers a DIY approach. Some are concerned about the quality of advice and high fees. More people are being persuaded, however, that the time saving alone can make it worth considering a professional wealth manager. Among the new clients of wealth managers are Alan Hunter, 61, and John Haddrell, 45, directors of thriving property rental business Midway in Mansfield, Nottinghamshire. As their business grew rapidly along with their personal assets they decided to turn to advisory firm Edward Jones. Their Edward Jones investment representative Vik Sharma regularly visits them at their office and homes. Haddrell, who has a portfolio of more than Â£300,000, says he had previously spent up to seven hours a week managing his own investments. He decided to seek a wealth manager after realising he was spending too much time watching the stock markets and not enough running his business. â€œI was reticent at first to use an adviser because I was concerned about the quality of advice. But I realised that running a business makes life very busy and itâ€™s nice to know somebody is keeping an eye on your investments for you all the time,â€ he says. John Hutchinson, 62, a retired chief executive of a music copyright business, and his wife Elspeth, 60, from Essex, became clients of Lloyds TSB Private Banking last year. Lloyds manages their joint Â£400,000 portfolio and provides tax and trust advice including advice on their two French properties. Barclays Private Banking targets those with more than Â£500,000 but its Premier Banking Service caters for those earning over Â£100,000 or with Â£50,000-plus to invest. HSBC Private Banking offers worldwide offices and Royal Bank of Scotland has expanded its private banking service by acquiring Coutts and Adam & Company. Other private banks include C Hoare & Co, Butterfield Private Bank, Brown Shipley & Co and NM Rothschild & Sons. As the sector has become more competitive, many private banks have added services including independent financial advice, trust and taxation planning and family wealth transfer advice. All offer a personal â€œrelationshipâ€ manager who promises that you will always be a name, not a number. Private banks are not the only providers of wealth management services. There is a growing queue of specialist wealth managers and independent financial advisers targeting the Â£100,000- plus bracket. The Association of Private Client Investment Managers (Apcims) lists more than 200 member firms and the number is growing. Firms offering wealth management services include financial adviser John Scott & Partners, Close Bros, Tilney Investment Management, Killik & Co, and Brewin Dolphin. Andrew Fisher is the chief executive of financial planning business John Scott & Partners, an Apcims member. It has 12 offices, 165 planners and 200,000 clients in the UK. He is a former chief executive of Coutts. He believes that DIY clients in the newly affluent category in particular should give serious consideration to using a wealth manager not just to provide time-saving, professional management but also to provide an valuable external eye on their portfolios. He warns that like medicine, â€œself diagnosisâ€ can be damaging to your financial health. The costs of wealth management will depend on the type of wealth manager but it is worth remembering that the larger the portfolio the lower the annual management percentage fee should be and that fees can be negotiable. Annual charges for portfolio management typically range from 1-2 per cent and private banks will usually charge Â£10-Â£30 per month in bank account fees but will often waive this if large sums are invested. The Financial Times Limited 2007 - create a keyword alert on the subject of this topic - download our application to receive instant alerts on this topic - start your day with daily email briefing on this topic - Track this news topic using our feeds "Middle East" sub navigation "By sector" sub navigation "By region" sub navigation "Markets headlines" sub navigation "Market data" sub navigation Australia & New Zealand "Managed funds" sub navigation "Comment & Analysis" sub navigation Comment & Analysis main "Debates and polls" sub navigation Debates and polls main "Video & Audio" sub navigation Video & Audio main View from the Top "Bu