http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-1&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601103%26sid%3DaMkV7eb24GCw%26refer%3Dnews&cid=1116813923&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ , May 31 12:15 , May 31 17:15 , Jun 01 01:15 Australia & New Zealand IBM Cuts 1,570 Jobs, Mainly in Technology Services (Update5) By Matthew R. Miller May 30 (Bloomberg) -- International Business Machines Corp., the world&#39;s largest computer-services company, cut about 1,570 jobs mainly in its technology services unit, where profit fell 19 percent in the latest quarter. Most of the reductions were in North America and workers were notified today, according to Edward Barbini, a spokesman for Armonk, New York-based IBM. The division accounted for more than a third of IBM&#39;s $22 billion in sales in the first quarter. Today&#39;s cuts are equal to about 1.2 percent of the U.S. workforce. This month IBM also trimmed about 1,300 jobs at its global services unit, which incorporates the technology division, to help reduce expenses in the U.S., where IBM has about 128,000 employees. In the technology unit, first-quarter gross margin, the percentage of sales left after production costs, was unchanged from a year earlier, IBM said last month. IBM shares rose $1.02 to $106.93 at 4 p.m. in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. They have gained 10 percent this year. Chief Executive Officer Sam Palmisano is targeting software, whose sales are growing faster than revenue from services, to help fuel profit growth. IBM aims to get about half its earnings from software by 2010, he said earlier this month. The company also has sought to spur increases by buying back stock, and yesterday said it repurchased about $12.5 billion in shares since announcing the program last month, equal to more than 80 percent the amount planned. IBM bought back 118.8 million shares, or 8 percent of outstanding common stock, at an initial price of $105.18 per share. The move may help boost 2007 earnings per share by 13 percent to 14 percent, IBM said. IBM has cut about 3,000 jobs this quarter, and had 355,800 employees as of last year. Lee Conrad, national coordinator for the Alliance at IBM, estimated that job cuts may reach 12,000 this year, saying the company has moved work overseas. His group, which he says has 400 dues-paying and 5,500 non-paying members, is seeking union recognition at IBM. Barbini declined to comment on further possible reductions. IBM has hired 14,000 workers globally this year, he said. He declined to say how many people are employed in the technology services division. To contact the reporter on this story: Matthew R. Miller in Atlanta at Last Updated: May 30, 2007 17:33 EDT Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division Economy Expands at a 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Home Prices in U.S. Climbed at Slowest Pace in Decade During First Quarter
