http://www.southflorida.com/news/sns-ap-odd-false-bomb-threat,0,5055729.story%3Fcoll%3Dsfe-guide-headlines2&cid Promotional Fax Mistaken for Bomb Threat: SouthFlorida.com Place a classified ad Promotional Fax Mistaken for Bomb Threat Posted May 31 2007, 9:16 AM EDT ASHLAND, Mass. -- A faulty bank fax printed a message that was misinterpreted as a bomb threat Wednesday, leading authorities to evacuate more than a dozen neighboring businesses and a day care center. The branch manager of the Bank of America called police about 10 a.m. after receiving a fax containing images of a lit match and a bomb with a fuse, bank spokesman Ernesto Anguilla said. But text explaining the fax was an internal bank promotion failed to transmit. The missing text included the phrases "The countdown begins" and "Small business commitment week June 4-8," according to a copy circulated by police. "The fax machine malfunctioned, so a partial image came through that looked somewhat suspicious," Anguilla said. Fears also arose because the branch received a suspicious package delivered by a customer around the same time, police said. A State Police bomb squad searched the bank branch and checked out the package, which was a delivery of documents. About 15 small businesses in a shopping plaza were evacuated for about three hours, including a day care center with about 30 children, Police Chief Scott Rohmer said. The fax was sent to the Charlotte, N.C.-based bank's branches in parts of New England, New York and New Jersey. It did not result in any other bomb scares at other branches, Anguilla said. Start a newspaper subscription , Sun-Sentinel Co. & South Florida Interactive, Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-2&fd=R&url=http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/05/31/wachovia-to-buy-ag-edwards-for-68-billion/&cid=1116840254&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for .8 Billion - Mergers, Acquisitions, Venture Capital, Hedge Funds -- DealBook - New York Times tag, as close to the beginning of it as possible--> Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion May 31, 2007, 7:08 am said Thursday it would buy for $6.8 billion in cash and stock, forming the second-largest retail stock brokerage in the United States after . The deal for St. Louis-based A.G. Edwards marks the latest big grab for Wachovia Securities, Wachovia&#8217;s brokerage unit, which nearly doubled in size in 2003 when it took control of With the addition of A.G. Edwards, Wachovia Securities will have more than 3,300 brokerage locations nationwide, more than $1.1 trillion in client assets and nearly 15,000 financial advisers. The combined retail brokerage business will operate out of St. Louis, Wachovia said, while A.G. Edwards&#8217;s other lines of business, including stock research and investment banking, will be folded into Charlotte, N.C.-based Wachovia&#8217;s current operations. Wachovia Securities was formed in 2003 through a joint venture with Prudential that did not involve any payment by Wachovia. That transaction put the brokerage firm in third place in the United States, behind Merrill and . (Prudential still owns a 38 percent stake in Wachovia Securities.) Thursday&#8217;s deal, which will place Wachovia ahead of Citi in terms of size, involves a significant outlay of cash and stock: It calls for A.G. Edwards&#8217;s shareholders to get 0.9844 Wachovia shares and $35.80 in cash per A.G. Edwards share, valuing their stock at $89.50, a 16 percent premium over Wednesday&#8217;s closing price. The deal is expected to close in the fourth quarter of 2007, Wachovia said. Wachovia, formed through a series of mergers over the years, has been expanding on the banking side as well. Last year, it bought Golden West Financial, one of the last major independent banks on the West Coast, in a $26 billion deal. Daniel J. Ludeman, currently president and chief executive of Wachovia Securities, will keep those roles at the combined brokerage firm. A.G. Edwards&#8217;s chairman and chief executive, Robert Bagby, will be chairman of the enlarged brokerage firm. Go to Article from The Associated Press via The New York Times Â» Go to Press Release from Wachovia Â» 12 comments so far... Great for Chris Gammon Wachovia&#8217;s new partner â€” Posted by Vivian I Gammon Assuming Wachovia got the buyout numbers right, as a shareholder think this is a very smart acquisition. An A.G. Edwards&#8217; office caught my attention when I attended a GOP county meeting the other day in a prosperous very small town Iowa county seat. Aside from a couple of local banks, it&#8217;s the only real financial game in town. â€” Posted by MARK KLEIN, M.D. As an employee of A.G. it leaves me with many questions but as a shareholder I&#8217;m pleased! I kind of take pride in the A.G. Edwards name. I hope that this doesn&#8217;t bring down the reputation the company has built up. â€” Posted by Tina Wachovia has a brilliant long term strategy. Little by little, step by step, year by year, they are setting the stage to becoming a true national bank, instead of just regional (East coast plus Texas and Calif.) They wait for the right time and the right price and they pounce. It may take another 10 years, but this is one well run and smart company. Kudos&#8230; â€” Posted by Ted Koppel Not in agreement here. Looking closely there are only the optics of a strategy that would truly work in the 1980&#8217;s but not going forward. It embraces size but not necessarily change much less agility. Wacovia management tends to say yes to many projects and investments without close, intelligent internal scrutiny. Too much Carolina Pride and not enough questioning and