http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-5&fd=R&url=http://www.northcountrygazette.org/news/2007/05/30/still_more_melamine/&cid=1116822409&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Melamine Contamination Expands To Livestock, Shrimp Feed The North Country Gazette Melamine Contamination Expands To Livestock, Shrimp Feed Posted on Wednesday, 30 of May , 2007 at 6:29 pm First it was pet food which resulted in the biggest pet food recall in history, a recall which is still ongoing. The public was told it was only wet and pouched food, that absolutely no dry pet food was involved. That was wrong.Â  Not only was dry pet food involved but so were dog biscuits and pet treats. Then it was pork, then chickens, then farm-fed fish.Â  But both the U.S. Food and Drug Administration and the U.S. Department of Agriculture tried to tell the public that there was minimal to no risk to the human food supply.Â  For the past two and half months since the recalls first began in mid-March with the nearly 100 brands of dog and cat recalled, the federal government has been busy downplaying the risk as more and more reports of contamination of the food supply for humans, pets, livestock and fish. Thousands of pets were killed and thousands more sickened and incapacitated from kidney failure.Â  Inanely, the contaminated pet food removed from the shelves was used to feed hogs, resulting in tainted pork. Now the FDA is alerting livestock and fish/shrimp feed manufacturers about a voluntary recall of products used in feed production because several have been found to contain melamine and related compounds. The FDA announced Wednesday that a source within the United States has been identified as producing a melamine-contaminated ingredient used in domestic livestock feed as well as in domestic and exported fish feed. This contamination is not considered to be related to the nationwide pet food recall that began March 16, according to the FDA. The feed ingredients were made by Tembec BTLSR Inc. of Toledo, Ohio and Uniscope, Inc. of Johnstown, Colo. Tembec, a contract manufacturer for Uniscope, makes AquaBond and Aqua-Tec II, which it distributes for Uniscope. Uniscope makes Xtra-Bond using ingredients supplied by Tembec. All of the products are binding agents that are used to make pelleted feed for cattle, sheep, and goats, or fish and shrimp. The companies have confirmed that Tembec added melamine as part of the formulation of the products to improve the binding properties of pelleted feed. Melamine is not approved as an additive for animal or fish/shrimp feed. The companies have stopped adding melamine to the feed products. Based on the levels of melamine and related compounds in the initial ingredients, FDA estimated the probable level of melamine and related compounds in livestock feed as less than 50 parts per million (ppm) based on the recommended mix rate of two to four pounds of binding agent per ton of livestock feed. The estimated levels in fish and shrimp feed are less than 233 ppm and 465 ppm, respectively, of melamine and related compounds. The estimated levels of melamine and related compounds vary in the livestock feed and the fish and shrimp feed because of differing levels of melamine in the binding agents used for each type of feed. FDA advises feed manufacturers and others who mix their own feed not to use these products, and to contact the manufacturers. FDA advises feed manufacturers to recall finished feed that is made from AquaBond or Aqua-Tec II due to the estimated levels of melamine and related compounds in the finished products. FDA believes that no recall is warranted of the finished feed made from Xtra-Bond based on the estimated levels of melamine and related compounds in the finished product and based on currently available data and information. The estimated melamine levels in feed made with these binding agents are similar to the levels discussed in the interim safety/risk assessment of melamine and related compounds made available by FDA earlier this month, says the FDA. Â In that assessment, federal â€œscientistsâ€ determined that, based on currently available data and information, the consumption of pork, chicken, domestic fish, and eggs from animals inadvertently fed animal feed contaminated with melamine and its analogues was unlikely to pose a human health risk, according to the FDA. FDA is encouraging domestic feed suppliers to be vigilant in quality control in their supply chain and to monitor for any improper additives, including melamine and its analogs. The Tembec and Uniscope products also reportedly contain a urea formaldehyde resin-type ingredient, a raw ingredient used to make the binding agent in these products. FDA is investigating this use of the urea formaldehyde resin-type ingredient in the Tembec and Uniscope products, and will take appropriate regulatory action if warranted. Earlier this month, Cereal Byproducts Company of Mt. Prospect announced that the FDA had determined that there are melamine and/or melamine derivatives in the rice protein concentrate produced by a single source Chinese supplier, Binzhou Futian Biology Technology Co. Lt. and purchased through a â€œlocalâ€ domestic importer.Â  FDA later said that it was wheat flour, not rice protein or wheat gluten which was the contaminated ingredient. The Xuzhou Anying Biologic Technology Development Co. Ltd., has also been identified as having exported the contaminated wheat flour containing melamine to the U.S. The managers of both of the Chinese companies which have been linked to the contaminated pet food which has killed and sickened thousands of cats and dogs in the U.S. and Canada, have been arrested. The head of Chinaâ€™s drug administration was sentenced to death Tuesday for accepting bribes to approve adulterated medicines including antibiotics which resulted in the deaths of six individuals and sickened scores more. The conviction and death sentenceÂ  for Zheng Ziaoyu, 63, former chief of the state Food and Drug Administration of China followed the international scandal about the tainted exports from the Chinese firms related to the pet food contamination and toothpaste with a potentially poisonous chemical addictive which was sold in Latin America. The Chinese companies had issued a statement that said that they had added melamine to the wheat gluten and rice protein in order to meet the contractual demand for protein levels.Â  Melamine is not approved as a food additive.Â  The companies said they only broke the law when they intentionally mislabeled the exported items to avoid inspection. Melamine is a molecule that has a number of commercial and industrial uses.Â  Other than a few limited authorizations for use in food contact materials for human food, melamine has no approved use as an ingredient in human or animal food in the U.S.Â  According to the Chinese government, Xuzhou Anying did not declare the contaminated wheat gluten (wheat flour) it shipped to the U.S. as a raw material for feed or food.Â  Rather, according to the Chinese government, it was declared to them as a non-food product, meaning that it was not subject to mandatory inspection by the Chinese government. Cereal Byproducts said it shipped the recalled product to a total of three customers located in the Midwest between July 19, 2006 and March 14, 2007. The FDA previously found melamine and/or melamine derivatives in Wilbur-Ellis Companyâ€™s rice protein concentrate, which was purchased from the same Chinese supplier as Cereal Byproducts. Cereal Byproducts proactively notified their customers of this finding, and thereafter both parties implemented their own voluntary recall of the contaminated products on or about April 19. Although Cereal Byproducts says it had received no confirmed cases of pet deaths, company officials said the voluntarily chose to initiate the recall when Cereal Byproducts discovered there was a potential contamination of melamine or melamine type derivatives. Cereal Byproducts had supplied rice protein concentrate to Royan Canin USA which on Friday announced its second recall, this time calling back right Sensible Choice dry food products and seven Kasco dry dog and cat food products. Â Royal Canin said it had found trace amounts of melamine in its products. FDA continues to assert that t he risk to human health is very low from eating meat from hogs and chickens that have been fed animal feed supplemented with pet food scraps containing melamine and related compounds, according to a risk assessment conducted by federal scientists. They say this conclusion supports the decision announced on April 28, not to recall meat from animals that were fed contaminated product. The FDA claimed that the pet food scraps fed to hogs and chickens made up only a small percentage of the farm animal rations. In addition, melamine is known to be excreted in animal urine, and believed not to accumulate in the body of animals. When exposure levels are much higher, as was the case with cats and dogs, the melamine and its compounds appear to cause the formation of crystals in the kidney systems, resulting in kidney damage. There was no indication of kidney damage in hogs. Both hogs and chickens known to have been fed contaminated feed appear to be healthy. For more information on the recalls and food contamination, see Add this post to COPYRIGHT 2007 - NORTH COUNTRY GAZETTE All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed without the express written permission of the publisher. Letters to the Editor Help Keep The North Country Gazette On The Web! Click Here To See How YOU Can Help!
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-4&fd=R&url=http://news.independent.co.uk/world/americas/article2600241.ece&cid=1116567986&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Black may escape witness box after 'weak' prosecution rests - Independent Online Edition > Americas Business Analysis & Features A-Z Unis & Colleges from The Independent & The Independent on Sunday Black may escape witness box after 'weak' prosecution rests Published: 31 May 2007 Lord Black of Crossharbour, the former owner of the Daily Telegraph who has been put on trial for fraud, won one-14th of the courtroom victory he has been loudly predicting, as prosecutors dropped a money laundering charge against him. The US government withdrew one of the 14 charges without explanation, as it wrapped up 11 weeks of evidence against the fallen media baron and three of his associates. Lord Black's lawyers have indicated that they will call only a few witnesses and could take barely a week to set out their defence, suggesting that they do not plan to risk putting the famously pompous peer on the stand. That in turn suggests they are confident that the prosecution has failed to build the cast-iron case that would require such a desperate last roll of the dice. Observers said that the prosecution has failed to present evidence that would allow the technical charge of money laundering to stick. Lord Black still faces 13 counts of fraud, racketeering and obstruction of justice, which could put him in jail for the rest of his life. The prosecution yesterday called their final witnesses after painting Lord Black as a fraudster who treated his US-quoted newspaper company, Hollinger International, as a personal piggy bank, to the detriment of outside shareholders. As well as living high on on company expenses, the peer cooked up a string of bogus "non-compete" agreements that allowed him and his associates to pocket $60m in illegal payments, the prosecution claimed. Hollinger's independent board members &shy; including the former governor of Illinois, Jim Thompson and the Canadian economist Marie-Josee Kravis &shy; testified that they did not know that such large sums were being diverted to Lord Black and the three other defendants, Jack Boultbee, Mark Kipnis and Peter Atkinson. And David Radler, Lord Black's right-hand man for more than three decades, said that he and Lord Black had dreamed up the idea of using non-compete payments as a way of sheltering bonuses from tax and to pay off debts at their other companies. Testifying as part of a plea deal that gives him a lenient 29-month term in a Canadian jail, Mr Radler was attacked by defence attorneys as a liar out to save his own skin. While Mr Radler repeatedly insisted that he had initially denied wrongdoing in order to protect Lord Black, Edward Greenspan, Lord Black's lawyer, forced him to admit that he had double-crossed Lord Black in other business dealings. Steven Skurka, a veteran defence attorney who has been observing the trial as a commentator for Canadian television, repeated his assertion that Lord Black will be acquitted, citing the defence team's performance in cross-examining the main witnesses, in particular their success in getting Mr Thompson to admit that he had only "skimmed" important documents. "Conrad Black is the uncontrollable waterfall. The prosecution's job is to do enough to force him to testify. I don't think that they have done enough, and as I result I think they will ultimately lose the case," Mr Skurka said. However, that is by no means a universal view among representatives of the dozens of media organisations from the US, the UK and Canada that have descended on Chicago to cover the trial. Others believe that the prosecution's vivid evidence of Lord Black's lavish personal spending on expenses will prove more persuasive to the blue-collar, mainly female jury than the non-compete deal paperwork. Eddie Genson, Lord Black's Chicago-based attorney, has repeatedly asked the judge to declare a mistrial because of what he says is the prosecution's pandering to "class prejudice". The peer has vowed to sue all his accusers "when" he is acquitted. He has loudly defended himself outside the court, in a round of media interviews to publicise his new biography of Richard Nixon, during which he has insisted that the prosecution case against him is a tissue of lies. The judge, Amy St Eve, was so incensed at Lord Black's public statements that she told the defence team to "restrain" him, or she would do it for them. Lord Black and his associates cooked up a scheme to pay themselves $5.5m by promising not to set up a newspaper in the tiny mountain town of Mammoth in California - a promise they had no difficulty in keeping, since they already owned the only paper there. Prosecutors brandished a copy of the Mammoth Times to illustrate that the non-compete clauses signed by Lord Black were sham agreements meant only to disguise massive bonus payments. Jurors were shown the sumptuous menu for the surprise 60th birthday party thrown by Lord Black for his wife at the lavish New York restaurant La Grenouille in December 2000. The $62,870 bill, it was revealed, included a $14,847 drinks tab. Beluga caviar was among the starters. Hollinger picked up two-thirds of the tab. The Park Avenue apartment Lord Black ordered a $2.1m refurbishment for his New York apartment, spending $5,300 on heated towel rails, $6,000 on shower doors and $7,000 on window sashes - and then made up for the expense by buying the apartment from Hollinger at $3m below the market price. Hollinger also paid for a servants' quarters. Hollinger's company jet was routinely used by Lord Black and his wife for personal trips. Prosecutors have charged him with defrauding outside shareholders by paying only half the $565,326 cost of a round-trip flight to the South Pacific idyll of Bora Bora. The jury was shown grainy CCTV footage of Lord Black, his personal assistant and chauffeur loading 13 boxes of documents into his limousine on the same day that prosecutors say he was told to hand over documents to US regulators. Also in this section Goldman Sachs marches on with Bush's candidate for World Bank Drugs giant faces criminal charges over clinical trial 'Orphaned' boy spells out plight of parents Bush to nominate Zoellick as World Bank president Cindy Sheehan quits as 'face' of anti-war campaign The true cost of putting imported food on your plate My war on electrosmog Julia Stephenson sets out to clear the airwaves The actress breaking hearts in Pinter's Betrayal How to protect children from the dangers of internet Put your questions to the Lib Dem leader The 1971 Martini Girl A life in the fast lane Introducing the IoS blogs Day in a page Find articles published on: Sign up for our free daily news update Independent News & Media &copy; 2007 Independent News and Media Limited
