http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-0&fd=R&url=http://business.guardian.co.uk/story/0,,2092148,00.html&cid=1116567986&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Conrad Black prosecutors drop a charge | | Guardian Unlimited Business Skip to main content Comment is free blog arts & entertainment blog Black prosecutors drop a charge Thursday May 31, 2007 Conrad Black is to face one less charge after prosecutors dropped one count of money-laundering against him minutes before resting their racketeering case against the former Daily Telegraph owner yesterday. Lawyers for Lord Black, who still faces more than a dozen charges relating to racketeering, obstruction of justice, mail, wire and tax fraud, said they would take just over two days to rebut 11 weeks of prosecution evidence. The apparent brevity of the defence case indicates that Lord Black himself will probably not be called to testify. This suggests that Lord Black's defence team is either confident that the prosecution's case is not strong enough, or, that it may be too risky to subject the former Telegraph owner to cross-examination over the $60m case. Lord Black's lawyers intend to put their case early next week. The prosecution's case ended with lawyers showing bank statements indicating Lord Black had spent millions on diamonds and jewellery for his wife. Earlier this week, the prosecution case levelled a number of other accusations against Lord Black. Lawyers argued obstruction of justice relating to CCTV footage of 13 boxes Lord Black allegedly removed from the company's headquarters in defiance of a court order. Further accusations centred on a Park Avenue flat bought by Hollinger International for Lord Black in 1994, which the prosecution argued was worth millions more than the amount he subsequently paid to buy it six years later. Lord Black said he spent several million dollars renovating the apartment. Lord Black and three other former executives of Hollinger International are charged with swindling the newspaper holding company out of millions of dollars through the sale of Hollinger assets. The alleged scheme began with a decision in the late-90s by Lord Black, who was the company's chairman, to sell hundreds of small Hollinger-owned community newspapers across the US and Canada. Millions of dollars were paid to Hollinger in exchange for promises that it would not go into competition with the new owners of the papers. Prosecutors have claimed Lord Black and two of his co-defendants, former Hollinger vice-presidents John Boultbee and Peter Y Atkinson, illegally diverted much of the money to themselves with help from corporate counsel Mark Kipnis. Mr Kipnis also is on trial. All four of the defendants maintain that they did nothing illegal. To contact the MediaGuardian newsdesk email or phone 020 7239 9857. For all other inquiries please call the main Guardian switchboard on 020 7278 2332. If you are writing a comment for publication, please mark clearly "for publication". Black emails dismissed fears over excesses as hysteria Black's lawyers criticise his successor Black trial told secret bonuses were 'mistake' 'Burglars use crowbars, robbers guns. He used memos and lies' Black's lawyers claim deal may prejudice trial Conrad Black's wife in outburst Conrad Black trial hits hitch Black breakfasts at the Ritz before facing his prosecutors Lord Black rebuffs journalists' questions Conrad Black's lawyer gets on wrong side of judge Conrad Black trial begins Black's successor to kick off prosecution Trump tipped to star as Conrad Black defence witness Conrad Black defiant as trial looms Send it to a friend Join our dating site today Guardian Unlimited &copy; Guardian News and Media Limited 2007
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-2&fd=R&url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-070531sears,0,2764969.story%3Fcoll%3Dchi-business-hed&cid=1116794261&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Sears' net income climbs | Chicago Tribune A $100 million mystery Red wolf pups unveiled at Lincoln Park Zoo Billboard called racy, wrong A most hollow oratory on Memorial Day 2nd builder eyes Evanston sky Sears' net income climbs By James P. Miller Published May 31, 2007, 8:02 AM CDT Sears Holdings Corp.'s fiscal first-quarter net income showed a solid increase -- thanks to a number of one-time gains -- but the retail giant's underlying profits were flat, the company said today. "In part, our domestic operating results reflect the impact of some of the same challenges being faced by our customers, such as rising energy costs and a slowing housing market," said President and Chief Executive Officer Aylwin Lewis. For the quarter ended May 5, net income at the Hoffman Estates company was $216 million, or $1.40 a diluted share, up from the year-ago period's $180 million, or $1.14 a share. Sears' revenues slipped slightly to $11.70 billion from $12.0 billion. But excluding the impact of onetime special items, Sears pointed out, per-share earnings dipped to $1.10 from $1.11 a year ago. In the latest quarter, the company enjoyed a 12-cent-a-share gain from a legal settlement; an 11-cent-a-share gain from curtailment of certain post-retirement benefits for workers at its Sears Canada affiliate; and an aggregate 14-cent gain related to a dividend from Sears Mexico and hurricane-related recoveries. Partially offsetting those gains was an 8-cent-a-share loss on certain financial "swap" investments that Sears chairman and controlling stockholder Eddie Lampert routinely makes using the company's cash flow. Those investments have often yielded big gains for Sears, but in the latest quarter they served as a drag on profits. On an operating basis, Sears noted that profits declined at its Kmart unit, with sales weakening "most notably" in home goods, health and beauty products, and food. At the company's Sears outlets, sales at stores open at least twelve months showed a decline -- in part because of weaker home appliance sales, which the company said "reflects both a slower U.S. housing market and the impact of increased competition." Chicago Bears Super Bowl coverage Wonders of the world 10 for the road Send a news tip What's in it for you? The day's top stories e-mailed to you each weekday. Exclusive access to Tribune experts for help with homework or research A free archive search of a year's worth of Chicago Tribune stories. Advice for making the most of a special night out. This month's featured offers include: Subscriber Advantage members can enjoy special offers such as save $30 off a pair of Camelot tickets with Michael York receive FREE Child Admission to the Nature Museum and , courtesy of Chicago Tribune Subscriber Advantage.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-3&fd=R&url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/31/technology/31yahoo.html&cid=1116823914&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Yahoo Technology Chief to Leave in Wake of Company Revamping - New York Times Yahoo Technology Chief to Leave in Wake of Company Revamping Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 31, 2007 SAN FRANCISCO, May 30 — Farzad Nazem, ’s chief technology officer and one of its longest-serving executives, said he would leave on June 8 after 11 years at the company. Yahoo said its co-founder, Jerry Yang, would assume Mr. Nazem’s responsibilities while it searches for a replacement. The departure of Mr. Nazem, 45, who is known as Zod, will follow a turbulent year at Yahoo that included a companywide revamping. Several other senior executives, including the chief operating officer, have left in the wake of the overhaul. Yahoo would not make Mr. Nazem or any other executive available to discuss his departure. But a spokeswoman, Joanna Stevens, said that Mr. Nazem had wanted to retire and that he and the chief executive, Terry S. Semel, had been planning his departure for some time. Writing in the company’s , Mr. Nazem said, “As I began contemplating retirement, there were a few milestones that I (along with the executive leadership team) wanted to accomplish prior to my departure.” Those milestones, he wrote, included the reorganization of the company and its technology group, as well as the introduction of an advertising platform, known as Project Panama, which Yahoo began introducing in February. “It was very important to me,” Mr. Nazem said, “to drive all the way to my last day here at Yahoo without distractions of an announcement like this.” The new advertising platform is aimed at narrowing the lead of in online advertising, but it has yet to translate into financial gains for the company. Mr. Nazem, who is responsible for the operation of the Yahoo Web site and for product development, was popular among the company’s technology ranks, whom he largely helped hire. This month, Yahoo appointed Blake Jorgensen, a founder of Thomas Weisel Partners, as chief financial officer, replacing Susan L. Decker, who is switching roles to become head of the company’s advertiser and publisher group. Yahoo is looking for an executive to lead its audience group, which is responsible for much of the main company Web site. After Mr. Nazem’s departure, Yahoo is likely to have vacant positions at the top of two of its three operating units. As part of his separation agreement, Mr. Nazem will receive a lump sum equal to his base salary for the rest of the year as well as accelerated vesting of stock options and stock awards, a package that an executive compensation firm, Equilar, estimated around $6.9 million. Sphere: Related Blogs & Articles Next Article in Technology (10 of 22) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Yahoo, Aiming for Agility, Shuffles Executives Suspensions, Dismissals and Resignations Next Article in Technology (10 of 22) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France Bomb Scare - 1956 Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art & Design &#x00bb; Sarkozys: The French Kennedys? Phil Spector’s Long and Winding Road The Dirty Water Underground An Animated Film by Jeff Scher Artist Sets Up House(s) at the Grand Palais The New York Times Company
