trategy to expand beyond its marketplace roots. An eBay user can already rate another buyer or seller, or see their past purchases, but StumbleUpon could theoretically help eBay users also see buyersâ€™ favorite web sites, view their pictures and add other eBay users to oneâ€™s StumbleUpon â€œfriends.â€ This builds more page views and traction at eBay and makes it more of a regular destinationâ€”or perhaps even a social networking siteâ€”rather than just a place to buy stuff. And eBay could also recommend products based on oneâ€™s friends. $280M acquisition follows moves on Wallstrip.com, Joost, Spot Runner. BuzzLogic and Visible Technologies competitor gets seed round. Sweden Opens Second Life Embassy Apple TV to Feature YouTube EveryScape Launches 3-D Search Could not find the linkURL in the DB: /Article.aspx?a=22447&hed=eBay+Makes+Social+Networking+Play&sector=Industries&subsector=InternetAndServices. Letter from the Editor &copy; 1993-2006 Red Herring, Inc. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.canada.com/topics/news/world/story.html%3Fid%3D8a4a0a15-58d1-4305-b0af-e499ca8c83f3%26k%3D10768&cid=1116434825&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Spain stakes claim to colonial-era treasure ship found by Florida company Jump to: canada.com, Newspapers, TV, Radio A Shopper's Secret Diary A Shopper's Secret Diary What's Hot and What's Not What's Hot and What's Not Ask a Shopping Question Ask a Shopping Question Unsure of how to feature? Click me to Spain stakes claim to colonial-era treasure ship found by Florida company In this photo provided by Odyssey Marine Exploration, Ground crew members unload more than 17 tons of silver coins May 16 at an undisclosed location.. (AP Photo/Odyssey Marine Exploration, Jonathan Blair) Phil Davis, Canadian Press Published: Thursday, May 31, 2007 TAMPA, Fla. (AP) - The Spanish government has filed claims in U.S. federal court over a shipwreck that a Florida company found laden with colonial-era treasure, a lawyer said Thursday. If the vessel was Spanish or was removed from that country's waters, any treasure would belong to Spain, said James Goold, a lawyer representing the Madrid government. "It's a very well established principle under Spanish, U.S. and international law that a government such as the kingdom of Spain has not abandoned its sunken ships or sunken property, and that a company like Odyssey Marine Exploration may not conduct recovery operations without authorization by the government," he said. "The kingdom of Spain has not authorized any such operations by Odyssey, and by these legal actions it will see the return of any Spanish property Odyssey has recovered," Goold said of the claims filed Wednesday. Odyssey officials were not available for comment. Odyssey announced two weeks ago that it had discovered a shipwreck containing 500,000 gold and silver coins somewhere in the Atlantic Ocean. At the time, Odyssey estimated the value of the find at some US$500 million. Rare-coin expert Nick Bruyer, who was contracted by Tampa-based Odyssey Marine Exploration to examine a batch of coins from the wreck, has described the find as "unprecedented." "I don't know of anything equal or comparable to it," he said in an interview earlier this month. The Tampa-based company said the site was outside any country's territorial waters but would not give the exact location or name of the ship. Odyssey has said that the ship was not in Spanish territorial waters and was not the HMS Sussex, a shipwreck that Odyssey recently got permission from the Spanish government to search for in the Strait of Gibraltar. But Spain has called the new discovery suspicious and said the booty may have come from a wrecked Spanish galleon. In Britain, the find generated press reports that Odyssey had salvaged the wreck of the long-sought British vessel Merchant Royal, which sank in bad weather off England in 1641. Odyssey has not confirmed or denied these reports. Spain is using the U.S. law firm Covington & Burling, which has represented Spain over shipwreck cases before, including the recovery of material from two ships, Juno and La Galga, in a 2000 court case. The Spanish government won that case. Previously the richest-ever shipwreck haul was from the Spanish galleon Nuestra Senora de Atocha, which sank in a hurricane off the Florida Keys in 1622. Treasure-hunting pioneer Mel Fisher found it in 1985, retrieving a reported $400 million in coins and other loot. Canadian killed in Afghanistan A Canadian soldier died Wednesday night when the American helicopter he was aboard... Ipperwash inquiry faults approach of police, Ont., Ottawa Shoddy police planning, the impatience of provincial politicians and the federal... More Top News Stories Organ-harvesting claims spark call for Olympic boycott No warning TB-infected man headed to Montreal: officials U.S. holds hard line on Iran nuclear program: Rice Taiwan space head in corruption probe Parents of soldier 'offended' by O'Connor's assertion A health alert has been issued for passengers who ... More Top News Videos Sam's shuts itâ€™s doors Five-year old flies plane Lohan hooked on painkiller, dad says Lindsay Lohan's estranged father says she suffers from multiple addictions, including alcohol and the... PLUS! All new POP!arazzi The MMVAs are coming! Jodie Foster gets cheeky Duke Ellington comes back to Canada Mercedes Ellington can't wait to visit Stratford, Ontario. PLUS! Brad Pitt in Montreal Look who's coming to the MMVAs! Visit Shopping on canada.com We've got the inside scoop on everything Shopping-related! Get in-the-know today! Read our Shopping Advice column Whatâ€™s Hot & Whatâ€™s Not? Shop Online for Great Stuff! Ask our experts a Shopping question! John Mayer acts out a bizarre ... Privacy czar warns web users to be wary Students cruising online networking... Deaths may be linked to diabetes drug Health Canada says the deaths ... Fox Sports World Canada Copyright & Permission Rules &copy; 2007 CanWest Interactive, a division of CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. . All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republication strictly prohibited.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-6&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601103%26sid%3DaEZikLRS.ysw%26refer%3Dus&cid=1116794261&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ , May 31 12:16 , May 31 17:16 , Jun 01 01:16 Australia & New Zealand Sears Profit Rises 20% on Insurance, Settlement Gains (Update2) By Lauren Coleman-Lochner and Heather Burke May 31 (Bloomberg) -- Sears Holdings Corp., the largest U.S. department-store chain, said first-quarter profit rose 20 percent because of insurance payments and a legal settlement. Sales at Kmart and Sears stores open at least a year fell 3.9 percent as shoppers curbed purchases of home appliances and health products. Revenue declined 2.5 percent to $11.7 billion, Sears said today in a statement. Comparable-store sales have fallen every quarter since Chairman Edward Lampert joined Sears with Kmart in March 2005 in a $12.3 billion union. Lampert, 44, said earlier this month that fixing retail operations was ``a priority&#39;&#39; for the company. ``They have to take a page out of J.C. Penney&#39;s playbook and revitalize the brands and improve sales,&#39;&#39; said Arun Daniel, who helps manage $40 billion, including Sears shares, at ING Investments LLC in New York. ``That takes time.&#39;&#39; Net income climbed to $216 million, or $1.40 a share, from $180 million, or $1.14, a year earlier. One-time items lifted profit by $44 million, or 30 cents a share, in the three months through May 5. Excluding the gains and charges, the company said it earned $1.10 a share, trailing analysts&#39; estimates of $1.21 a share, the average of seven projections compiled by Bloomberg. Shares of Sears, based in Hoffman Estates, Illinois, fell $4.35, or 2.4 percent, to $178.90 at 9:39 a.m. New York time in Nasdaq Stock Market composite trading. They have gained 6.5 percent this year. Same-store sales fell 3.4 percent at the Sears division on sluggish demand for home appliances, which the company attributed to a U.S. housing slump and higher energy prices. Kmart&#39;s same-store sales declined 4.4 percent on lower sales in home goods, health care and most other merchandise categories. Kmart shoppers may have reduced purchases because of higher gasoline prices and poor weather, the company said. Sears earned $18 million after-tax from the legal settlement of a contractual dispute, $16 million from amendments to Sears Canada&#39;s post-retirement benefit plans, a $12 million dividend from an investment in Mexico and $9 million in insurance money from stores damaged by 2005 hurricanes. Sears lost $13 million, or 8 cents, on investments in total-return swaps, agreements in which one investor makes payments based on any coupons and capital gains or losses of an asset and the other makes fixed or floating-rate payments. Sears sells exclusive brands including Kenmore home appliances and Craftsman tools. Earlier this month, the company began a new advertising campaign with the slogan, ``Sears, where it begins.&#39;&#39; At Kmart, it introduced Mr. Bluelight, an animated character who will highlight bargains and unique items for sale. Kmart was known for ``Blue Light Special&#39;&#39; sales in the 1970s and &#39;80s. Lampert said at the company&#39;s shareholder meeting earlier this month that Sears may add more exclusive brands, he said, a strategy that has helped J.C. Penney and Kohl&#39;s Corp. prosper. Gregory Melich, an analyst at Morgan Stanley in Purchase, N.Y., had forecast profit of $1.15 a share on sales of $11.8 billion. There&#39;s a ``newfound willingness on Chairman Eddie Lampert&#39;s part to spend money to improve the business,&#39;&#39; Melich wrote in a May 8 report. The company will need to invest more in stores and operations, he wrote. To contact the reporter on this story: Lauren Coleman-Lochner in New York at ; Heather Burke in New York at Last Updated: May 31, 2007 09:42 EDT Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division Economy Expands at a 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Home Prices in U.S. Climbed at Slowest Pace in Decade During First Quarter
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-2&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/us-gdp-revised-lower-06/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257B31B26C89-4FDB-4AFF-BB72-F5A8A0FA5FAB%257D&cid=1116840694&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Corporate profits growing at slowest pace in five years Last Update: 9:43 AM ET May 31, 2007 WASHINGTON (MarketWatch) -- The U.S. economy slowed to a crawl in the first quarter, held back by falling investments in homes, shrinking inventories and a large trade gap, the Commerce Department reported Thursday. The economy grew at a 0.6% annualized pace in the quarter, revised down from the initial estimate of 1.3%, the government said in its second estimate of quarterly gross domestic product. It was the slowest growth since late 2002. Read the full government report. Economists surveyed by MarketWatch were expecting GDP to be revised to 0.7%. The economy has grown just 1.9% in the past four quarters, well below the 3% growth most economists say is the long-run potential. It's the weakest year-over-year growth in four years. Consumers continued to lead the way in the first quarter with strong gains in spending and income, which were revised even higher than in the first estimate. The business sector, however, invested little and saw year-over-year before-tax profit growth fall to the lowest level of the five-year-old expansion. "The details of the report suggest some reasons for even more optimism for the second quarter," wrote Drew Matus, an economist for Lehman Bros. The faster businesses cut their inventories, the sooner they'll be ready to ramp up production again. Considering the large upward revision to consumer spending, the report "will widely be viewed as a positive when the details are scoured," wrote Tony Crescenzi, chief bond market strategist for Miller Tabak & Co. Although the drags from inventories and home building will lessen in coming quarters, consumer spending is weakening, he said. "The composition of GDP will turn unfavorable in the second quarter, putting into question the sustainability of a rebound in GDP," Crescenzi said. Data on consumer spending will be the main variable to watch. The revisions do little to change the broad picture of an American economy bolstered by the steady consumer, but weakened by a sickly housing market and a cautious business sector. In nominal terms (not adjusted for inflation), the economy grew 4.7% to $13.6 trillion annualized. Fed officials seem to be looking past the grim first-quarter growth data to a rebound later this year. In the minutes of the May 9 meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee released on Wednesday, Fed officials unanimously voiced the view that inflation, not recession, remains the greater risk. Economy-wide inflation surged at the fastest pace in 16 years, and core consumer inflation accelerated a bit above the Federal Reserve's comfort zone. The GDP price index increased 4% annualized, the most since 1991. The core personal consumption price index increased at a 2.2% annual rate and is up 2.2% in the past year, above the 1% to 2% target zone for the Fed. The chances of any change this year in the Fed's interest rate target have evaporated in recent months. Recent signs point to reinvigorated capital spending. However, hopes for a quick rebound in housing have been dashed by further declines in key indicators. And consumer spending has started the second quarter on a weak note. In a separate report, the Labor Department said initial claims for unemployment benefits fell 4,000 last week to 310,000, a sign that layoffs remain relatively rare. The government will report on May nonfarm payrolls on Friday, with economists expecting a gain of 150,000. Real consumer spending increased 4.4% annualized, the fastest in a year, compared with the 3.8% initial estimate. Spending on durable goods increased 8.8%, spending on nondurable goods rose 3.5% and spending on services increased 4%. With the 4.2% gain in the fourth quarter, it was the best back-to-back performance for consumer spending in four years, noted David Greenlaw, an economist for Morgan Stanley. Consumer spending contributed 3 percentage points to growth. Real disposable personal incomes increased at a 4.7% annual rate in the first quarter, boosted by a $50 billion disbursement of annual bonuses. Fourth-quarter income was revised higher by $33 billion from wages and salaries. Investments in houses dropped at a 15.4% annual pace, revised from 17% earlier. It's the sixth consecutive decline. Residential investments cut 1 percentage point from growth. Business fixed investments increased at a 2.9% annual pace, revised up from 2% earlier. Investments in equipment and software rose 2%, while investments in structures increased 5.1%. Business investments contributed 0.3 percentage points to growth. Inventories shrank by $4.5 billion. The change in inventory investment cut 1 percentage point from growth. Corporate profits before tax increased $20.3 billion, or 1.2%, to $1.67 trillion after falling $4.9 billion in the fourth quarter. Before-tax profits are up 6.3% in the past year, the weakest year-over-year growth since the fourth quarter of 2001. After-tax profits rose 1% in the first quarter and are up 6.4% in the past year. Nonfinancial corporate profits rose $16.2 billion, while financial corporate profits rose $4.8 billion. Exports fell 0.6%, the biggest decline in four years. Meanwhile, imports rose 5.7%. The trade deficit cut 1 percentage point from growth. Government spending rose 1% in the first quarter. Federal spending fell 3.9%, including a 7.3% drop in national defense spending. State and local government spending rose 3.9%. Government spending contributed 0.2 percentage points to growth. Rex Nutting is Washington bureau chief of MarketWatch. Related Blog Posts & Articles U.S. April construction spending rises 0.1% Home prices rise at slowest pace in 10 years Jobless claims fall back slightly in latest week Chicago Purchasing Managers Index improves in May 97,000 jobs added in May, ADP says Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion Jobs wants to use iPhone to put the 'baby Internet' to bed U.S. futures up after Wachovia deal, Yahoo upgrade Want to beat the market? Take the inside path U.S. stocks rise amid deal news Thursday's biggest stock gainers and decliners U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Stocks in focus for Thursday Dell seen posting 22% drop in profit as it fights H-P threat Rouleau still seeing a 'mini-bull' market to be avoided Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion Jobs wants to use iPhone to put the 'baby Internet' to bed Big drug wholesalers may get bigger, with FDA help Want to beat the market? Take the inside path Three specialty REITs to buy on a pullback U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Growing share of 'Big Three' drug wholesalers gets attention U.S. mortgage rates edge higher for third straight week Five ways unmarried partners can safeguard their finances Bristol-Myers pleads guilty in federal Plavix case U.S. stocks rise amid deal news Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion U.S. mortgage rates edge higher for third straight week U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Dell seen posting 22% drop in profit as it fights H-P threat Get the Latest MarketWatch News >> Dow Jones Licensing Services Dow Jones Online Network: Copyright &copy; 2007 MarketWatch, Inc. All rights reserved. By using this site, you agree to the U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter - MarketWatch Intraday data provided by , a division of Interactive Data Corp. and subject to . Historical and current end-of-day data provided by . More information on and their current financial status. Intraday data delayed 15 minutes for Nasdaq, and 20 minutes for other exchanges. Dow Jones IndexesSM from Dow Jones & Company, Inc. SEHK