http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-5&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/northwest-taxis-out-chapter-11/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257BAD063E49-000A-4504-BC65-D97C9E5B9F68%257D&cid=1116733522&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Northwest taxis out of Chapter 11; shares gain in debut - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Last of legacy U.S. airlines out of bankruptcy Northwest debuts on NYSE; no carriers in Chapter 11 for first time since 2002 Last Update: 12:15 PM ET May 31, 2007 NEW YORK (MarketWatch) -- Thursday marks a notable moment in the recent history of U.S. airlines: For the first time in nearly five years, there will be no major carrier slugging it out with creditors in bankruptcy court. Northwest Airlines Corp. exited bankruptcy on Thursday with creditors agreeing on a reorganization plan and the airline's flight attendants voting to accept a new labor agreement -- albeit barely, by just about 100 votes. The Eagan, Minn.-based carrier's new shares debuted Thursday, under the symbol NWA , and notched early gains of about 2% in New York Stock Exchange trading. The company's previous stock was delisted from Nasdaq in September 2005 after the carrier entered bankruptcy. The optimism that accompanied many of carriers' journeys through bankruptcy -- predicated on the shedding of debt and costly airplane leases and the freezing or jettisoning of pension obligations -- has helped the industry prepare better, though not fully, for the realities of mid-2007. Stubbornly high jet fuel prices, softening demand for travel and an excess of seats have hindered airline profit in recent quarters, renewing calls for mergers that would substantially trim available seat miles and associated costs. The new Northwest shares carried an initial price of $27 each, but like Delta shares earlier this year and United Airlines parent UAL Corp.'s post-Chapter 11 shares in early 2006, that price tag was too high. The trading marks the final return to solid footing for the last of the so-called legacy carriers that, starting with U.S. Airways in August 2002, began a long slide into bankruptcy. The trading marks the final return to solid footing for the last of the so-called legacy carriers that, starting with U.S. Airways in August 2002, began a long slide into bankruptcy. The airline's chief executive, Doug Steenland, said Northwest emerged from its 20 months in bankruptcy with more than $3 billion in cash and was looking forward to a "very strong" summer travel season. "It's a great day for the airline business," he said. Listen to the full interview. Northwest entered Chapter 11 in September 2005, as did rival Delta Air Lines Inc. the same day. Delta emerged earlier this year, and like Northwest, has shed labor costs and airplane leasing agreements. Northwest was able to reduce its costs by about $2.2 billion, including $1.4 billion in labor and pension expenses, and to shrink its aircraft fleet and reduce seating capacity by about 10%. "Northwest did not face as many problems to fix as did Delta upon entering bankruptcy because Northwest's non-labor costs were in fairly good shape, and their revenue generation was broadly comparable to their legacy airline peers," said Standard & Poor's airline analyst Philip Baggaley. But the carrier, despite its fresh-start accounting, is forecasting weak second-quarter demand, as the industry grapples with an oversupply of passenger seats and a softening U.S. economy. International route revenue remains strong, according to Northwest, which is the No. 1 U.S. carrier to Japan. Northwest in early April offered 27.8 million new shares as part of its exit from bankruptcy, with J.P. Morgan Securities acting as underwriter. General unsecured claimants received new stock worth between 66% and 83% of their allowed claims, the airline said in its federal filing. Delta's recently issued shares have slipped about 7% in their first month of trading -- a period during which the Amex Airline Index ( ) , composed of 11 airline stocks, gained about 6%. Delta's shares aren't part of the Amex benchmark. "For the first since 2002 there are no major airlines in bankruptcy. It seems weird," said Baggaley. "The industry situation has certainly improved -- there's a better balance of supply and demand. But fuel prices are higher now than they were at the start of that period, and the big airlines still are carrying a lot of debt and other financial obligations." Padraic Cassidy is a reporter for MarketWatch in New York. Related Blog Posts & Articles Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion U.S. stocks rise amid deal news U.S. mortgage rates edge higher for third straight week U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Dell seen posting 22% drop in profit as it fights H-P threat Sign up to receive the Weekend TV Show Preview Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion Jobs wants to use iPhone to put the 'baby Internet' to bed U.S. futures up after Wachovia deal, Yahoo upgrade Want to beat the market? Take the inside path U.S. stocks rise amid deal news Thursday's biggest stock gainers and decliners U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Stocks in focus for Thursday Dell seen posting 22% drop in profit as it fights H-P threat Rouleau still seeing a 'mini-bull' market to be avoided Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion Jobs wants to use iPhone to put the 'baby Internet' to bed Big drug wholesalers may get bigger, with FDA help Want to beat the market? Take the inside path Three specialty REITs to buy on a pullback U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Growing share of 'Big Three' drug wholesalers gets attention U.S. mortgage rates edge higher for third straight week Five ways unmarried partners can safeguard their finances Bristol-Myers pleads guilty in federal Plavix case U.S. stocks rise amid deal news Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion U.S. mortgage rates edge higher for third straight week U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Del