 posted a 20 percent rise in quarterly profit on Thursday, helped by a legal settlement and other special gains, but sales declined at both its Sears and Kmart units. REUTERS/Jeff Christensen Email to a friend Excluding special items, earnings fell to $1.10 per share from $1.11. Analysts on average were expecting $1.22, according to Reuters Estimates. "In part, our domestic operating results reflect the impact of some of the same challenges being faced by our customers, such as rising energy costs and a slower housing market," Chief Executive Aylwin Lewis said in a release. "However, as an organization, we need to overcome these factors by better controlling costs and developing innovative solutions that better meet our customers' needs." Sales fell 2.5 percent to $11.7 billion, and U.S. comparable-store sales were down 3.9 percent. By brand, comparable-store sales, also known as comps, declined 3.4 percent at Sears and fell 4.4 percent at Kmart. The results came in at the lower end of the forecast the company provided on May 3, Credit Suisse analyst Gary Balter said in a note to clients. "Surprisingly, comps at Sears were a full point lower, at -3.4 percent, than they projected with two days to go in the quarter," he said. "Must have been a tough last weekend (or may reflect the apples to apples comps they reported which they may not have used in their preliminary report)." The Hoffman Estates, Illinois-based company's cash balance came to $3.4 billion. Investors watch Sears' cash position closely because the company has given Chairman Edward Lampert authority to invest excess money as he sees fit. The latest results include gains from a legal settlement, benefit plans at Sears Canada , a dividend from Sears Mexico and hurricane-related recoveries. Sears shares were down $4.09, or 2.2 percent, at $179.16 in morning Nasdaq trade. At Wednesday's close, the stock had risen about 9 percent this year and traded in a 52-week range of $195.18 to $134.56. John Mayer acts o