http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-5&fd=R&url=http://www.star-telegram.com/business/story/120572.html&cid=1116822769&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Star-Telegram.com | 05/31/2007 | Exxon Mobil chief cools global-warming dissent and all of North Texas Find Sales & Deals DFW Find a Home The Flower Mound Messenger DFW Find a Home Posted on Thu, May. 31, 2007 Exxon Mobil chief cools global-warming dissent New executive counters criticism with charm and patience Exxon Mobil chief cools global-warming dissent DALLAS -- Global warming was a hot topic at the Exxon Mobil Corp. annual meeting Wednesday, but Chief Executive Rex Tillerson continued his effort to cool some of the criticisms of the oil-industry giant. Tillerson, continuing the conciliatory approach he undertook a year ago upon succeeding the combative Lee Raymond, patiently tried to convince environmental and social activists that Exxon Mobil is concerned about and is taking steps to address the possibility that human and industrial activity are causing global temperatures to rise. "We don't have a difference of views that it's an important issue," Tillerson said. "We have differences about what we know and what we don't know." A sizable group of activists critical of the company's environmental policies were among the 1,000 or so shareholders who turned out for the three-hour meeting at the Morton H. Meyerson Symphony Center in downtown Dallas. One after another, critics took the microphone to criticize Exxon Mobil's past policies and support of groups that question the validity and the science behind the claims that global warming is largely caused by human consumption of fossil fuels. Framing their arguments in management terms, activists charged that Exxon Mobil's efforts have hurt the company's image and threatened to undermine its long-term financial viability. Andrew Logan of the Investor Network on Climate Risk pointedly asked why Exxon Mobil "has put so much effort into making itself public enemy Number 1 in terms of the global-warming debate" by openly opposing calls for the U.S. and foreign governments to make significant environmental policy changes. "You've sacrificed the company's reputation by taking a position that, it seems to me, is to the benefit of no one," Logan said. Tillerson, as he did repeatedly throughout the meeting, responded in measured tones. "We never set out to make the company public enemy Number 1," Tillerson said. Exxon's differences with global-warming activists, he said, have always been over the degree of certainty involved in the science of climate change. "What I find perplexing," Tillerson said, "is why people feel so threatened because we want to have a discussion" about the scientific issues "and what is known and what is not known." Even under Raymond, Tillerson said, Exxon Mobil has sought to support organizations that back work on the science of global warming and cutting carbon-dioxide emissions. Company scientists and engineers have played a role in the efforts of the United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, which has authored leading studies on climate change. Other critics, saying Exxon Mobil should seek to be a broad-based energy company, called for it to take a more active role and devote a share of its research and development funds and expertise in the development of alternative fuels rather than continue investing almost entirely in oil and gas production. "We do not oppose the development of alternatives to fossil fuels," Tillerson said, attempting to cool the discussion. But Exxon Mobil's expertise has made it the industry leader in oil and gas production and, Tillerson said, estimates of the world's rising energy requirements for the next 25 years show that the majority will still come from fossil fuels such as oil, natural gas and coal. Tillerson's charm offensive may not be winning many converts among the ranks of environmental and social activists, but it may be lessening the tension somewhat. None of the 15 shareholder proposals, all opposed by management, was approved. But several gained more than 40 percent of the votes cast, a significant advance against the management opposition. A year ago, for the first time in memory, a management-opposed measure was approved. One of the rejected proposals called for the company to adopt specific goals for reducing its own carbon-dioxide emissions to help counter global warming. It received a 31 percent favorable vote. The proposal gaining the most support, 47.8 percent, would have amended the company's bylaws to allow shareholders representing 10 percent of the company's stock to call a special shareholders meeting. The com- pany said such a provision now exists, provided shareholders can show good cause in court to call such a meeting. Tillerson, at the conclusion of the meeting, extended an olive branch to the dissidents among the Exxon Mobil shareholders. "I really do appreciate all of your comments today and the respectful way they were presented." DIRECTORS AND SHAREHOLDER INITIATIVES Shareholders overwhelmingly approved the election of all Exxon Mobil's nominated directors. Economist Michael Boskin of the free-market oriented Hoover Institution at Stanford University received the least support, 93 percent of the vote. New director Steve Reinemund, former chairman and CEO of PepsiCo, received a 98 percent favorable vote. 7.8 percent favored a proposal to allow shareholders representing 10 percent of the company's stock to call a special shareholders meeting. The company said such a provision now exists, provided shareholders can show good cause in court. 7.2 percent supported a resolution asking the Exxon Mobil board to adopt a bylaw allowing the company to recoup unearned bonuses or other incentive payments to senior executives. 1.2 percent voted for a proposal that would have allowed shareholders to vote on an advisory resolution approving the pay and other compensation of senior company executives. 1 percent voted for the company to adopt specific goals for reducing its own carbon-dioxide emissions to help counter global warming. About the Real Cities Network About the McClatchy Company Terms of Use & Privacy Statement
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-0&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/05/31/business/motorola.1-65313.php&cid=1116823896&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Motorola plans to cut 4,000 more jobs - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings Motorola plans to cut 4,000 more jobs Published: May 31, 2007 The latest round of cuts means the world&#039;s No.2 handset maker has announced plans to eliminate more than 10 percent of its workforce since the start of 2007 to improve sagging financial and operational results. The cellphone maker Motorola said it would cut another 4,000 jobs as part of a plan to improve sagging financial and operational results. The latest round of cuts means Motorola, the world&#039;s No. 2 handset maker, has announced plans to eliminate more than 10 percent of its work force since the start of 2007, when it became clear that two years of strong momentum behind its popular Razr phone had collapsed. The company is already eliminating 3,500 jobs as part of a two-year cost-cutting plan to save $400 million. Those layoffs, announced in January, are to be completed by June 30. Motorola said Wednesday that it would save another $600 million in 2008 by cutting 4,000 more workers, prioritizing investments and putting controls on discretionary spending and general and administrative expenses. US economy grows by just 0.6 percent in the first quarter Wachovia buys A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion . Deutsche Telekom executive who once worked at Siemens to leave company The company did not specify where the new cuts would be made. A spokeswoman, Jennifer Weyrauch, said they would be achieved through a mixture of attrition and layoffs. The company expects to take a restructuring charge of $300 million, or 8 cents per share, in 2007, from severance and related expenses from staff cuts. Tom Meredith, Motorola&#039;s chief financial executive, said the move was an "update to the commitment" the company had made "to drive out additional costs, and a continuation of the plan we announced in January." Motorola&#039;s work force, which stood at 150,000 people worldwide as recently as 2000, had declined to 66,000 at the beginning of the year. Weyrauch said the company, which has acquired several smaller firms in recent months, also is continuing to hire. It remains to be seen whether it can come up with a hit successor to the Razr, the success of which has been eroded by declining sale prices and competitors&#039; new phones. Wall Street appeared to modestly approve of the latest cuts. Motorola shares rose 12 cents in extended-hours trading after closing the regular session down 2 cents at $18.28. "From a cost-cutting perspective, these are steps in the right direction for the long term," said John Slack, a Morningstar analyst. "But the big issue to underscore is that products in the market are the key, and that is a slow ship to turn." Motorola began to cut back in January in an effort to recover from a series of miscues that caused it to lose about a third of its market value since October. It had ridden the Razr to significant gains in the world cellphone market for two years, closing the gap on its rival Nokia. But its strategy of cutting prices sharply to sell more units backfired, hammering its profit margins. Exacerbating its troubles, Ron Garriques departed abruptly in February as head of the cellphone unit. This spring, the company posted its first quarterly loss since 2004 and executives indicated that its efforts had not gone far enough. Motorola has already warned that its results from the April-June quarter will not be good. French presidency gets a bold new style Man with rare tuberculosis tells his tale Naples&#39;s trash is a challenge politicians are flunking Jihadist groups fill a Palestinian power vacuum Russia worried over UN plans for Kosovo independence Ernst & Young Won&#39;t Face Criminal Charges Thai court orders dissolution of ex-prime minister&#39;s party Gorbachev lends hand to book by Putin critic Turkey masses troops at border with Kurdish Iraq Poison used in China is found in U.S.-made animal feed With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow France&#39;s universities could be first test for Sarkozy Algeria&#39;s quiet revolution: Gains by women How the body (and mind) learns a dance With measure of caution, Europe joins biofuel gold rush Letter From China: China building gigantic cities to offset rural poverty Romania rules at Cannes Film Festival With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Do not neglect culture Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy Next venture from Martha Stewart: Groceries The assault on Assyrian Christians U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow The torture of the grave Islam and the afterlife Will oil wealth keep Cambodia afloat, or drown it? IHT.com on the go Listen to IHT articles on your computer, and create custom podcasts for your portable music player. Join the IHT's Daniel Altman in a lively discussion of the day's economic news with an eye on globalization. Today's Page One in Europe Today's Page One in Asia Advertise with the IHT Copyright &#169; 2007 the International Herald Tribune All rights reserved
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-0&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3DahNZsWtauvTk%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116844899&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ , May 31 12:17 , May 31 17:17 , Jun 01 01:17 Treasury 10-Year Yield at 9-Month High as Business Index Jumps By Elizabeth Stanton and Deborah Finestone May 31 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. Treasuries fell, pushing the benchmark 10-year note&#39;s yield to its highest level since August, after a measure of business activity rose more than forecast. Expectations the Federal Reserve will cut interest rates this year fell to the lowest since last July as the National Association for Purchasing Management-Chicago report indicated the economy is rebounding from a first-quarter slowdown. U.S. equities extended an advance that yesterday pushed the Standard & Poor&#39;s 500 Index to a record. ``I wouldn&#39;t be surprised to see people change their minds and raise the probability of the Fed hiking,&#39;&#39; said Ajay Rajadhyaksha, co-head of U.S. fixed-income strategy in New York at Barclays Capital, one of the 21 primary dealers that underwrite the U.S. government&#39;s debt. ``Yields will continue to move higher.&#39;&#39; The 10-year note&#39;s yield, which moves inversely to its price, rose more than 3 basis points, or 0.03 percentage point, to 4.9022 percent at 11:33 a.m. in New York, according to bond broker Cantor Fitzgerald LP. Earlier it touched 4.917 percent, the highest since Aug. 16. Until today, the highest level of the year was 4.902 percent on Jan. 26. The price of 4 1/2 percent notes maturing in May 2017 fell 9/32, or $2.81 per $1,000 face amount, to 96 27/32. The Dow Jones Industrial Average also rose from a record, and the Morgan Stanley Capital International Emerging Markets Index increased the most since March, approaching its May 22 record. ``Overlap the S&P and the 10-year contract, and you&#39;d see a very good correlation,&#39;&#39; said Jeffry Feigenwinter, head of U.S. Treasury trading at primary dealer BNP Paribas Securities Corp. in New York. ``Everybody thinks the market&#39;s cheap, but it&#39;s really still expensive&#39;&#39; relative to the overnight lending rate set by the Fed. The NAPM-Chicago&#39;s business barometer rose to 61.7 in May from 52.9 in April. Readings greater than 50 signal expansion. The median forecast of economists polled by Bloomberg was for a smaller increase to 54.0. ``We&#39;ll have to see if this follows through with the ISM number tomorrow,&#39;&#39; said Theodore Ake, head of U.S. government bond trading in New York at primary dealer Mizuho Securities USA Inc. He referred to the Institute for Supply Management&#39;s manufacturing index. The median forecast was for a decline to 54.0 from 54.7 in April. On a comparable increase in that gauge, ``the market&#39;s going to have to take out the fact that the next move from the Fed is an ease, and that any kind of ease in 2007 is out of the question,&#39;&#39; Ake said. Yields on Eurodollar futures expiring in December rose to the highest since July as traders pared bets on interest-rate cuts by the Fed. The yields forecast the interest rate on three- month bank deposits, which closely tracks the Fed&#39;s target for the overnight lending rate between banks. The three-month deposit rate, also known as Libor, is 5.36 percent. The federal funds target is 5.25 percent. The December Eurodollar futures yield rose 3 basis points to 5.285 percent, the highest since July 25. The market had little reaction to a government report showing the U.S. economy in the first quarter expanded at a slower pace than originally estimated. Gross domestic product grew at a rate of 0.6 percent, compared with an initial estimate of 1.3 percent, the Commerce Department said. The median forecast of economists polled by Bloomberg was for a revision to 0.8 percent. While the pace of GDP growth was the weakest in more than four years, reports have shown that business spending has improved in the second quarter. Minutes of Fed policy makers&#39; most recent meeting, released yesterday, showed they still expect growth to accelerate this year and are primarily concerned about inflation. A Labor Department report released at the same time as the GDP report showed new claims for state unemployment insurance benefits last week fell below their average for all of last year, pointing to strength in the labor market. The department&#39;s monthly employment report for May is forecast to show job creation accelerated. First-time claims for state jobless benefits fell to 310,000 for the week ended May 26, from a revised 314,000 during the prior period. Last year&#39;s average was 313,000. Treasuries may benefit later today from the monthly rebalancing of bond indexes to include securities issued during the month. Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc., whose U.S. investment-grade bond indexes are used as benchmarks by managers of $2.5 trillion, estimated the duration of its U.S. Treasury Index will increase by 0.22 years when the index is rebalanced, the most since August 2002. Duration measures price sensitivity to changes in yield, and is partly a function of maturity. Some portfolio managers buy bonds around the time of a rebalancing that causes the index&#39;s duration to lengthen. The so- called index extensions in February, May, August and November are larger than in other months because 10-year notes and 30-year bonds are sold then. Lehman&#39;s indexes are rebalanced at 3 p.m. New York time on the last business day of the month. Bonds issued during the month move into the index, and ones that no longer fit the index criteria are removed. The duration of the Treasury index was 4.77 years yesterday. To contact the reporters for this story: Elizabeth Stanton in New York at ; Deborah Finestone in New York at Last Updated: May 31, 2007 11:36 EDT Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division U.S. Economy Grows at 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Home Prices in U.S. Climbed at Slowest Pace in Decade During First Quarter
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-6&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/business/317825_jeppesen31.html&cid=1116798859&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Jeppesen provides added aviation services Skip ads and navigation Last updated May 30, 2007 10:12 p.m. PT Jeppesen provides added aviation services Jeppesen Dataplan Inc., sued by the American Civil Liberties Union on Wednesday, is a subsidiary of Boeing Commercial Aviation Services, which is a unit of Boeing Commercial Airplanes. Based in Englewood, Colo., Jeppesen is the world's largest provider of flight information services, such as the navigation charts that pilots use. It produces more than 2 billion such charts a year. The Boeing Co. acquired Jeppesen in August 2000 as part of its strategy to expand in the aviation services business, which Boeing estimated at the time would generate more than $2.6 trillion over the next two decades. The $1.5 billion in cash Boeing paid for the company was about six times Jeppesen's 1999 revenue of $235 million. Boeing has continued to grow Jeppesen, but it does not break out that revenue separately from overall sales in commercial airplanes. In its bid to acquire Jeppesen from the Tribune Co., Boeing had to beat out 10 other competitors. The media giant shed Jeppesen to help pay off debt after its purchase of the Los Angeles Times. When Boeing acquired Jeppesen, then-Boeing Chairman and Chief Executive Phil Condit had this to say: "This really is the glue to providing a whole set of information services. In the long run, we are trying to buy a business that can continue to grow." Jeppesen has since provided Boeing with an important and consistent revenue stream, according to industry analysts, although the amount is probably tiny compared with the more than $40 billion in annual sales generated by Boeing's jetliner business. P-I aerospace reporter James Wallace can be reached at 206-448-8040 or . Read his Aerospace blog at What do you think? Add P-I Business headlines t