sion, following last week's hike in the share trading tax. Nevertheless, markets in Tokyo, Hong Kong and Seoul ended higher, and European markets were only marginally lower on Monday. "The market opened down on the Chinese news, but I think we can shake that off. The reason that market is down is because of what the (Chinese) government is doing," said Victor Pugliese, director of listed equity trading at First Albany Corp. in San Francisco. The Dow Jones industrial average was down 24.79 points, or 0.18 percent, at 13,643.32. The Standard & Poor's 500 Index was down 1.25 points, or 0.08 percent, at 1,535.09. The Nasdaq Composite Index was down 2.40 points, or 0.09 percent, at 2,611.52. Stocks briefly pared some of their losses after data on April orders for durable goods was revised to show a bigger-than-expected 0.8 percent rise. The report said factory orders rose less than expected. Airline stocks fell after Continental Airlines reported lower revenues per passenger in May, an early sign of weakness going into the key summer travel season. Continental shares dropped 4 percent to $38.14. , parent of United Airlines, fell down 6.2 percent to $36.36 and was the worst percentage loser on the Nasdaq 100. Wal-Mart stock was up 3 percent to $50.93 on the New York Stock Exchange. Shares of contract electronics maker Solectron Corp. rose more than 15 percent to $3.88 on a takeover bid by rival Flextronics International Ltd. Shares of Onyx Pharmaceutical rose following news from the American Society of Clinical Oncology's annual meeting in Chicago. Onyx jumped after news its Nexavar liver cancer treatment was shown to extend the lives of patients. Shares of Onyx were up 8.5 percent to $33.50. Other shares trading higher were Palm Inc. , up 8 percent to $17.37 on its plan to sell a stake in private equity firm Elevation Partners. Scandal Sheet: Brad Pitt Brad Pitt was spotted in Montreal... Mexican crime won't stop Canadians Canadians took more trips abroad... Go topless t