http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-3&fd=R&url=http://articles.moneycentral.msn.com/Investing/Dispatch/070604markets.aspx&cid=1116822290&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Market Dispatches - MSN Money 6/4/2007 4:50 PM ET Stocks finish with a small rally The indexes withstand the pressures of $66 crude oil and a huge sell-off in China's stock market. Wal-Mart jumps on analysts' upgrades. News Corp.'s Rupert Murdoch meets with Dow Jones' controlling shareholders. E-mail to a friend Discuss in a Message Board View all lists and trends United States Dollar (b) vs UK Sterling Spot United States Dollar (b) vs Euro Spot United States Dollar (b) vs Japanese Yen Spot United States Dollar (b) vs Canadian Dollar Spot With little warning, a modest dip in the stock market turned into a bit of a rally by the close as investors shrugged off a big sell-off in China but piled into energy stocks. finished up about 8.2 points to 13,676, after spending most of the day in the red. The Standard & Poor's 500 Index moved 2.8 points higher to a record 1,539, and the added 4.4 points to 2,618. While gains are gains, they were limited by an 8.3% decline in stocks in Shanghai and a 1.7% gain in crude oil futures in New York to $66.21 a gallon, and a 4% gain in natural gas to $8.191 per million British thermal units. Pushing the commodities higher was a forecast that Cyclone Gonu would enter the Persian Gulf tomorrow and possibly disrupt shipments of crude oil from the oil fields of that region. Also, there were signs that consumers are not changing their driving habits in the face of higher gasoline prices. U.S. demand was up 2.4% in May, Bloomberg News noted. And there were concerns a strike in Nigeria over higher taxes would limit production from oil fields there. At the same time, the market has shown remarkable resilience. Mostly, CNBC's Bob Pisani said this afternoon, that's due to the flood of deals and stock buybacks, a sense that stocks are decently priced and high skepticism about the rally that forces some traders to buy to cover short positions. While energy stocks jumped -- the exchange-traded fund was up 1.6% to $70.03 -- the rest of the market was treading water. Only 13 of the 30 stocks in the Dow were higher on the day, led by , up 3.4% to $51.21. Five analysts upgraded the stock today after the company announced a new buyback plan and plans to scale back openings of new superstores in the next year. The Dow laggard was , down 0.8% to $51.75. But nearly 270 stocks in the S&P 500 were higher. The big leader in the market this afternoon was energy stocks. The Amex Natural Gas Index ) was up 2.1%, the Philadelphia Oil Service Sector Index ) was up 2.5%, and the Airlines were clobbered by the energy price increase and by heavy selling in , which reported weaker-than-expected results for May after Friday's market close. Continental was down 6.1% to $37.45. slumped 6.6% to 36.21. The ) fell 2.75%, the worst performer of 41 indexes that Market Dispatches tracks. The Dow Jones Transportation Index Energy prices -- New York close Crude oil (NYMEX) (per barrel) Heating oil (per gallon) Natural gas (per million BTU) Unleaded gasoline (per gallon) What's the problem in China? China's stock market tumbled today with the Shanghai Composite Index falling 8.3%. Today's falloff totaled more than 330 points and was its biggest one-day point drop since Feb. 27, when the index plunged 9%. The February sell-off sent shivers across the globe and helped push the Dow down 416 points -- the index's biggest one-day point loss since the stock market opened after Sept. 11, 2001. "There's panic selling" in China, money manager Yan Ji at HSBC Jintrust Fund Management in Shanghai told Bloomberg News. "Investors are convinced the government won't do anything to support the market." China's market had risen 62% for the year as of May 29. It has fallen 15.3% since the government tripled the tax on stock transactions. But the Chinese sell-off had little effect in other markets. The German, British and Japanese stock markets were little changed. But Briefing.com noted that the sell-off is again serving as a reminder that the U.S. stock market, which has also gotten ahead of fundamentals, is due for a pullback. Get free, real-time stock quotes on MSN Money The 15%-plus decline is almost as much as the Nasdaq lost in the first five trading sessions after the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks. Murdoch meeting with Bancrofts Rupert Murdoch met with members of the Bancroft family to hear their concerns about the editorial independence of The Wall Street Journal, should it accept his $5 billion bid for CEO and one of his sons, James Murdoch, were meeting with three members of the Bancroft family today to discuss the News Corp. bid, The Journal reported. The group will discuss how to safeguard Dow Jones' flagship newspaper, but Rupert Murdoch isn't expected to give in to a demand that the Bancroft family control an editorial-oversight board, The Journal reported. The Bancroft family holds 64% of the voting power in Dow Jones. "I can't put down $5 billion of my shareholders' money and not be able to run the business," the elder Murdoch told the newspaper. Shares of Dow Jones have risen 68% since Murdoch offered $5 billion, or $60 per share, for Dow Jones on May 1. Dow Jones was down 1.7% to $60.16. News Corp. was down slightly to $24.10. It's a beautiful day for Palm is selling a 25% stake in the company to private-equity firm Elevation Partners for $325 million. Palm will pay $940 million in cash, or $9 per share, to its existing shareholders for the change in ownership. The investment from Elevation Partners, along with $400 million in new debt, will help Palm pay the $9 distribution. Palm shares jumped $1.48, or 8.6%, to $17.57 on the day. The company also announced today that it will increase the size of its board to nine members from eight. Joining the board will be John Rubenstein, a former head of iPod division, who will be named executive chairman of Palm. Two co-founders of Elevation Partners, Fred Anderson and Roger McNamee, will replace two current board members who plan to resign. More from MSN Money Who will take your kids if you die? The damage of the dollar glut 10 stocks to buy now How much house can you really afford? 10 things you should know about gas prices See how the Dow stocks are doing "As a result of this transaction, we will strengthen the Palm leadership team and create a more effective capital structure, which puts us in a great position to attract new talent, significantly strengthen our execution capabilities, and deliver long-term shareholder value," Palm CEO Ed Colligan said in a statement. Rock superstar Bono is a managing director and co-founder of Elevation Partners. Release date set for iPhone Techies, get ready. You'll be able to get your hands on iPhone at the end of the month. Apple announced a June 29 release date for its latest gadget through three new advertisements posted on the company Web site. Apple hopes to sell 10 million iPhones next year. For now, the phone will be available only through Apple was up nearly 2% to $121.33. The stock is up nearly 31% this quarter and more than 43% this year. AT&T was up 0.9% to $40.90. Avaya eyed by private equity Private-equity firms Silver Lake Partners and TPG Capital are leading the pack of interested parties for , according to published reports, with the two firms set to buy the telecommunications-equipment maker for $17 per share. Shares of Avaya jumped nearly 4% to $16.72. The shares have risen 25% since rumors emerged a week or so ago that it was a takeover target. !heading text="Dominion to sell U.S. gas and oil operations "/> said it is selling most of its U.S. onshore oil-exploration and natural-gas operations in two transactions worth a total of $6.5 billion. , the big conglomerate that has stakes in CNA Insurance and , will buy Dominion's Michigan and Alabama operations for $4.025 billion. will buy the company's ope