http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-0&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/fn/4859271.html&cid=1116960778&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Ahead of the Bell: Factory Orders | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices June 4, 2007, 8:03AM Ahead of the Bell: Factory Orders &copy; 2007 The Associated Press WASHINGTON &mdash; Wall Street expects Commerce Department data due Monday to show that orders to U.S. factories grew at a far slower pace in April after March orders surged by the largest amount in a year. Total factory orders rose by 3.1 percent in March, driven by a jump in demand for commercial aircraft and greater business investment in new equipment. But analysts expect the April growth rate to cool considerably to 0.7 percent, according to the median forecast of economists surveyed by Thomson Financial. Commerce said orders for big-ticket durable goods rose by 3.7 percent in March, and orders for nondurable goods like petroleum and chemicals, rose by 2.3 percent. Following a massive 5.7 percent drop in total orders in January and an increase of 1.4 percent in February, March's better-than-expected jump offered hope that demand was rising for manufacturers who have been hurt by slumping housing and auto sales. Despite the slower growth estimate for orders to U.S. factories in April, the sector received a boost on Friday when the Institute for Supply Management said its manufacturing index showed growth for the fourth month in a row in May and reached its highest level in a year. The index registered 55 compared with 54.7 in April, a figure it last hit in May 2006. A reading above 50 indicates growth while a reading below 50 indicates contraction. ISM reported new orders and production grew, and the top five performing industries were: nonmetallic mineral products; fabricated metal products; food, beverage and tobacco; chemical products; and petroleum and coal. Haverty May Same-Store Sales Fall Big Retail Stocks Are Mixed Starbucks' Music Label Releases 1st CD S&P 500 Leaders & Laggards: SLR XTO SWY Chittenden to Buy Community Bank & Trust Magna's Stock Jumps on UBS Report U.S. manufacturing sector expands U.S. Manufacturing Sector Expands Ahead of the Bell:Manufacturing Activity Houston home prices on rise Other top ten companies New home sales surge in U.S., but prices drop Ahead of the Bell: Income and Spending Unemployment rate rises to 4.6 percent in January Wall Street Eyes Service Sector Report Wall Street eyes service sector report Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
http://www.forbes.com/markets/feeds/afx/2007/06/04/afx3784689.html&cid US April factory orders up 0.3 pct, ex-transportation up 0.7 pct. - Forbes.com US April factory orders up 0.3 pct, ex-transportation up 0.7 pct. 06.04.07, 11:20 AM ET WASHINGTON (Thomson Financial) - April US factory orders failed to show the kind of rebound economists were expecting on the back of strong manufacturing surveys, the Commerce Department said today. Overall factory orders rose 0.3 pct in April, while new orders excluding transportation related goods rose 0.7 pct. Economists had expected a 0.8 pct overall rise and a 0.9 pct gain excluding transportation. A decline in orders for non-durable goods was one factor for the lower-than expected rise, as orders and shipments of oil and gas fell due to a larger than normal number of refinery shutdowns. Commercial aircraft orders fell 10.7 pct, mostly on a decline in ) orders, while auto orders were down 3.3 pct. The weakness in the housing industry showed up in a 31.5 pct decline in orders for construction machinery. Overall non-defence capital goods orders fell 0.1 pct after rising 13.8 pct in March. So-called core capital goods orders, which excludes commercial aircraft and defence related goods, rose 2.1 pct in April. April factory shipments rose 0.8 pct, while inventories rose 0.5 pct. That left the inventory/shipment ratio down a tick to 1.24. Copyright AFX News Limited 2007. All rights reserved. The copying, republication or redistribution of AFX News Content, including by framing or similar means, is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of AFX News. Neither the Subscriber nor AFX News warrants the completeness or accuracy of the Service or the suitability of the Service as a trading aid and neither accepts any liability for losses howsoever incurred. The content on this site, including news, quotes, data and other information, is provided by AFX News and its third party content providers for your personal information 