http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-5&fd=R&url=http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,1895,2141370,00.asp&cid=1116926502&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Amp&#39;d Mobile Files for Chapter 11 - News and Analysis by PC Magazine Computer & Console Gaming Amp'd Mobile Files for Chapter 11 Broadband wireless provider Amp'd Mobile announced on Monday that it filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on June 1. The move is an effort to restructure the business, according to Amp'd Mobile. Amp'd announced recently that it had almost 200,000 customers. "As a result of our rapid growth, our back-end infrastructure was unable to keep up with company demand," the company said in a statement. Amp'd is working with several unnamed investors to "obtain debtor-in-possession financing," the statement said. The company's executive team will remain "largely intact," Amp'd said. The Wall Street Journal has reported that Amp'd is more than $100 million in debt and has less than $100 million in assets. It owes Verizon Wireless about $33 million, its handset provider Motorola about $16 million, investor Vivendi SA about $10 million, and retailer Best Buy about $8 million, according to court documents. Earlier this year, Motorola released its Moto Q, Amp'd Edition covered several Amp'd handsets and services I'm saddened. Amp'd "gets" mobile content in a way that other carriers don't; its prices are refreshingly reasonable, and some of its programming is so good that it's made its way to big-screen TV! Hopefully the company will be able to reinvent itself as a content provider for Verizon, and transition users gently over to Verizon's network. (Verizon certainly needs the coherent content vision that Amp'd provides.) This news is also bad news for any other companies who want to go up against the big carriers with a high-end or content-focused product. Can you ramp up your sales enough before the bills come crashing down? Looks like that's tough to do. PC Magazine Breaking News RSS feed to you