http://www.mercurynews.com/news/ci_6057974&cid San Jose Mercury News - Accredited Home Lenders agrees to be sold for $400 million san jose / valley start / stop paper (From the last 24 hours) Southwest jet skids after landing gear collapses in Oakland Parents of TB patient are 'in hell' Informant helped bust alleged JFK plot Roadshow: Value of carpool lanes in dispute, but more on way Kawakami: Blame must fall on Giants' G.M. Sabean, and it's time to go Better times bring worse traffic Accredited Home Lenders agrees to be sold for $400 million By ELLIOT SPAGAT AP Business Writer Article Launched: 06/04/2007 10:55:17 AM PDT SAN DIEGO- Accredited Home Lenders Holding Co., which makes mortgage loans to high-risk buyers, said Monday that it agreed to be acquired by a private-equity fund for about $400 million in cash. Lone Star Fund V LP will pay $15.10 per share for the company, a 10 percent premium over the stock's closing price of $13.76 on Friday. Accredited shares rose $1.58, or 11.6 percent, to $15.34 in early afternoon trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Still, the shares traded above $50 a year ago. "After a careful analysis, we believe this agreement is the best alternative available to protect shareholder value and provide the capital we need to support the company's business over the long-term," said Accredited Chief Executive James A. Konrath. "In Lone Star, we have found a partner who has a record of helping companies like ours successfully address financial and operational challenges." The offer is expected to close in the third quarter. Accredited, based in San Diego, competes in the subprime mortgage industry, which fell into turmoil earlier this year as payment defaults spiked and investors lost their appetite for risky home loans. In March, it received a $200 million loan from Farallon Capital Management LLC, a San Francisco-based money manager, following the sale of $2.7 billion of mortgage loans. Last month, it delayed filing its audited first-quarter report because it had a new auditor and forecast a "significant loss" for the quarter. Another subprime lender, New Century Financial Corp., sought Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in April. The Irvine-based company had been the second-largest provider of home loans to high-risk borrowers, but it collapsed after a spike in mortgage defaults led its lenders to pull funding and demand that it buy back bad loans. Private investment firm Carrington Capital Management LLC and an affiliate won a bankruptcy auction of New Century's loan servicing business&mdash;its core asset&mdash;for $188 million. The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. E. coli fear spurs ground beef recall at Albertsons, Save-A-Lot Milpitas soldier killed by explosive in Baghdad Los Gatos skatepark supporters want voters to decide issue Daily Entertainment Break: Paris Hilton behind bars Flextronics to buy Solectron for &#36;3.6 billion Two San Jose teens killed in fatal crash San Francisco man with dementia missing for more than a week Elevation buys stake in Palm Copyright 2007 San Jose Mercury News Privacy Policy and Terms of Use MNG Corporate Site Map
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-5&fd=R&url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/06/04/ap3785347.html&cid=1116959363&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Sector Snap: Subprime Mortgage Lenders - Forbes.com Sector Snap: Subprime Mortgage Lenders 06.04.07, 12:24 PM ET Shares of subprime mortgage lenders rose Monday after Accredited Home Lenders Holding Co. reached a deal to sell itself to a private equity firm, signaling that some investors are willing to bet on a rebound in the troubled sector. Early Monday, the San Diego-based mortgage lender agreed to sell itself to Lone Star Fund V LP for $400 million, or $15.10 per share, cash. The deal values Accredit Home Lenders at a 9.7 percent premium to Friday's closing trade. ) fell victim this year to the turmoil sweeping through "subprime" mortgage lending, the area of banking catering to home buyers with patchy credit histories. As borrowers with bad credit began missing payments more frequently, subprime mortgage loans became harder to sell to investors and many of the banks' financial backers cut lenders off from borrowing more money. More than 30 subprime lenders have gone bankrupt this year amid an industrywide cash crunch. Fox-Pitt Kelton analyst Matthew Howlett wrote in a research report Lone Star provides Accredited with "a diversified funding base." The disarray in the sector is not because subprime mortgage lending will be permanently unprofitable, Howlett said. A lot of lenders simply ran out of cash during the downturn and had to sell their loans at a loss. "The business is inherently cyclical and the economics of the business are likely to rebound," he said. "Ultimately, we believe private-equity money realizes this and are capitalizing on the current stress in the marketplace to build capacity cheaply." While Lone Star is paying a premium to Accredited Home Lenders' stock from the previous trading day, the buyout price is a fraction of the stock's value before the industry collapsed. The shares topped $60 in May 2006 and ended last year at more than $27. The stock went from August 2003 until February 2007 without dipping below Lone Star's offer price. Howlett said Lone Star is acquiring Accredited Home Lenders at a discount to the total value of the lender's assets. Shares of many subprime mortgage lenders and financiers rose Monday even as the overall stock market fell. Shares of Accredited Home Lenders jumped $1.62, or 11.9 percent, to $15.39; shares of ) Inc. rose 34 cents, or 5.6 percent, to $7.80; and shares of ) rose 27 cents, or 2.1 percent, to $13.16. Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed More On This Topic ",">"); transformedStoryStr=transformedStoryStr.replaceAll(""","\""); out.write(transformedStoryStr); %--> Starting A Small Business Brought to you by the sponsors below A new book from brings the Himalaya experience home.
