http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-1&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/safeco-geico-ruling-limits-credit/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257BA4D0F0A5-17A2-42E9-BC78-1CC18E2E3C2C%257D&cid=1116962805&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Safeco, Geico ruling limits credit score lawsuits - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Safeco, Geico ruling limits credit score lawsuits By Mark H. Anderson Last Update: 4:20 PM ET Jun 4, 2007 (Updates paragraphs 1-7, focusing on the broad impact of the ruling; Adds details about the vote count in paragraphs 1 and 7; Add information about additional deliberations in the cases in paragraph 10.) WASHINGTON (MarketWatch) -- The U.S. Supreme Court Monday made it harder for consumers to bring credit score lawsuits against the insurance industry, in a unanimous ruling favoring Safeco Insurance Co. of America, a unit of Safeco Inc. (SAFC) and Geico General Insurance Co., a unit of Berkshire Hathaway The justices said the insurance industry, under the Fair Credit Reporting Act, must notify customers that it is charging higher insurance rates only when the higher rate is based on a low credit score. Companies aren't in violation of the law, the high court said, if the consideration of a credit score, as one of several considerations, didn't by alter the pricing. "Congress meant to require notice and prompt a challenge by the consumer only when the consumer would gain something if the challenge succeeded," Justice David Souter wrote in the court's opinion. The Supreme Court also said Safeco and Geico weren't reckless by not notifying customers about how their credit scores were used in insurance pricing decisions. Justice Souter's opinion added that Geico didn't violate the federal credit law and that Safeco "might have" but didn't do so recklessly. In a move creating a mixed outcome for the insurance industry, the high court stopped short of backing a higher standard of legal recklessness under the credit reporting law that the companies sought in the appeal. "There being no indication that Congress had something different in mind, we have no reason to deviate," Justice Souter wrote in applying a standard recklessness test. The Supreme Court ruling reverses opinions by the Ninth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco. While all nine justices supported most of the opinion, Justices John Paul Stevens and Ruth Bader Ginsburg filed a concurring opinion arguing the opinion will lead to too few consumers getting notices about how their credit scores impact pricing decisions. Justices Clarence Thomas and Samuel Alito filed a statement saying they support most of the ruling but saw no reason for the court to resolve factual questions in the Safeco case. Insurance companies have faced a wave of class-action lawsuits alleging they violated federal law by not telling consumers low credit scores resulted in higher quotes for insurance coverage. It's a common practice in the insurance industry to review credit scores and offer lower rates to customers with higher credit scores. Safeco and Geico were challenging a Ninth Circuit decision that said companies must tell consumers any time credit scores result in higher insurance rates. Companies face up to $1,000 in actual damages plus punitive damages for violation of the federal law. The cases are Safeco Insurance v. Burr, 06-84 and Geico General Insurance v. Edo, 06-100. Both appeals now go back to lower courts for additional deliberations. Related Blog Posts & Articles Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Sign up to receive the Weekend TV Show Preview U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 U.S. stock futures drop with bond yield rise, China in focus Five little-known tips for getting better gas mileage Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Three safe havens to stash your cash Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Palm sells stake to Elevation; former Apple execs join ranks Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Three safe havens to stash your cash Who has the hot hand? Flextronics to acquire Solectron for $3.6 bln DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 Telecom firm Avaya reportedly close to private-equity deal Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 More equity hedge funds are shorting ETFs rather than stocks Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Get the Latest MarketWatch News >> Company: Berkshire Hathaway Inc Del (BRKA) Company: Berkshire Hathaway Inc Del (BRKB) Company: SAFECO Corporation (SAF) Berkshire Hathaway Inc Del Berkshire Hathaway Inc Del Dow Jones Licensing Services Dow Jones Online Network: Copyright &copy; 2007 MarketWatch, Inc. All rights reserved. By using this site, you agree to the Safeco, Geico ruling limits credit score lawsuits - MarketWatch Intraday data provided by , a division of Interactive Data Corp. and subject to . Historical and current end-of-day data provided by . More information on and their current financial status. Intraday data delayed 15 minutes for Nasdaq, and 20 minutes for other exchanges. Dow Jones IndexesSM from Dow Jones & Company, Inc. SEHK intraday data is provided by Comstock and is at least 60-minutes delayed. All quotes are in local exchange time.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-2&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/fn/4859281.html&cid=1116960538&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Laureate Education OK's Raised $3.8B Bid | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices June 4, 2007, 3:48PM Laureate Education OK's Raised $3.8B Bid By STEPHEN MANNING AP Business Writer &copy; 2007 The Associated Press CHEVY CHASE, Md. &mdash; Laureate Education Inc. said Monday that it has agreed to go private for $3.82 billion in cash from a group led by the higher education company's chairman and chief executive officer. The sweetened offer of $62 per share tops the investor group's earlier bid of $60.50 per share, a deal that some of Laureate's major investors said was too low. A tender offer for Laureate's shares is scheduled to begin Friday. Baltimore-based Laureate, formerly known as Sylvan Learning Systems Inc., is a for-profit higher education company with 24 accredited institutions and 240,000 students in 15 countries. It includes online schools such as Walden University and universities in places such as Chile, Switzerland and China. Laureate's board unanimously accepted the latest offer, which represents a 26 percent premium over the company's closing stock price on Jan. 4, the day before a special committee of independent Laureate directors authorized advisers to start negotiations on a definitive acquisition. Shares of Laureate Education rose $1.52, or 2.53 percent, to $61.63 Monday. The investor group led by Chairman and CEO Douglas Becker includes Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., Citi Private Equity, SAC Capital Management LLC, SPG Partners, Bregal Investments, Caisse de depot et placement du Quebec, Sterling Capital, Makena Capital, Torreal SA and Brenthurst Funds. Becker and director R. Christopher Hoehn-Saric, along with certain other affiliates of Sterling Capital, have agreed to accept the original per share offer price in connection with the rollover of their shares in the transaction. The deal, however, could face problems from some of Laureate's larger shareholders. Three investors _ T. Rowe Price Group Inc., Select Equity Group Inc. and BlackRock Inc. _ all expressed doubts about the earlier $60.50 per share offer. Laureate has forecast earnings of $5 per share by 2010, which T. Rowe Price said could send Laureate's share price to $110 over the next three years. The mutual fund company said in a March letter that it wanted Laureate to remain public so that shareholders could benefit from its "excellent long-term growth prospects." The three investors also said they were concerned about potential conflicts of interest, saying the deal put Becker in the position of trying to seek the lowest price as a buyer while ostensibly trying to maximize value for shareholders. T. Rowe Price, Select Equity and BlackRock did not immediately return calls seeking comment on the raised offer. Laureate also did not reply to a phone message. Trace Urdan, an analyst with the investment bank Signal Hill Capital Group, said the higher price likely got "one of the nay sayers to come on board." "Though I am sure they probably won't pull everyone on, they probably have successfully broken the anti-deal coalition," he said. The tender offer requires only a simple majority of 50 percent of the company's outstanding shares to approve the buyout. But if that threshold isn't met, Laureate can then include the stock options held by Becker and Hoehn-Saric to reach a majority. The tender offer is slated to last 20 business days. Becker has been CEO and chairman since 2000. Urdan described him as a "bright" executive and said the decision behind the buyout was likely in part a reflection of Becker's impatience with the constraints of running a public company. Going private will also help Laureate as it expands into developing _ and more volatile _ markets around the world, he said. Haverty May Same-Store Sales Fall Big Retail Stocks Are Mixed Starbucks' Music Label Releases 1st CD S&P 500 Leaders & Laggards: SLR XTO SWY Chittenden to Buy Community Bank & Trust Magna's Stock Jumps on UBS Report List of the world's richest people Forbes' list of the world's billionaires Forbes' billionaires by rank Failure of Legislation Helps TXU Buyers Failure of electric legislation helps TXU buyers Senate OKs bill allowing state to review TXU sale Premarket Movers: Cray Drops on Outlook Forbes' billionaires by country (PRN) KKR, TPG and TXU Announce a Total 15% Price Reduction Deal would give regulators more of a say in power market Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
http://news.digitaltrends.com/news/story/13173/ampd_mobile_files_for_chapter_11&cid Amp'd Mobile Files for Chapter 11 - Mobile News - Digital Trends Amp'd Mobile Files for Chapter 11 Monday, June 4th 2007 @ 9:00 AM PDT Staff Writer, Digital Trends News Youth-oriented MVNO Amp'd Mobile has filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection after failing to raise enough money to meet its debt payments. filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection . According to a statement from Amp'd Mobile, the company's infrastructure hasn't been able to keep up with customer demand, and the Chapter 11 filing is a way for the company to restructure its business, with the expectation it will resume normal business operations. The Wall Street Journal ( ) reports the company wasn't able to raise enough money to keep up on its debt payments. Amp'd Mobile operates as an MVNO&mdash;mobile virtual network operator&mdash;operating on Verizon's mobile network. The service has been operating for about a year and a half. Amp'd investors include MTV and Universal Music Group, and targets technologically-hip young consumers via music promotions, media-centric devices and services, and by sponsoring youth-oriented action-sports events. A bankruptcy filing will likely enable the company to shake much of its estimated $100 million in debt (including substantial sums owed to Verizon and Motorola), but will also likely consume ownership stakes and preferred stock owned by investors and key executives. Amp'd describes its top management team as remaining "largely intact;" reports in recent weeks have pointed to a possible rift between CEO Peter Adderton and Amp'd's directors; the company has also had issues with COO Susan Swenson, who's move to Amp'd from T-Mobile was delayed in 2005 by a judicial ruling which found she'd violated a non-compete clause with her former employer, T-Mobile. Amp'd says it is working with one of its largest investors to obtain debtor-in-possession financing. Palm Adds Former Apple Execs to Board Now We Know When We Can Buy An iPhone AT&T Launching New 3G Samsung Phones Nokia Launches N75, N76 in United States Palm Spreads Its Wings With The Foleo on Jun 4th, 2007 at 10:08 AM No suprised here. Rebranding someone elses phone isn't a good business plan. I don't care if they have better software or features, it's not enough to carry a company. Comments should be relevant to this news story. An email address is required for verification purposes only and will not be displayed. HTML is not allowed in comments. For links, simply type the url. Your Email Address (required, but will not be shown): Your Site's URL (optional): Search for Wi-Fi hot spots near you: Be in the know! Sign up for the Digital Trends Newsletter today. Copyright &copy; 2007 Digital Trends - All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-3&fd=R&url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070420.ingramnewmedia/BNStory/Business/columnists&cid=1116960159&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg reportonbusiness.com: Ingram on Media Letters to the Editor Globe and Mail Update June 4, 2007 at 11:42 AM EDT YouTube, the video-sharing site now owned by Google, has struck a deal with a regional U.S. TV network to run the network's local content on YouTube and share any advertising revenue with the company -- although the exact terms of the arrangement aren't clear. YouTube said on Sunday that it has signed a deal with Hearst-Argyle Television, and that it will carry news, weather and entertainment video content from five of the company's TV stations. Hearst-Argyle has 29 stations, including outlets in Boston, New Hampshire, Sacramento, Pittsburgh and Baltimore. They are affiliates of ABC, NBC, CBS, and Fox. Hearst has about an 18 per cent share of the U.S. market, according to the company. In addition to news and weather, YouTube is also going to carry some of the network's newer digital video content, including footage of high-school football and basketball games, as well as local amateur entertainment, the companies said in a statement. The video-sharing site, which is currently fighting lawsuits over misappropriated content from Viacom and other groups, has said that it plans to sign other revenue-sharing deals with content owners -- including individuals -- who allow their videos to be shown on YouTube. Got any interesting new media tips or sites you've come across that are interesting? Send me an email at Comments are closed for this story | Send a letter to the editor Add MATHEW INGRAM to my e-mail alerts Top Report on Business Stories Brian Mulroney tapped for board seat at Blackstone GE buys properties from Dundee REIT for $2.4-billion Loonie rockets higher, again 'Big leavers' lever bigger pay packages Go to the Report on Business section Report on Busines