http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-5&fd=R&url=http://www.wnep.com/Global/story.asp%3FS%3D6609652%26nav%3Dmenu158_2&cid=1116856910&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Rite-Aid Buys Eckerd Drugs Give Thanks To Dad Cook Up Something Hot Father's Day Fun Facts Daily Comic -- With Sound File and Pay Online Healthy Living: Food & Nutrition This Week in House and Home House & Home Main Help Around the House This Week in Money Sun Sign Guide to Money 66 Ways to Save Money Loss of a Pet Our Newest Viewer Recipes! This Week in Weddings Wedding of the Week Planning Ideas & Advice This Week from CareerJournal.com Interview Like a Pro Rite-Aid Buys Eckerd Drugs Monday, June 4, 4:26 p.m. The Rite-Aid Drug Store chain announced Monday it closed a deal to acquire almost 300 Eckerd Drug Stores in Pennsylvania. It is part of a $3.9 billion acquisition that makes Rite-Aid the biggest drug store chain on the east coast. Rite-aid said customers will begin seeing changes soon at Eckerd Drug stores. All the stores will be remodeled and will take on the Rite-Aid name within 16 months. The first Rite-Aid store opened 45 years ago along North Washington Avenue in Scranton. Shopper Paul Kamor admitted he&#39;s a Rite-Aid fan. "I like the rebates. Matter of fact, I have one right here!" he said. With the acquisition, Rite-Aid expands to more than 5,000 stores nationwide. Financial consultant Lou Ingargiola thinks the company is now poised to compete with the big boys in the drug store business, Walgreen&#39;s and CVS. "If you are small, you will not survive. You need big, and big is working in every industry," Ingargiola said. Andrew Brown&#39;s Pharmacy on Scranton&#39;s south side is one of a handful of independently owned drug stores still around. After 96 years in business the owners are confident they know how to keep their customers. "Our feeling is they&#39;re better to have the personalized service that the community pharmacies can give them," said Mike Brown of Andrew Brown&#39;s Pharmacy. He added these days mail-order drug companies are a bigger threat to his business than the big chains. As for the big getting bigger in the drug store world Rite-Aid shopper Kamor is unconcerned. "If it&#39;s efficient and it brings better service and prices to the customer, then it&#39;s probably worth it," Kamor said. There is nothing in Rite-Aid&#39;s announcement to indicate there are thoughts about closing any of the just-acquired Eckerd stores. A Rite-Aid spokeswoman was looking into whether any closures could be expected. More from Newswatch 16 . . . Teachers Strike in Northwest Area School District Expanded Bus Service in Schuylkill County Rite-Aid Buys Eckerd Drugs Scranton Park Gets Makeover Cabbie Robbed in Monroe County Send questions or comments about this web site to All content &copy; Copyright 2002 - 2007 WorldNow and WNEP. All Rights Reserved. For more information on this site, please read our
