http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-4&fd=R&url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070604.wblack0604/BNStory/International/home&cid=1116567986&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg globeandmail.com: Former National Post editor grilled at Black trial Letters to the Editor Former National Post editor grilled at Black trial Globe and Mail Update June 4, 2007 at 4:27 PM EDT &#151; Maclean's editor Ken Whyte faced tough questioning by prosecutor Julie Ruder at the Conrad Black trial this morning over a $100,000 he received in 2003 that was arranged by Lord Black. At the time, Mr. Whyte was editor of the National Post, which had been sold to CanWest Global Communication Corp. by Hollinger International Inc. Ms. Ruder pointed out that Lord Black arranged for Hollinger to pay the bonus to Mr. Whyte in order to keep up their association. She also noted that at the time Lord Black was bound by a non-competition agreement with CanWest that prohibited him from inducing or recruiting the paper's senior mangers. Mr. Whyte replied that he did not know details about Lord Black's non-competition agreement and he understood the bonus was for his past work with Hollinger. Testimony provides glimpse of Black's collectibles and tomes How Black built his empire');"> How Black built his empire Ms. Ruder read portions of a deposition Mr. Whyte gave as part of a lawsuit he filed in New York against Hollinger in 2005 over company stock options. (He settled the suit earlier this year.) In that deposition, Mr. Whyte said the bonus was paid in part to maintain their association. Mr. Whyte insisted the bonus was for his past work at the paper which had been "sold out from under him." He said Lord Black wanted to ensure that they were remained on good terms so they could work together again in future. Under questioning by Edward Greenspan, one of Lord Black's lawyers, Mr. Whyte confirmed that Lord Black talked about positions in Chicago or New York. Mr. Greenspan said the CanWest non-competition agreement only applied to Canada. During her questioning Ms. Ruder also referred to Mr. Whyte's alleged bias, asking him several times if he was friends with Lord Black and loyal to him. Mr. Whyte said he was "friendly" with Lord Black. As for his loyalty, Mr. Whyte said: "I suppose I am loyal to him." In her examination, Ms. Ruder referred Mr. Whyte to the prosecution's contention that Lord Black was on vacation in July, 2001 in Bora Bora. Hollinger paid for part of that trip, which prosecutors have argued was an abuse of company money. Lord Black's lawyers have argued that Lord Black ended up paying for most of the trip and that Lord Black worked all the time. Ms. Ruder showed Mr. Whyte e-mails from marketing people at the National Post around the time of the trip. The marketing people were trying to arrange a letter from Lord Black for an upcoming ad in a trade publication. However they were told that Lord Black was out of touch and "on vacation." Mr. Whyte said he could recall details about the e-mails and that the issue was not significant at the time. While there had been speculation that Donald Trump would appear as a witness today he was not called. Lord Black's lawyers later said they will not be calling Mr. Trump as a witness. They did not say why. Mr. Trump's name had been on a proposed list of witnesses for weeks. Also Monday morning, the jury was shown several invoices for furnishings and decorations for Lord Black's New York apartment. Prosecutors allege Lord Black paid too little when he bought the apartment from Hollinger for $3-million (U.S.) in 2000. That was the same price Hollinger paid in 1994. Lord Black's lawyers argue that he paid a fair price considering the amount he spent fixing up the place. This morning, Lee Williams, a forensic accountant, testified that Lord Black spent $4.6-million on the apartment. But under cross examination by prosecutor Eric Sussman, Mr. Williams acknowledged that some of those costs included items Lord Black took with him and therefore would not affect the value of the apartment. Mr. Sussman presented a list of some examples of the expenses, including a $9,750 plaque "depicting Amazon women," a $9,600 mother of pearl box, a $17,000 music system and a pair of white marble elephant reliefs which cost $17,710. Lord Black also spent $4,399 on heated towel bars, according to the invoices. Comments are closed for this story | Send a letter to the editor Add PAUL WALDIE to my e-mail alerts U.S. case against Khadr collapses Harper offers Canada's law as greenhouse template Putin threatens to target Europe China vows to cut greenhouse gases Go to the World section A surprise invitation ton intimate dinner at Putin's countryside dacha Top Stories by Section Brian Mulroney tapped for board seat at Blackstone Rising waters could force hundreds from homes in B.C. U.S. case against Khadr collapses Pronger leaves a hole Paris Hilton begins serving jail sentence On the Web, TV's been a bottom-line blip Living life through the grief Putin threatens to target Europe Harper offers Canada's law as greenhouse template Cutting health tax will put province in debt, McGuinty says Silence of the lamb Submit post to digg.com Seed this post at Newsvine Technorati links to this post A tag is a keyword or descriptive term supplied by our editorial staff used to associate related articles with one another. Tags make it easier for you to find other stories that share the same theme or topic with the article you&#8217;re currently reading. Globe Insider E-mail Alerts Have all subsequent stories by this writer e-mailed to you. Add PAUL WALDIE to my breaking news e-mail alerts What are e-mail alerts? What are e-mail Alerts? E-mail alerts deliver the news to your inbox as it happens. &#169; Copyright 2007 CTVglobemedia Publishing Inc. All Rights Reserved. The Globe and Mail are divisions of CTVglobemedia Publishing Inc.,
