a and telecom and technology sectors. According to NEP, Jacobson, founded in 1968 by Richard Jacobson, has tripled profitability and revenues under its ownership and has a proven business model, growth potential and strong management team. The group consists of six integrated operating companies - Jacobson Warehouse Company, Jacobson Transportation Company, Jacobson Logistics Company, Jacobson Packaging Company, Jacobson Staffing Company, and Jacobson Investment Company. Jacobson has grown through strategic acquisitions of Arthur Wells in July 2006; Wilpak in May 2006; Southwest Storage & Distribution in January 2006; and Bekins Logistics in February 2005. Ted Dardani, a Partner at Oak Hill, stated, “We are excited to partner with Craig and his outstanding management team. Jacobson has consistently delivered high-quality services and built profitable long-term customer relationships.” In addition, NEP's affiliated mezzanine fund, Norwest Mezzanine Partners, made a $17 million subordinated debt investment concurrent with NEP's initial investment in Jacobson. The transaction will be financed by a banking group to be led by Bear, Stearns & Co., CIBC World Markets Inc. and Wells Fargo & Co. Rite Aid Completes Acquisition Of Brooks And Eckerd Stores - Update [RAD] 6/4/2007 1:38:22 PM Monday, drug retailer Rite Aid Corp. (RAD) revealed the completion of the Brooks and Eckerd stores acquisition and along with six distribution centers from Canadian company The Jean Coutu Group (PJC), Inc. (PJC.A), elevating it as the third largest drug retailer in the U.S. Rite Aid entered into a definitive agreement with the Jean Coutu Group on August 24, 2006 to acquire the U.S. subsidiary of the Jean Coutu Group that included 1,854 Brooks and Eckerd stores and six distribution centers located in 18 states, predominantly on the East Coast and the Mid-Atlantic region. The Camp Hill, Pennsylvania based company named Mary Sammons, Rite Aid President and Chief Executive Officer, as the Chairman of the Rite Aid Board of Directors in place of Robert Miller who will continue as a director. The former President of the Jean Coutu Group's U.S. subsidiary, Michel Coutu, has been made Rite Aid's non-executive co-chairman. The acquisition is expected to provide Rite Aid achieve significant cost efficiencies, however, expects to report a net loss for 2008 from integration expenses. Rite Aid also projects nine months of acquisition-related cost savings of approximately $155 million. Additional acquisition-related cost savings, net of the remaining integration expenses, are anticipated to be accretive by $0.18 - $0.20 per share in 2009. Included in the accretion estimates for fiscal 2009 are annual cost savings of $225 million. Rite Aid entered into a definitive agreement with the Jean Coutu Group on August 24, 2006 to acquire the U.S. subsidiary of the Jean Coutu Group, and subsequently approved by Rite shareholders in January 2007. The Federal Trade Commission cleared the deal on June 1, 2007 with Rite Aid consenting to divest 23 stores in nine states and will also enter into state consent orders for the divestitures required by the Commission and for the divestiture of three additional stores. Sammons, said, "The completion of this transaction is a significant milestone for the shareholders, customers and associates of Rite Aid, and we are ready to hit the ground running with a detailed integration plan that includes significant investments in the Brooks and Eckerd stores and in our new associates. With a much larger Rite Aid, we're confident we will have substantial opportunities to reduce costs, improve operations and grow earnings per share, which will generate greater value for our shareholders." Rite Aid will now have 5,160 stores after regulatory requirement in the divestures of 26 stores. The acquired Brooks and Eckerd stores will be remodeled in phases and re-branded Rite Aid in the next 16 months. Rite Aid will immediately convert 23 Brooks and Eckerd pilot stores and will integrate the six distribution centers. Rite Aid said full remodeling is planned over the years with total upgrade investment of stores and distribution centers anticipated to be over $1 billion. As part of its ongoing store development program, the company proposes to open about 1,000 new and relocated stores over the next five years. The acquired stores include Massachusetts, Rhode Island, North Carolina and South Carolina where Rite Aid makes an entry and the balance in 14 states where Rite Aid already has a presence. Rite Aid also acquired the Brooks Eckerd corporate headquarters in Warwick, Rhode Island. The transaction included $2.36 billion in cash to the Jean Coutu Group, subject to a working capital adjustment, and 250 million shares of Rite Aid common stock, giving it an about 32% common equity interest and approximately 30% voting power in Rite Aid. RAD is gaining $0.17 or 2.67% and currently trades at $6.53, on a volume of 5.02 million shares on the NYSE. PJC-A.TO is gaining C$0.13 or 0.89% and currently trades at C$14.73, on a volume of 158,325 shares on the Toronto Stock Exchange. PACCAR Financial Services Completes Acquisition Of Truck Center Hauser GmbH In Germany Microsoft Announces Launch Of Ignition Program Kosan Biosciences Reports Positive Results For Alvespimycin Monsanto Says EPA Approves Natural Refuge For Bollgard II Cotton ZymoGenetics Reports Results For Atacicept In Phase 1b Clinical Trial Copyright &copy; 2007 RealTimeTraders.com, Inc. All rights reserved. By using this site, you agree to the Terms of Service How To Use RTTNews.com
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-3&fd=R&url=http://moneycentral.msn.com/inc/news/providerredir.asp%3Ffeed%3DOBR%26Date%3D20070604%26ID%3D6989759&cid=1116957983&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Reuters Business News: Loews bets on natural gas in $4 billion Dominion deal - MSN Money Enter name or tic June 4, 2007 4:44 PM ET Loews bets on natural gas in $4 billion Dominion deal Stocks mentioned in this article Boardwalk Pipeline Partners, LP ( CNH Global N.V. ( Dominion Resources, Inc. ( XTO Energy Inc. ( NEW YORK (Reuters) - Loews Corp.'s $4.03 billion purchase of gas exploration and production assets from Dominion Resources Inc. gives the conglomerate a way to spend excess cash and diversify its revenue stream as it bets on rising natural gas prices. "It vindicates Loews' strategy of holding cash at the holding company level," said Matt Nellans, a Morningstar Inc. analyst. "It got a reasonable price and Dominion's exploration and production management team. Absent a complete bottoming out of natural gas prices, the deal should work out well." The two companies announced the deal on Monday. Loews shares rose to a record. The main properties being acquired are located in the Permian Basin in Texas, the Black Warrior Basin in Alabama and the Antrim Shale in Michigan, with estimated reserves of about 2.5 trillion cubic feet of gas. The price equates to about $1.61 per thousand cubic feet, Loews said. Loews Chief Executive James Tisch, whose billionaire family runs New York-based company, has been looking for ways to deploy some $5.5 billion in cash. Loews, the majority owner of natural gas pipeline operator Boardwalk Pipeline Partners LP and Diamond Offshore Drilling Inc. , plans to set up a new company for the acquired assets. It also will keep existing management, led by Timothy Parker, a Dominion senior vice president of exploration and production. Natural gas "will be a fuel of choice for years to come (as) we move into a world that is worried about global warming and greenhouse gases," Tisch said on a conference call. "We're seeing a reserve base in the United States that is, at best, staying flat, and we're seeing reduced importing of natural gas from Canada," he added. "If prices just stay where they are, we'll do very well with this investment." Richmond, Virginia-based Dominion is also selling other U.S. gas and oil operations to XTO Energy Inc. for $2.5 billion as it focuses on its power business. Loews expects a third-quarter closing. It said it may obtain bank loans, but not sell public debt, at the subsidiary level to help fund the acquisition. "This acquisition will further diversify Loews' holdings and reduce its concentration of cash flow from tobacco operations," Standard & Poor's credit analyst Rick Joy wrote. Loews' businesses include financial, tobacco, energy, hotel and watch-making. It said it owns 75 percent of Boardwalk, 51 percent of Diamond, 89 percent of insurer CNA Financial Corp. , and all of tobacco company Lorillard Inc., Loews Hotels and watchmaker Bulova Corp. Loews shares were up $1, or 2 percent, at $52.02 in afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Their previous high was $51.50, set on May 31. The shares began the year at $41.47. Back to News Home
