http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi%3Ff%3D/c/a/2007/06/04/BAGADQ79FB9.DTL&cid No explanation yet for why Southwest jet's landing gear collapsed No explanation yet for why Southwest jet's landing gear collapsed Marisa Lagos, Chronicle Staff Writers Monday, June 4, 2007 (06-04) 11:45 PDT OAKLAND -- Officials for Southwest Airlines and the federal government were at Oakland International Airport today trying to figure out why the landing gear in a Boeing 737 collapsed in an emergency landing Sunday afternoon. None of the 119 passengers and crew members on board the flight, which was headed from Sacramento to San Diego, was injured. The runway where the jet made its landing was reopened at 5:45 a.m., 15 minutes ahead of schedule, and flights were on time today, airport spokeswoman Cyndy Johnson said, adding that the plane involved in Sunday's incident had been moved off the runway and onto another area of the airfield. More details began to emerge today about what happened during the emergency landing. Officials said that Southwest Flight 3050 departed Sacramento International Airport at 1:52 p.m. As the plane was en route to San Diego -- and was in fact closer to the Southern California city than to Oakland -- the pilots observed an indicator light showing a problem with the nose landing gear of the plane, said Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Ian Gregor. Gregor was unsure why the pilots opted to return to Northern California rather than land in San Diego or another airport. "The indicator light went on in cockpit, saying there might be something wrong," said Johnson. "It's not unlike a car -- sometimes the lights go on, and they are either alerting you to something wrong or they are malfunctioning." The pilots diverted the flight to Oakland and informed the passengers that there was an "issue" that needed to be checked. Meanwhile, the plane flew over San Francisco Bay as the pilots tried to get the landing gear to work properly, according to Southwest. Gregor said the pilots flew over Oakland Airport three times to test the landing gear and have officials in the air traffic control tower visually inspect the gear. During the first flyover, he said, the main landing gear under the wings appeared to be cocked to the side at a 45-degree angle instead of being pointed straight down. "They did it again, and the landing gear appeared to be in order," he said. "During the third flyby, they were still in order." Gregor said at that point, the pilot told the control tower that he had three green lights, indicating that all three of the plane's landing gear mechanisms, two under the wings and one under the nose, were working properly. "Everything appeared in order, and they landed and touched down," he said. "There was a shower of sparks, and the full emergency response." Beth Harbin, a spokeswoman for Southwest Airlines, said the landing gear collapsed but did not break off. "Essentially, what happened, the airplane landed on its main gear, at the back of the aircraft," Johnson said. "They went down a little ways and put the nose down, and essentially the nose gear collapsed. They traveled down the runway for a little bit of time before the plane stopped." None of the officials who spoke with The Chronicle today knew exactly how far the plane slid before stopping, but officials said Sunday that it most likely continued moving for a while, as planes are traveling at more than 100 mph when they land. The plane ended up resting nose-down and at an angle on the runway -- with its tail appearing to stick out over the runway edge. An emergency slide was deployed on one side of the plane, and 114 passengers and 5 crew members were evacuated safely. Officials said they were still in the process of determining whether the Federal Transportation Safety Board would investigate the emergency landing. The FTSB only investigates accidents, not situations deemed "incidents," Gregor said. "It's unclear whether it rises to the level of accident," he said. "There are incidents and there are accidents, and it depends on how much damage occurs." Gregor said FAA officials were inspecting the plane, looking at maintenance records and talking to the crew to see whether they will hand off the inquiry to the NTSB. A spokeswoman for Southwest said that airline officials were at the scene and conducting their own investigation. Johnson said Oakland airport would not investigate the emergency landing, but will conduct an internal inquiry of its response to the situation. "(The airport) will be evaluating how well we responded to the incident and use it as a learning experience so we can improve our response in case something like this happens again," she said. Records show that the plane has experienced some problems with landing gear in the past. On Aug. 20, 1994, the same plane made an unscheduled landing after taking off from Los Angeles International Airport, according to FAA records. Pilots were unable to raise the gear after takeoff and had to use an override handle to do so, records indicate. The plane returned to the airport and made an "uneventful landing;" mechanics readjusted a cable in the main gear. Sunday's incident had little impact on other travelers, Johnson said. "For the most part, we just have arrivals in the evening, and because of the additional runways at the north field location, it's just a few extra minutes of taxiing to send an aircraft over to an alternate runway," she said. "The delays were minimal -- we can't even call them delays." Harbin said the pilots were in the midst of a standard debriefing process today and were being made available to the FAA and NTSB as needed. Gregor praised the pilots' response to the emergency. "Pilots are trained in simulators to deal with situations like this. It's something they practice all the time," he said. "Obviously the pilot did exactly what he or she should have done." It is "certainly not a common" occurrence for landing gear to fail, he said. "To have a suspected problem isn't that unusual, but for it to collapse, it's not unheard of but it's rare," he said. Staff writers Tanya Schevitz and Henry K. Lee contributed to this report. E-mail the writers at Get up to 50% off home delivery of the Chronicle for 12 weeks! Garbage truck backs up, kills Sausalito restaurant employee Familiar name back on city payroll with new job Enhanced romance The G-Shot -- Is it the latest panacea to improve your... No explanation yet for why Southwest jet&#x27;s landing gear collapsed 2 hospitalized in SoMa stabbing Paris Hilton Checks Into L.A. Jail THE BADGE The two cops who know all the gang members Enhanced romance The G-Shot -- Is it the latest panacea to improve your... THE NIGHTMARE OF GETTING THERE Surge in applications has created a... ON THE JOB Quitters sometimes win: Jumping ship in order to clean them Southwest flight&#x27;s gear collapses on landing at Oakland airport SAN FRANCISCO Woman hit and killed in crosswalk on 19th Ave. IN JOHN MUIR&#x27;S FOOTSTEPS Santa Cruz couple retrace famed naturalist&#x27;s 1868... Familiar name back on city payroll with new job THE BADGE The two cops who know all the gang members &#x27;No intention of resigning,&#x27; vows S.F. Supervisor Ed Jew Guantanamo Judge Dismisses Terror Case Polish Girl&#x27;s Holocaust Diary Unveiled Indiana Kangaroo Dies After Capture Deputies arrest man after Dana Point knife attacks E. coli fear spurs ground beef recall at Albertsons, Save-A-Lot SOS Security Inc . Immediate OF CALIFORNIA DEPARTMENT OF Sales Manager Will train right RN CASE MANAGER Chinese Community if you are looking for a modern San Mateo County Office of Education 1000 HIRING BONUS Deliver small The California Dept. of Corrections & Rehab. Not just a career, but a way of life. City of Walnut Creek Office. SF, B.A . in management FABRICATION Layout - Custom Sheet View All Top Jobs &copy; 2007 Hearst Communications Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-0&fd=R&url=http://news.zdnet.com/2100-3513_22-6188457.html&cid=1116959869&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Yahoo opens Panama search ad platform | Tech News on ZDNet Yahoo opens Panama search ad platform June 4, 2007, 7:03 AM PT Yahoo announced Monday that its Panama search advertising platform is now open to third parties. Under Panama, which was launched in February, sponsored search results are based on items such as relevancy and not just on the advertiser's bid price. Yahoo Search Marketing Commercial API Program , both businesses and individual developers have access to a series of application program interfaces (APIs) so that they can tweak the Panama platform to suit their individual needs. The company is offering three levels of partnership, ranging from a free "basic" deal for small advertising agencies and technology companies, to "advanced" and "elite" levels with varying subscription rates. All participants in the Panama APIs, regardless of partnership level, have access to the software platform and any related technical support. Advanced partners also have account management support and a listing in Yahoo's partner directory. Elite partners, according to Yahoo, can "leverage the Panama platform, resources and brand via regular business review, product council, road map coordination and joint marketing activities." The inaugural Elite partners in the API program include SearchIgnite, Efficient Frontier, Omniture and The Search Agency. Yahoo launched Panama earlier this year as a direct competitor to Google's successful advertising programs. So far, Panama's biggest success has been a deal with to provide sponsored search and contextual ads to 33 of its entertainment sites. Viacom, meanwhile, is famously at odds with Google over a billion-dollar copyright infringement lawsuit over YouTube video clips. In another strategic move to bolster its place in the online advertising market, Yahoo purchased ad exchange Right M