K.N: Consent orders were reached with state officials requiring the the divestiture of three additional stores. Rite Aid, the No. 3 U.S. drugstore chain, said the Jean Coutu Group had received $2.36 billion in cash, subject to a working capital adjustment, and 250 million shares of Rite Aid common stock in the transaction. Rite Aid said it expects a net loss for fiscal 2008 because of integration expenses, but the company also expects nine months of acquisition-related cost savings of approximately $155 million. The acquisition gives Rite Aid more than 5,000 stores, making it a closer rival to the leading U.S. drugstores, Walgreen and CVS Corp. (CVS.N: ((Reporting by Peter Kaplan, editing by Tim Dobbyn; Reuters Messaging: peter.kaplan.reuters.com@reuters.net; e-mail: peter.kaplan@reuters.com; +1 202 898 8463, fax: +1 202 898-8383)) Keywords: ECKERD RITEAID/ (C) Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Republication or redistribution ofReuters content, including by caching, framing or similar means, is expresslyprohibited without the prior written consent of Reuters. Reuters and the Reuterssphere logo are registered trademarks and trademarks of the Reuters group ofcompanies around the world.nN04484580 &copy; Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Editors Choice: Best pictures from the last 24 hours. Acquisitions by Rite Aid get antitrust approval START News Content Page Tags 'Text' | 'Picture' | 'Slideshow' | 'Video' ie. headline for article ie. headline for article END News Content Page Tags In quotes: Subprime fallout The stories behind the deals and the deal-makers as seen and heard by Reuters reporters covering mergers & acquisitions and Wall Street. Deals of the Day: Read the latest headlines Rounding up the papers UPDATE 3-US court rejects FCC broadcast decency rule UPDATE 1-Two ex-Putnam managers settle SEC trading charges UPDATE 2-Chemotherapy pill successful for prostate cancer Top Company Research Reports on Reuters.com Qantas Airways Ltd. [QAN] Globalstar IPO Update