r in which each remaining untendered share of Accredited will be converted into the same $15.10 cash per share price paid in the tender offer. The tender offer is expected to commence within ten business days, unless extended. Subject to customary closing conditions, the transaction is expected to close in the third quarter of this year. The tender offer is not subject to a financing contingency. Meanwhile, the 9.75% Series A Perpetual Cumulative Preferred Shares, par value $1.00 per share of Accredited Mortgage Loan REIT Trust will continue to remain outstanding. Commenting on the deal, James Konrath, CEO of Accredited, said, "After a careful analysis, we believe this agreement is the best alternative available to protect shareholder value and provide the capital we need to support the company's business over the long-term. In Lone Star, we have found a partner who has a record of helping companies like ours successfully address financial and operational challenges." Accredited's Board, on the unanimous recommendation of a Special Committee composed entirely of independent directors, has unanimously approved the transaction. The acquisition will be effected pursuant to a merger agreement. In connection with this deal, Accredited got the financial advise from Bear, Stearns & Co. Inc., Friedman, Billings, Ramsey Group Inc. and Houlihan Lokey Howard & Zukin, while Dewey Ballantine LLP and Morris, Nichols, Arsht & Tunnel LLP were its legal advisors. Bear, Stearns & Co. Inc. and Houlihan Lokey Howard & Zukin each rendered fairness opinion on the deal to Accredited's Special Committee. Lone Star is represented in the transaction by its financial advisor Piper Jaffray & Co., and its legal counsel, Sullivan & Cromwell LLP. Many home loan providers, including, Accredited has been suffering with rising losses, mounting defaults. Subprime specialists, who offer loans at higher interest rates to homebuyers with blemished credit histories, have watched their stocks nose dive, gone on the sale block, posted hefty losses, exited business or declared bankruptcy. Recently, U.S. subprime lender New Century Financial Corp. (NEWCQ.PK) warned in a filing that all of its lenders have discontinued their short-term funding or notified the company of their intent to do so. In May, the San Diego, California-based Accredited delayed filing its audited first-quarter report and also expects a "significant loss" for the quarter compared to net income of $35.8 million for the comparable period in 2006. The company noted its first quarter results will be affected by losses on loan dispositions and expenses associated with higher delinquencies and cost restructuring initiatives. The company cut 1,300 of its 4,200 jobs in the first quarter. About Lone Star Funds Lone Star is a U.S. private equity firm. Since 1995, the principals of Lone Star have organized private equity funds totaling more than $13.3 billion to invest globally in corporate secured and unsecured debt instruments, real estate related assets and select corporate opportunities. Accredited is currently up $1.47 or 10.68% and trading at $15.23. For the past one-year, the stock has been trading in range of $3.77 - $51.35. Flextronics To Buy Solectron In $3.6 Bln Cash And Stock Deal - Update Cray Trims FY07 Forecast; Expects Not To Achieve Profitability Due To Estimated Lower Revenue; Shares Fall - Update Noble Announces Probe Of Nigerian Operations - Update Laureate Education Accepts Sweetened $3.82 Bln Cash Offer From CEO-led Investor Group - Update Krispy Kreme Q1 Loss Widens On Costs; Revenues Decline 7% - Update Copyright &copy; 2007 RealTimeTraders.com, Inc. All rights reserved. By using this site, you agree to the Terms of Service How To Use RTTNews.com
