d downloading songs, videos and games, they did not enjoy paying their bills. In May, it concluded that as many as 80,000 of its subscribers were likely to be &#8220;non-paying customers,&#8221; according to a document filed Monday with the court. Amp&#8217;d also cited a dispute with Verizon, its wireless network carrier, as a reason it landed in Chapter 11 protection. Other investors in Amp&#8217;d are The Red Herringâ€™s Cassimir Medford wrote Monday that at least one analyst believes that investors â€œwill be taking a much more skeptical view of startups that resell mobile services.â€ Such skepticism may have served investors better earlier on, notes Matt Marshall of VentureBeat, who on Sunday wrote an I-told-you-so post about Amp&#8217;d Mobile&#8217;s â€œspectacular crash.â€ To raise so much cash was risky &#8212; as weâ€™d pointed out back in March, when Ampâ€™d had raised its last $107 million &#8212; because other such networks have struggled. ESPNâ€™s network, for example, shut down. These so-called â€œmobile virtual network operatorsâ€ are tough to pull off because they donâ€™t own their own spectrum, but resell services using the network of other mobile phone operators. Branding is hard to create, given the dominance of established carriers. , has not made a profit in five years and has accumulated $553 million in debt, according to the Herring. But, the Herring notes, despite the sectorâ€™s â€œgloomy outlook,â€ venture firms including recently invested $12.7 million in a second round for , a company that leases spectrum from big wireless carriers and rebrands it for other companies and organizations. Go to Article from The Red Herring Â» Go to Item from VentureBeat Â» Go to Previous Item from DealBook Â» Required (will not be published) Comments are moderated and will be posted if they are on-topic and not abusive. They may be edited for length and clarity. For more information see our Is Dow Jones&#8217;s Union Pursuing an ESOP? Loews to Acquire Gas As