ing last month because of the cost of signing up new players. The company stopped taking bets in the US following the ban and has had to work furiously to rebuild its customer base elsewhere. It said yesterday it was too early to assess how talks with US authorities would end. Separately, online payment firm Neteller told the market it had agreed to a plan for US customers to access money in their accounts for the first time since its funds were frozen in February. Also on Guardian Unlimited business Andrew Clark on America Send it to a friend Join our dating site today Guardian Unlimited &copy; Guardian News and Media Limited 2007
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-3&fd=R&url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/04/AR2007060400520.html%3Fhpid%3Dtopnews&cid=1116962805&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Court Backs Firms on Credit Notification - washingtonpost.com Find Bars & Clubs View a Sample and Sign Up Today's Headlines & Columnists Daily Politics News & Analysis Obama Starts Throwing Elbows House Majority Leader Tom DeLay Indicted Court Backs Firms on Credit Notification Monday, June 4, 2007; 5:07 PM WASHINGTON -- The Supreme Court ruled in favor of two large insurers Monday, limiting the circumstances under which companies must tell customers their credit ratings are affecting the amount they pay. The justices said Geico General Insurance Co. did not violate the Fair Credit Reporting Act and that Safeco Insurance Co. of America might have, but did not do so recklessly. In Today's A Section More in Today's Print Edition Save & Share Article Consumer groups point to the notification requirement as the cornerstone to cleansing credit reports of inaccurate information. The case has significant implications for pending class-action lawsuits seeking billions of dollars in punitive damages on behalf of consumers who say they should have been notified, but weren't. In order for a company to be found liable, its conduct must entail an unjustifiably high risk of harm that is either known to a company or is so obvious that it should have been known, wrote Justice David Souter. "It's not a great decision for consumers, but there are some silver linings," said Scott Shorr, a Portland, Ore., attorney representing plaintiffs in the case against Safeco and Geico. The court ruled that the law's notification requirements apply to initial applicants, which means new customers will be informed when their credit scores affect the rates they're being quoted. But the court overturned an appeals court ruling that would have required notification of the vast majority of customers. Notification would have been the rule unless consumers were paying the very lowest rate offered to those with the very best credit ratings. Under such an expansive notification standard, Safeco would have been required to notify 80 percent of its new customers, while at Geico, just 10 percent of new customers qualify for the top tier of credit, lawyers representing the companies say. The court agreed with Geico's approach, which was to compare the rate a customer is being offered with the rate that would be charged if the company had not taken the credit score into account. The companies lost on their contention that in order to be found liable for a willful violation, it must be shown that they knew they were breaking the law. The court said "reckless disregard" was sufficient. But the justices laid down a restrictive definition. The court's ruling on the liability question was unanimous, while the decision on notification was 7-2. Putin Cautions U.S. Over Missile Defense Plans Putin Attacks West Ahead of G-8 Summit Jury Seated for Trial in '60s Killings Appeals Court Hands Broadcasters a Win Related Topics & Web Content Top 35 Most Viewed &copy; 2007 The Associated Press Refinance Rates As Low As 2.9% - FREE QUOTES! $300,000 Mortgage for $965&frasl;mo! Refinance & Save $1,000's! Be Prepared. Fight Identity Theft! Equifax.com. $425,000 Loan for only $1,417&frasl;mo. NO SSN REQUIRED! $599,000 Loan for only $1,997&frasl;mo. NO SSN REQUIRED! Cool Gadgets, Great Deals, Visit CircuitCity.com Try Email Marketing with Constant Contact dell_ran = Math.floor(Math.random() * 1000000); document.write(' The Washington Post Store The Washington Post Company: Information and Other Post Co. Websites 1996- The Washington Post Company User Agreement and Privacy Policy
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-6&fd=R&url=http://www.9news.com/news/article.aspx%3Fstoryid%3D71329&cid=1116887572&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg 9NEWS - Article - Crime rates rising in western states School & Business Closings Leader of the Year AS SEEN ON 9NEWS Crime rates rising in western states created: 6/4/2007 1:06:31 PM Last updated: 6/4/2007 1:08:14 PM Set 9NEWS as your homepage WASHINGTON - The FBI says the overall crime rates in the nation are going up with western states showing the largest increase. The recently released numbers show the western region of the United States rising 2.8 percent in violent crime. Throughout the nation the homicide rates rose slightly and robberies increasing by six percent. The FBI numbers were released just as the US Justice Department began a push to give more money to local police and send more federal agents to troubled cities. Despite the difficulties, Attorney General Alberta Gonzales says cracking down on violent crime will be one of his top priorities before the Bush administration leaves office at the end of 2008. (Copyright KUSA*TV, All Rights Reserved. The Associated Press contributed to this report.) Visit 9NEWS.com Story Chat 9NEWS.com Story Chat Disclaimer Man reels in record fish - June 04, 2007 Parents of man with TB support his decision to fly back to the US - June 04, 2007 Man sentenced for giving marijuana to 5-year-old - June 04, 2007 John Ramsey and mother of missing teen girl have special friendship - June 04, 2007 Colorado man drowns in Wyoming reservoir - June 04, 2007 Police search for driver in crash that killed woman - June 04, 2007 - June 04, 2007 5-year-old girl burned in apartment fire - June 04, 2007 Top Stories on 9NEWS.com Teen finds 'time capsule' buried in Grandma's garden Email this to a friend 3 arrested in massive high school food fight Email this to a friend Man reels in record fish Email this to a friend 7,000 turn out for bike ride; see Gov. sign bike plate bill Email this to