MC shareholders 21%. But for this roughly 25% increase in its issued equity, sxr is lifting its target annual production profile for 2013 by more than 50% to 28m lb, of which EMC will contribute a disproportionate 11m lb. This reflects the fact that, though sxr is offering a 28% premium to EMC&#39;s pre-bid share price, the market priced EMC&#39;s resource base at the equivalent of only $4.28/lb, one of the lowest valuations in the sector. By contrast, the present biggest producer, Cameco, has a production target of 27m lb by 2011. Of course, that could still increase in the ensuing two years; but then, the latest deal doesn&#39;t exhaust sxr&#39;s ambitions, either. At today&#39;s briefing, VP Jean Nortier said that while sxr would probably only be interested in "consolidating" its interests in the three areas - Kazakhstan, the US and SA - where it is now well represented, it would like to "balance" its portfolio in the other two major uranium provinces, Canada and Australia, where its only interest is the relatively minor Honeymoon property in South Australia. Of the EMC properties, the Hobson facility in South Texas should come into production next year, with the first output in Wyoming following two years later, in 2010. The use of EMC material should also allow sxr&#39;s Shootaring mill, in neighbouring Utah, to start producing that year, two years earlier than originally planned. Virtually all the EMC production is expected to cost less than $20/lb . sxr agrees with a recent study that suggests that the price, now just over $130/lb, could hit at least $155. Nortier added that sxr has contracts to sell almost all that 2013 production of 28m lb. Forward sales aren&#39;t hedged, but contracts provide for a price equal to the spot price at the time of delivery, with a minimum floor price but no ceiling. Meanwhile, trial production started at sxr&#39;s Dominion Reefs project in SA in April, and is said to be going well. Production at the first UrAsia project in Kazakhstan, Akdala, is also building up ahead of budget and generating "significant" cash flow, which is being re-invested in the four times bigger South Inkai project, where production should start in the first quarter of this year. With all this good news, you wonder why the notional market cap of the combined sxr/EMC is dwarfed by Cameco&#39;s, of about $21bn. Fact is, of sxr&#39;s handsome claimed resource base, only a small proportion falls into the "proven and probable" category. Not only Cameco, but smaller rivals like Paladin and Australia&#39;s ERA, have higher "proven and probable" reserves. Sxr may be confident that it can prove up its reserves, but until it actually does so the share price will always be discounted, to some extent. 0.5% of your home loan back in upfront rewards vouchers. Click here to apply make new .net version: include virtual="/commonmmx/articles/comments.inc" A E C I Information supplied by McGregor BFA Make FIN24 my home page
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-3&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/accredited-home-agrees-lone-stars/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257BFF29A4A9-65CC-43F0-9B7B-443A73559288%257D&cid=1116959363&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Accredited Home agrees to Lone Star's $400 million offer - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Lone Star to buy Accredited Home Private-equity firm to pay $400 million for subprime lender Last Update: 12:48 PM ET Jun 4, 2007 SAN FRANCISCO (MarketWatch) -- Accredited Home Lenders said Monday that it's agreed to be acquired by private-equity firm Lone Star Funds for $400 million, thus becoming the latest subprime originator to sell itself. Lone Star will buy Accredited's shares for $15.10 each in cash, a 10% premium to the company's closing price on June 1. The 9.75% Series A perpetual cumulative preferred shares of Accredited Mortgage Loan REIT Trust will remain outstanding, Accredited said. Accredited shares rose as much as 12% and changed hands at $15.39, up $1.63, during afternoon trading. Subprime mortgages are offered to poorer home buyers with blemished credit records. Rising interest rates and flat house prices have sparked a jump in delinquencies and foreclosures. That in turn has touched off a rash of bankruptcies among originators such as New Century Financial . Many analysts predicted earlier this year that few subprime lenders will remain independent after the crisis in the sector subsides. "This agreement is the best alternative available to protect shareholder value and provide the capital we need," said James Konrath, chief executive of San Diego-based Accredited , in a statement. "In Lone Star, we have found a partner who has a record of helping companies like ours successfully address financial and operational challenges." Lone Star has raised more than $13 billion to invest in corporate debt, real estate and acquisitions. The firm has also invested in non-performing loans and notes on its Web site that what it called the banking system's tendency to "cyclically over-finance and then under-finance" the property business and other sectors presents investment opportunities. "We are confident that Accredited can successfully manage through the current industry dynamics and leverage the platform," said Len Allen, president of Lone Star Funds' U.S. operations, in a statement. Alistair Barr is a reporter for MarketWatch in San Francisco. Related Blog Posts & Articles Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Sign up to receive the Weekend TV Show Preview U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 U.S. stock futures drop with bond yield rise, China in focus Five little-known tips for getting better gas mileage Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Three safe havens to stash your cash Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Palm sells stake to Elevation; former Apple execs join ranks Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Three safe havens to stash your cash Who has the hot hand? Flextronics to acquire Solectron for $3.6 bln DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 Telecom firm Avaya reportedly close to private-equity deal Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 More equity hedge funds are shorting ETFs rather than stocks Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on