d it had a very high chance of a favourable outcome?â€ said one analyst. Analysts pointed to rival Sportingbetâ€™s deal with the State of Louisiana in March when warrants for Peter Dicks were dropped and the company made a reported payment of $400,000 to settle the case against its former chairman. They said they thought PartyGaming would expect to be reasonably confident of being able to agree a financial settlement that would not be too onerous. There appears to have been a change in sentiment in the US since last October when the government passed the Unlawful Internet Gambling Enforcement Act which outlawed online gambling. Since then there have been fears that online gambling rather than stopping has gone underground. PartyGaming stopped any US based customers having access to its website when the act was passed but there is still uncertainty over the legal position on online gaming before the Act was passed, a risk PartyGaming highlighted in its prospectus when it floated two years ago. When the Act was passed, PartyGaming lost three-quarters of its customers who were US-based and its share price plunged along with those of other companies in the sector. Richard Carter, analyst at Numis Securities, said in a note to clients, â€œthere now appears a willingness on behalf of the US Attorneyâ€™s Office to settle and draw a line under the uncertainty caused by recent DoJ actions towards online gaming companies that participated in the US prior to the enactment of the UIEGAâ€. There has been some recovery in share prices in recent months as speculation mounted that the mood in the US was changing. Partygaming shares, which slumped to 25Â½p following the US ban, have recovered in recent months. On Monday morning fell 0.5 per cent to 41p. The uncertainty has made PartyGaming unattractive to potential bidders, but if it were removed, analysts said, an approach could come from companies such as MGM or Harrahâ€™s. Alternatively, a recovery in PartyGamingâ€™s share price might allow it to make bids for other companies as the sector consolidates. Also if the US did change the law to allow online gambling, a settlement with the Department of Justice would permit PartyGaming to return to the market. The Financial Times Limited 2007 - create a keyword alert on the subject of this topic - download our application to receive instant alerts on this topic - start your day with daily email briefing on this topic - Track this news topic using our feeds "Middle East" sub navigation "By sector" sub navigation "By region" sub navigation "Markets headlines" sub navigation "Market data" sub navigation Australia & New Zealand "Managed funds" sub navigation "Comment & Analysis" sub navigation Comment & Analysis main "Debates and polls" sub navigation Debates and polls main "Video & Audio" sub navigation Video & Audio main View from the Top "Business Life" sub navigation "Business education" sub navigation Features of the week "Your Money" sub navigation "Advice & comment" sub navigation Advice & comment main "Compare & apply" sub navigation Compare & apply main "Arts & Weekend" sub navigation Arts & Weekend main How to spend it "Weekend columnists" sub navigation "In depth" sub navigation "Special Reports" sub navigation Future of Europe 2007 "Jobs & classified" sub navigation Jobs & classified main "Services & tools" sub navigation Services & tools main "News tracking" sub navigation Minimum delay 15 minutes All times are London time Advertise with the FT The Financial Times Ltd 2007. "FT" and "Financial Times" are trademarks of The Financial Times Ltd. Type your search criteria below: BGH International Pty Ltd TREASURER â€“ FOOD DIVISION BGH International Pty Ltd FINANCIAL ADMINISTRATOR / BURSAR FT.com can deliver talented individuals across all industries around the world Post a job now Retailer Of Oriental/Decorative Carpets Edinburgh, Lothian, United Kingdom Printers With Spare Capacity? Traditional Silversmiths Plant and Equipment Sheffield, S