http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-2&fd=R&url=http://www.dailytech.com/Flextronics%2Bto%2BAcquire%2BSolectron%2Bin%2B36B%2BDeal/article7539c.htm&cid=1116957571&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg DailyTech - Flextronics to Acquire Solectron in $3.6B Deal Flextronics to Acquire Solectron in $3.6B Deal June 4, 2007 3:39 PM comment(s) - last by Please input the letters/numbers that appear in the image below. (not case-sensitive) Microsoft contracts Flextronics to make Xbox 360 components (Source: Xbox-Scene) Electronics manufacturing giant Flextronics swallows Solectron Electronics manufacturer Flextronics International Ltd. said today that it will acquire Solectron Corporation in a multi-billion dollar deal. Under the terms of the definitive agreement, unanimously approved by the boards of directors of both companies, shareholders of Solectron will receive total consideration currently valued at approximately $3.6 billion, based on the closing price of Flextronics ordinary shares on June 1, 2007. "By joining forces, we expect the increased scale will enable us to further extend our market segment reach and leverage an increased vertical integration opportunity, realize significant cost savings, and better serve the needs of our combined customers, employees and shareholders," said Mike McNamara, CEO of Flextronics. Operating in 35 countries, with a combined workforce of approximately 200,000 employees, including approximately 4,000 design engineers, the combined company's annual revenues will exceed $30 billion across seven diversified customer market segments and several vertical component divisions. "We believe Flextronics has the large scale integration expertise and systems infrastructure capable of successfully integrating and managing the combined company to ensure all of the significant synergies are realized," said Paul Tufano, executive VP and interim CEO of Solectron. "Moreover, with the significant stock component offered in the transaction, Solectron's shareholders have a meaningful opportunity to participate in the realization of that value." Thomas J. Smach, CFO of Flextronics, says about the dollars and cents of the deal, "While some synergies will be achieved in the first 12 months after closing, it could take up to 18-24 months to fully integrate this acquisition and realize the full synergy potential, which we estimate to be at least $200 million after tax." The acquisition is expected to close by the end of calendar year 2007. Until the acquisition is completed, both companies will continue to operate their businesses independently. Marcus, I really like your stories, you post some great happenings. However, this must be the fourth or fifth time I've asked, Link the .pdf press release: I don't see why it is necessary to state sources in a news article. I don't see most other sites or other types of publications doing the same, and you can so quickly search for more information using a web search engine that knowing the exact source the author was using is unnecessary, in my opinion. Time to sell all my Solectron stock! ...buying all these American companies. Keep **American** jobs in America. Thank the Bushsquad for another economic f_ckup! This wouldn't happen if the government owned all companies, you know. ;) This happens all over the world. Allot of Swedish companies have been and are being bought by American. A very good example is Volvo which used to represent everything Swedish. Is now since some time ago owned by an American company. Other examples are Astrazeneca and Pfizer (I think). It's nothing personal it's business they used to say. the problems are with the corporation... the Bush squad has done more to try to keep more business in the states as this is where their paycheck comes from. The real problem was the previous administration outsourcing much of the American workforce. LOL, are you kidding - blaming the Clinton Administration?!? No, you must be referring to the Bush Administration in his