http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-3&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/04/america/NA-GEN-US-Crime.php&cid=1116887572&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Violent crime increasing in US, FBI reports - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings Violent crime increasing in US, FBI reports Published: June 4, 2007 The murder rate rose slightly in the United States last year, but the number of robberies skyrocketed by 6 percent, preliminary FBI data released Monday show. The statistics were part of an overall 1.3 percent rise in violent crime across the country in 2006, the second consecutive annual increase. Car thefts, arsons and other property crimes dipped for a second straight year, the data show. The modest increase in murders reflected a mixed bag for cities. The number of homicides in major metropolitan areas &#8212; those with at least 1 million residents &#8212; climbed by 6.7 percent. Smaller cities, meanwhile, saw their murders decrease by a collective 11.9 percent. The spike in robberies marked the largest increase in any category of crime surveyed in the FBI report, which was compiled with data from more than 11,700 law enforcement agencies nationwide. Huge setback to Bush&#x27;s military tribunals at Guant&#xE1;namo Efficient adoption system attracts American couples to Ethiopia JFK plot was short on means and smarts Violent crime rose in every region of the country except for the Northeast, the FBI reported. Western states saw the largest jump in violent crime, by 2.8 percent, the data show. The new numbers come amid a Justice Department push to tamp down violent crime with millions of dollars distributed to local police forces and a surge of federal agents to troubled cities. Attorney General Alberto Gonzales, who took office as violent crime started to rise, has called the crackdown one of his top priorities for the remaining 18 months of his tenure at the Justice Department. In a spot of good news, violent crime grew at a slower pace than had been expected. In December, the FBI projected a 3.7 percent increase for the first six months of 2006. The year before, in 2005, violent crime rose by 2.3 percent. Property crimes decreased overall by 2.9 percent from 2005, the FBI reported. Burglaries, however, rose slightly, particularly in mid-sized cities where the rate grew by 3.3 percent. The FBI&#039;s 2006 preliminary Uniform Crime Report can be found at: Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; Corruption in China: The anger boils over Chinese drug commissioner is sentenced to death Understanding and coping with tremors An escapee tells of life and death in North Korea&#39;s labor camps Malaysia rejects Muslim convert&#39;s bid to be recognized as Christian A rare glimpse of 19th-century Iran With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Genes take charge, and diets fall by the wayside U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Tracing a poison&#39;s global path back to China Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation Do not neglect culture In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy The assault on Assyrian Christians No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; IHT.c