http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-5&fd=R&url=http://www.thestar.com/Business/article/221301&cid=1116567986&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg TheStar.com - Business - Trump not expected at Black trial: Lawyers Full Text Article Archive TheStar.com - Business - Trump not expected at Black trial: Lawyers Trump not expected at Black trial: Lawyers 2002 Black memo (.pdf) CP Video: Radler testimony, day 2 CP Video: Radler's first day Photos: Camera hits Amiel Black: In his own words Trial exhibits (DOJ site) Photos: Setting the scene A Conrad Black timeline Text of U.S. indictment (.pdf) Graphic: The trial (Flash) Video: Boxes episode, caught on tape Crime sheet: Lawyer's black trial blog Jun 04, 2007 05:06 PM CHICAGO â€“ Media mogul Conrad Black furnished his Park Avenue apartment in lavish fashion including a US$12,000 commode and a $17,000 built-in music system, his racketeering and fraud trial heard Monday. The description of plush furnishings in Black's apartment on New York's Upper East Side came as an expected appearance by real estate tycoon Donald Trump as a witness for the defence failed to materialize. Lawyers indicated that contrary to widespread reports circulating since last Friday, Trump wouldn't be called to the stand at the 12-week trial which is going into its final few days. Defence attorneys instead called Lee Williams, a former federal tax agent, who said his investigation showed that Black plunged $4.6 million into refurbishing the luxury co-op apartment â€“ double the amount prosecutors say can be proven. They also indicated they wanted to call Black's longtime associate David Radler, who worked with Black for more than 30 years but took the stand against him last month in exchange for a lenient sentence after pleading guilty to one count of fraud. Black, 62, and three other former executives of the Hollinger International newspaper empire are charged with swindling the company out of millions of dollars, largely through the sale of assets. Purchasers of hundreds of Hollinger community newspapers across the United States and Canada paid the company not to go into competition with them. Black and fellow executives got much of the money, which federal prosecutors say should have gone to shareholders. Black is also charged with bilking the company by taking the Hollinger jet on a vacation to Bora Bora in French Polynesia, billing shareholders $42,000 for his wife's birthday party at New York's swank restaurant La Grenouille and transactions involving the apartment. Black's defence attorneys have maintained that the birthday party was partially a business function and thus Hollinger should have picked up at least part of the tab. In fact, Black paid one-third and billed two-thirds of the cost of the party to the newspaper company. Trump, who was negotiating with Hollinger to buy the Chicago Sun-Times building at the time, was among the guests at the party and might have been expected to testify there was a business component to the affair. Apartment furnishings also pointed to a lavish lifestyle. Besides a $12,000 "three-drawer" commode and the $17,000 music system, there were $4,399 towel-holder bars, $17,710 Indian white marble elephants, $9,800 Louis XVI painted stools, a 1920s Chinese carpet for $33,000 and a porcelain bottle that belonged to Napoleon Bonaparte on his campaign in Russia along with a mahogany shaving stand for $12,500. A diamond vault cost $12,000 and Black paid $828 for sofa pillows plus two yards of silk, according to the list. It also included a Brussels carpet that cost $3,255, a mother of pearl Persian box valued at $9,600 and a $9,750 plaque depicting Amazon women. Prosecutor Eric Sussman also noted a bill for travel by architects to Palm Beach, Fla., where Black has another home. "These same architects were actually doing work for Mr. Black on his place down in Palm Beach?" Sussman asked. Williams said the documents appeared to suggest that they were. How much Black paid for capital improvements, furnishings and decorations for the apartment which occupies the entire third floor of a vintage building not far from Central Park is in dispute at the trial. Black lived in the apartment owned by the Hollinger International newspaper group for six years rent free when he was the company's CEO. When shareholders started to grumble that they shouldn't pay his rent, Black bought the apartment for $3 million â€“ the amount Hollinger paid for it six years earlier. Prosecutors say Black scammed the company because the apartment's value skyrocketed in six years. An appraiser who testified as a prosecution witness said the apartment was worth $8.5 million. But Black's lawyers claim the improvements he paid for out of his own pocket made up for the difference â€“ making the value of those improvements a key point of dispute at the trial. On Monday, they said wanted another chance to question Radler, citing new evidence that he lied when he testified against Black and asking the Chicago court "to require the government to produce F. David Radler for examination in the defence case." While on the stand, Radler professed to be telling the truth, but Black lawyer Eddie Greenspan suggested it was ludicrous for Radler to claim he was not aware of one of his plea bargain's best features â€“ that he would serve his term in a Canadian prison and under Canadian law is likely to serve only six months. In his filing Monday, Black lawyer Marc Martin said Radler ``professed ignorance" about the possibility of serving his time in Canada, as well as "Canadian parole rules governing release of white-collar prisoners after service of one-sixth of a sentence." Black's lawyers have since unearthed evidence that Radler had contacted a leading Canadian parole lawyer before making his plea arrangement with U.S. prosecutors. "That Mr. Radler has had the leading Canadian parole lawyer on his legal team since November 2004 is probative of his bias, motive and interest in testifying for the government," the court filing said. "It also impeaches his claims of ignorance about Canadian surrender and parole rules." Horse, heiress and a hurdle Charities worthy of donations Great home delivery subscription deals here! More in the news Housing market to cool: Report TSX inches to record high Trump not expected at Black trial: Lawyers Uranium producer grows again with $1.6B deal Dundee REIT sells $2.4B of assets to GE Murdoch meets with Dow Jones shareholders Slower car sales dampen U.S. factory demand Electronics firms in $3.6B buyout deal View from the top MOST POPULAR ON THESTAR.COM Grieving families demand answers Man out of 19-year coma Horoscopes for Monday, June 4 Paris Hilton goes to jail Highrise fall kills toddler Interest sags in nude retreats Man out of 19-year coma Grieving families demand answers Napoleon's love letter found in laundry room What they got: June 2 Careers at the Star Pages of the Past Star Store & Photo Sales &copy; Copyright Toronto Star 1996-2007
