http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-1&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601103%26sid%3DaInU2j22L5os%26refer%3Dnews&cid=1116957983&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg , Jun 04 17:18 , Jun 04 22:18 , Jun 05 06:18 Australia & New Zealand Loews, XTO Buy Dominion&#39;s Onshore Oil, Gas Business (Update9) June 4 (Bloomberg) -- Loews Corp., the holding company controlled by New York&#39;s Tisch family, and XTO Energy Inc. agreed to buy most of Dominion Resources Inc.&#39;s onshore oil and gas properties in separate transactions valued at about $6.5 billion. Loews, the majority owner of Diamond Offshore Drilling Inc., will pay about $4 billion for Dominion&#39;s operations in west Texas, Michigan and Alabama, the companies said in a statement today. Oil and gas producer XTO, based in Fort Worth, Texas, is buying deposits in Utah, New Mexico, southern Colorado and Louisiana, for about $2.5 billion. The sale includes reserves equal to about 3.5 trillion cubic feet of gas, enough to supply New York State for three years. Richmond, Virginia-based Dominion, the second-largest U.S. utility owner, put the oil and gas business up for sale in November to reduce debt and buy back stock. ``We&#39;ve been looking at this business for a long time, kicking a lot of tires,&#39;&#39; Loews Chief Executive Officer James Tisch said in an interview. Loews will keep the management of the exploration and production unit, he said, and consider additional acquisitions. Dominion CEO Thomas Farrell II is selling the assets to concentrate on the higher-growth electric utility business. Farrell also said today that the company expects 2008 operating earnings of $6 a share and at least 4 percent to 6 percent average annual earnings growth. Eni SpA, Italy&#39;s largest oil company, agreed in April to buy Dominion&#39;s offshore Gulf of Mexico oil and gas reserves for $4.8 billion. Two Canadian energy trusts last week agreed to pay $583 million for Dominion&#39;s deposits in Canada. Loews said it is paying about $1.64 per thousand cubic feet of natural gas. That&#39;s a good price compared with other recent transactions at $2.50 to $3 per thousand cubic feet, SunTrust Robinson oil and gas analyst John Gerdes said in an interview. Executives at Loews already ``have a pretty good insight into this business&#39;&#39; because of their drilling company and involvement in pipelines, said Steven McSorley, an analyst at Cathay Financial in New York, who rates Loews shares ``neutral&#39;&#39; and doesn&#39;t own any. While the company is using much of its cash on this, more oil and gas acquisitions are possible, he said. The Dominion acquisition is the biggest transaction for Loews since at least 1995. Since 2003, Loews acquired Gulf South Pipeline for $1.1 billion and Texas Gas Transmission LLC for $1 billion. The company was formed in 1945 when brothers Laurence and Preston Robert Tisch took over their father&#39;s resort business and formed Tisch Hotels. The company expanded their hotels business and then invested in tobacco and insurance with Lorillard Tobacco and CNA Financial Corp. Loews also owns watchmaker Bulova Corp., and has had a controlling stake in Diamond Offshore Drilling since 1989. Laurence Tisch died in 2003 at the age of 80. His son, James Tisch, 54, has been CEO since 1999. Preston Robert Tisch died in 2005. XTO Energy Chief Executive Officer Bob Simpson is using the company&#39;s biggest-ever acquisition to add to existing holdings in East Texas, Oklahoma, Colorado, New Mexico and Wyoming. The company had oil and gas reserves equal to about 8.55 trillion cubic feet of gas on Dec. 31. Gas accounted for 85 percent of the total. The company said it replaced 302 percent of the oil and gas it pumped last year. XTO said it is considering setting up a master limited partnership, with an initial capitalization of $500 million, to hold some of its oil and gas properties and provide greater value to investors because of the tax structure. U.S. oil and gas producers Pioneer Natural Resources Co. and Plains Exploration & Production Co. in April said they may form similar partnerships to take over some of their established fields. Such partnerships distribute most of their earnings to unit holders and are not subject to corporate taxation. Investors get higher cash payouts than a company would otherwise pay in dividends, and taxes on some of the income can be deferred. XTO shares jumped $3.18, or 5.5 percent, to $61.55 at 3 p.m. in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. They are up 46 percent in the past year, the most among the six members of the S&P 500 Oil and Gas Exploration and Production Index. Shares of XTO are up because of the news that they are considering an MLP, according to oil and gas analyst Fadel Gheit of Oppenheimer & Co. Gheit rates XTO stock a buy and doesn&#39;t own any. Shares of Dominion rose 48 cents, or 0.6 percent, to $88.12, while Loews gained 99 cents to a record $52.01. Dominion said it still plans to sell its mid-continent assets. These are primarily in Oklahoma and equal about 780 billion cubic feet of gas. The transaction should be completed by the end of this year. The company said it now has agreements covering about 85 percent of the reserves it plans to shed. The company is keeping some producing properties in Appalachia. JPMorgan Chase & Co. and Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. are among the firms advising Dominion on the asset sales. Other utility companies also have been selling non-power businesses. Last year, Duke Energy Corp. spun off Spectra Energy Corp., a natural gas pipeline unit. In 2004, KeySpan Corp. sold its stake in oil and natural gas producer Houston Exploration Co. Dominion&#39;s shares have risen 18 percent in the past year, lagging behind the 25 percent gain for the Dow Jones Utilities Average, which has 15 members. Dominion said a year ago that investor concern about potential losses at the oil and gas business held down the share price. The divestures will leave Dominion as an owner of 7,800 miles of natural-gas pipelines, almost a quarter of U.S. natural gas storage, a natural-gas import terminal in Maryland, Virginia&#39;s biggest electric utility and power plants capable of generating 26,300 megawatts, enough to power 20.8 million U.S. homes based on U.S. Energy Department figures. To contact the reporter on this story: Dan Lonkevich in New York at Last Updated: June 4, 2007 14:58 EDT Factory Orders in U.S. Increased 0.3 Percent in April, Less Than Estimated Oil Rises Above $66 on Increased Fuel Demand, Threats to Nigerian Supply U.S. Stocks Rise to Records, Led by Oil Producers; Wal-Mart, XTO Advance
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-4&fd=R&url=http://www.networkworld.com/news/2007/060407-yahoo-opens-access-to-ad.html&cid=1116959869&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Yahoo opens access to ad system APIs - Network World rxptopicname: Servers & Data Center rxptopicname: Servers & Data Center Firewalls / VPN / Intrusion Servers & Data Center This Week in Print -Virtual Academy of Technology Faster, smarter, safer ... the new style of storage The latest security trends and technologies See your link here. Servers & Data Center Yahoo opens access to ad system APIs By Juan Carlos Perez, IDG News Service, 06/04/07 Yahoo Inc. is making APIs (application programming interfaces) available for external developers so that they can build tools and applications for its new Panama search advertising platform. Other stories on this topic With Yahoo deal off, what next for Microsoft? McAfee: Search results can be dangerous Humans get bigger role in search Better data center management with virtualization. Howard Anderson says online gaming could be the killer app for convergence. Vyatta targets Cisco channel with new open-source networking partner program CCIE job openings in Boston, Morristown NJ, New York City and Philadelphia SecureCRT best terminal emulator? The APIs, available under the Yahoo Search Marketing Commercial API Program, are available to anyone but designed primarily for Yahoo search advertisers, ad agencies, search marketing consultants and commercial application developers, Yahoo said Monday. Yahoo wants these companies to develop complementary tools and applications that will enhance their use and their clients' use of Panama for tasks like designing, deploying, tracking, managing and refining search marketing campaigns. Yahoo has high hopes that Panama will help boost revenue from search engine advertising, a market dominated by rival Google Inc. Yahoo maintains that Panama significantly improves on its ability to match ads to search queries, and is convinced that this improved targeting will increase the number of times users click on its search engine pay-per-click ads. While ad-serving enhancements are certainly important for Yahoo to improve its position against Google, Panama doesn't directly address the other big component of search wars: user popularity. Google still draws significantly more users to its search engines than Yahoo does, so Google's ads are seen by more people and as such are more likely to get clicked on. For example, in April, U.S. users ran almost half of all queries through Google's search engines, while Yahoo processed almost 27 percent, according to comScore Networks Inc. In total numbers, this means that Google had 3.6 billion queries on its search engines and Yahoo had 2 billion. Thus, in addition to improving its ad system, Yahoo needs to cut that popularity gap if it wants to significantly raise its search ad revenue. Different levels of access to the Panama APIs exist, both free and fee-based. More details are on the The IDG News Service is a Network World affiliate. &copy; Copyright 2007 Network World Inc. | Be the first to comment on this article to have your user name appear; otherwise your comment will show up as "Anonymous." *Anonymous comments will only appear once they are approved by the moderator. Already have an account? to see if you're logged in. Sign up for the Video & Podcast Alert Newsletter Keith travels the floor of Interop looking at some of the gimmicks vendors use to attract attendees. Magicians, performers and games from the '70s seem to all work. What Google bought in the past 12 months Avaya buyout rumors reveal VoIP market churn Did Street View spook Eric Schmidt? Malware hidden in fake IRS notices Adult filmmakers taking their lumps on &#8216;Net? Google Desktop vulnerable to new attack EMC buys authentication service provider Verid Will Cisco suffer IBM's fate? Michigan man fined for using free Wi-Fi Michigan man fined for using free Wi-Fi What Network World