http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-2&fd=R&url=http://business.iafrica.com/news/932868.htm&cid=1116960181&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg business.iafrica.com | business news Uranium One acquires Energy Metals » More market data [ h o m e ] Take control of your financial future with our expert personal finance advice. Mon, 04 Jun 2007 Want to know what's happening in the world of finance? Sign up for our daily newsletter and we'll deliver the day's business stories, analysis and market data straight to your inbox for free! Uranium One acquires Energy Metals Mon, 04 Jun 2007 South African and Canadian listed mining group Uranium One announced on Monday that it has signed a definitive agreement to acquire Energy Metals Corporation. In a statement, Uranium One said the acquisition will dramatically enhance the group's asset portfolio in the United States and solidify the new Uranium One's ability to build a leading US uranium producer. Under the terms of the agreement, EMC shareholders will receive 1.15 common shares of Uranium One for each issued share of EMC, representing a value of C$19.12 per share based upon the closing price of Uranium One on the TSX on 1 June 2007. This represents a 28 percent premium to the 20-day volume weighted average trading prices of Uranium One's and EMC's shares on the TSX for the period ending 17 May 2007, the day before EMC announced that it had entered into exclusive negotiations with respect to a potential sale of the company. "The acquisition of EMC is consistent with Uranium One's value-accretive external growth strategy and will consolidate Uranium One's position in the United States," Uranium One said. It added that on a pro forma basis, the group will have a fully diluted market capitalisation of $7.8-billion and improved liquidity as well as a strong balance sheet with a combined cash balance of $678-million. The group will also have a balanced and geographically diversified portfolio of reserves and resources, with the second largest uranium reserve and resource base in the world in terms of publicly traded, pure play uranium companies. Commenting on the proposed acquisition, Neal Froneman, Uranium One president and CEO said: "With our solid position in Kazakhstan and South Africa, the acquisition of EMC fits in perfectly with our stated strategy of value-accretive external growth and our focus on growth in the United States. Creating a diversified portfolio “The combination of Uranium One and EMC will create a powerhouse in the United States uranium sector with the potential to become the domestic supplier of choice for US utilities. Our combined portfolio of assets will be geographically diversified, with assets in the world's top five uranium jurisdictions. The existing conventional mining and ISR expertise within Uranium One, coupled with the excellent technical team that EMC has built over the past several years will result in one of the industry's leading technical teams, with the necessary expertise to deliver on development and growth opportunities in the United States." Paul Matysek, President and CEO of EMC added: "The transaction provides our shareholders immediate exposure to uranium production and cash flow, while at the same time creating new avenues for growth. “The addition of Uranium One's technical team will augment our elite ISR staff and provide us with the ability to develop our US conventional uranium assets, which are incremental to our current growth strategy. The new Uranium One's significant resource base, strong balance sheet and proven management team will ensure that the company becomes one of the world's leading diversified uranium producers. My colleagues and I at EMC look forward to continuing to play an important role in what I believe to be the fastest growing and most dynamic uranium company in the world." On completion of the transaction, it is expected that current Uranium One shareholders will own approximately 79 percent of the combined company and current EMC shareholders will own approximately 21 percent. Copyright © 2002-2005 iafrica.com, a division of Metropolis* - a Primedia company Reproduction without permission is prohibited. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-1&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/06/04/business/avaya.php&cid=1116948983&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Private equity firms near to acquiring Avaya in $8 billion deal - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings Private equity firms near to acquiring Avaya in $8 billion deal By Andrew Ross Sorkin and Michael J. de la Merced Published: June 4, 2007 Avaya is near a deal to sell itself to Silver Lake Partners and TPG for more than $8 billion in the latest buyout in the telecommunications industry, according to people briefed on the sale. The two private equity firms appear to have bested a rival bid from Nortel Networks and a deal may be announced Monday, those people said. But they cautioned that the talks were ongoing and that Nortel could still make a higher bid. The firms are expected to pay about $17 a share, the people said. Avaya&#039;s shares closed Friday at $16.08, and in afternoon trading Monday, they were up 68 cents at $16.76. Speculation about a buyout first arose two weeks ago, when the company unexpectedly postponed a meeting with analysts without offering an explanation or setting a new date. An Avaya spokeswoman declined to comment. Avaya, which was once part of Lucent Technologies and AT&#038;T before that, is one of the top U.S. makers of phone equipment, rivaling Cisco, Nortel and Alcatel-Lucent in providing Internet-based communications to corporations. Much of its business focuses on upgrading companies to voice networks that include video and data services. Today in Technology &#038; Media Suddenly, the Weather Channel is controversial Netflix offers $1 million prize for a more accurate system to find what online movies customers want At her request, Hillary Clinton is getting a presidential theme song from YouTube viewers The company suffered in 2002 as the dot-com bubble burst. But its financial health has rebounded so strongly that a Merrill Lynch analyst recently described Avaya as an ideal buyout candidate. The move comes amid heavy deal-making in the telecommunications sector. Last month, Alltel, the wireless service provider, agreed to a $27.5 billion buyout by TPG, formerly called Texas Pacific Group, and a unit of Goldman Sachs. Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; Corruption in China: The anger boils over Chinese drug commissioner is sentenced to death Understanding and coping with tremors An escapee tells of life and death in North Korea&#39;s labor camps Malaysia rejects Muslim convert&#39;s bid to be recognized as Christian A rare glimpse of 19th-century Iran With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Genes take charge, and diets fall by the wayside U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Tracing a poison&#39;s global path back to China Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation Do not neglect culture In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy The assault on Assyrian Christians No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; IHT.com on the go Listen to IHT articles on your computer, and create custom podcasts for your portable music player. Today's Page One in Europe Today's Page One in Asia Adver