http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-4&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3DauTbQgdCmA5Y%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116948983&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg , Jun 04 17:18 , Jun 04 22:18 , Jun 05 06:18 Silver Lake to Buy Avaya for $8 Billion, NYT Says (Update3) June 4 (Bloomberg) -- Silver Lake Partners and TPG Inc. agreed to buy Avaya Inc. for about $8 billion in the largest leveraged buyout of a computer-networking company, the New York Times reported. Avaya shareholders will receive about $17 a share, the Times said, citing unidentified people familiar with the transaction. That&#39;s 5.7 percent more than Basking Ridge, New Jersey-based Avaya&#39;s closing price on June 1, and 24 percent more than the price before speculation about the purchase surfaced. The deal would give the buyout firms the world&#39;s biggest maker of corporate phone equipment, going head to head with Cisco Systems Inc. in the $5 billion market for Web-based gear. The acquisition also would mark private equity&#39;s latest dive into the technology and communications industry, following deals last month for Acxiom Corp., Alltel Corp. and CDW Corp. ``You&#39;ve got one or two strategic buyers and a couple of private-equity buyers looking at the asset and trying to see if it makes sense for them,&#39;&#39; Prudential Equity Group analyst Inder Singh said in an interview today. ``For private equity, it makes sense from a financial standpoint because Avaya is a fairly strong cash generator.&#39;&#39; Avaya spokeswoman Lynn Newman said the company doesn&#39;t comment on rumors or speculation. Shares of Avaya jumped 64 cents, or 4 percent, to $16.72 at 4 p.m. in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. They climbed 15 percent on May 29 after the Wall Street Journal reported that Avaya was in talks with Silver Lake. Takeover speculation began building last month when Merrill Lynch & Co. analyst Tal Liani said in a report that Avaya would be a ``perfect&#39;&#39; buyout candidate because of its improving cash flow and profit margins. The company then canceled an analysts&#39; day scheduled for May 31. ``That&#39;s when it really came to the spotlight,&#39;&#39; said William Choi, an analyst at Jefferies & Co. in New York, who rates Avaya shares ``hold.&#39;&#39; He said Nortel Networks Corp., North America&#39;s largest maker of phone gear, was involved in talks with Avaya in early May. Nortel spokesman Jay Barta declined to comment. Buyout firms globally have engaged in 993 deals this year valued at about $450 billion, according to Bloomberg data, following last year&#39;s record $701.5 billion. TPG, formerly Texas Pacific Group, was founded in 1992 by David Bonderman, 64, James Coulter, 47, and Bill Price, 51. The Fort Worth, Texas-based firm raised $15 billion last year. The firm and Silver Lake bought Sabre Holdings Inc., the owner of tourism Web site Travelocity.com, this year for $4.4 billion. They also helped make up the group that bought financial software and services provider SunGard Data Systems Inc. in July 2005 for $11.3 billion. Silver Lake, founded in 1999, is the largest buyout fund to focus on technology. The company disclosed plans in January to raise as much as $10 billion for a new fund. Acxiom, a provider of computer and database services, said May 16 it&#39;s being acquired by Silver Lake and ValueAct Capital Partners LP for about $2.24 billion. Alltel, the fifth-biggest U.S. wireless service, agreed May 21 to be bought by TPG Inc. and Goldman Sachs Group Inc. for $27.5 billion. Madison Dearborn Partners LLC agreed on May 30 to buy computer reseller CDW for $7.3 billion. Avaya generated $205 million in operating cash in the fiscal second quarter and had cash and equivalents totaling $829 million at the end of March. Another attractive quality is that the company is debt free, Liani wrote. Avaya regained the top spot in the Web-based corporate phone equipment market in the first quarter with 25.3 percent, compared with Cisco&#39;s 25.2 percent. Second-quarter profit soared 50 percent to $38 million, or 8 cents a share, after severance costs dwindled, the company said in April. Sales increased 4.5 percent to $1.29 billion. Profit and revenue growth at Avaya have been trumped by San Jose, California-based Cisco, which entered the phone equipment market eight years ago. Unlike Cisco, Avaya is saddled with older, traditional phone systems, which have seen declining sales as clients upgrade to faster Web equipment. Avaya first sold shares to the public in September 2000, after being spun off from Lucent Technologies Inc., which wanted to focus on its fiber-optic and Internet equipment business. The shares peaked that month and then tumbled as the technology bubble burst. The company lost 95 percent of its stock market value before bottoming out in August 2002. Donald Peterson, a 10-year veteran of the old AT&T Corp. and Lucent, led Avaya through the IPO and held the position of chief executive officer until he was replaced last July by Louis D&#39;Ambrosio as part of a management shake-up. D&#39;Ambrosio joined the company in December 2002 after 16 years at International Business Machines Corp. To contact the reporter on this story: Ari Levy in San Francisco at Last Updated: June 4, 2007 16:13 EDT U.S. Stocks Rise to Records, Led by Oil Producers; Wal-Mart, XTO Advance Loews, XTO Will Buy Dominion&#39;s Onshore Oil, Gas Business for $6.5 Billion Ritchie Hedge Fund, Facing Losses, Plans Bankruptcy for Insurance Holdings
