call include: [ -10-pound casings of "MORAN'S All Natural, 73/27 fine ground beef." -10-pound casings of "MORAN'S All Natural, 90/10 fine ground sirloin." -2-pound chubs of "INTER-AMERICAN PRODUCTS 93/7 ground beef." -1-pound chubs of "INTER-AMERICAN PRODUCTS 80/20 ground beef." -1-pound chubs of "MORAN'S All Natural 73/27 ground beef." -5-pound chubs of "MORAN'S All Natural 73/27 ground beef." -3-pound chubs of "MORAN'S All Natural 73/27 ground beef." -1-pound chubs of "MORAN'S All Natural, 90/10 fine ground sirloin." -2-pound chubs of "MORAN'S All Natural 93/7 ground beef." -2-pound chubs of "MORAN'S All Natural 96/4 ground beef." -3-pound chubs of "STATER BROS. MARKETS 73/27 ground beef." Consumers with food safety questions can "Ask Karen," the FSIS virtual representative available 24 hours a day at . The toll-free USDA Meat and Poultry Hotline 1-888-MPHotline (1-888-674-6854) is available in English and Spanish and can be reached from l0 a.m. to 4 p.m. (Eastern Time) Monday through Friday. Recorded food safety messages are available 24 hours a day. Copyright 2007 Integrated Management Information, Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-4&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/palm-sells-stake-elevation-former/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257BB5933F97-E4D3-4C99-83D5-7B6CF9F29A8D%257D&cid=1116950216&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Palm sells stake to Elevation; former Apple execs join ranks - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Palm Inc. to sell 25% stake to Elevation Partners Deal brings former high-level Apple execs to Palm's management ranks Last Update: 5:13 PM ET Jun 4, 2007 SAN FRANCISCO (MarketWatch) -- Palm Inc. said Monday it has agreed to sell a 25% stake to Elevation Partners, a private-equity group, and plans to distribute $940 million to investors, capping months of deal speculation that have surrounded the wireless device maker. The recapitalization deal will also bring fresh talent to the company's management ranks - mostly from red-hot consumer electronics maker Apple Inc. As part of the deal, former Apple senior vice president Jon Rubinstein will become executive chairman at Palm . At Apple, Rubinstein was a key executive in the development of the company's popular iPod digital music player as well as the company's line of iMac computers. Fred Anderson, former CFO of Apple and a managing director at Elevation, will also join Palm's board of directors, as well as Elevation co-founder Roger McNamee. "We believe this strategic recapitalization with Elevation Partners will enable us to take maximum advantage of the huge market opportunity in front of us," Palm CEO Ed Colligan said in a conference call. "It will allow us to attract the best and brightest talent to create the most compelling mobile computing solutions, and is the most effective way to manage our balance sheet." Takeover speculation pumps stock price The deal comes after months of market speculation that Palm was negotiating a takeover deal. Rumors had the smartphone maker being bought out by larger wireless device makers such as Motorola Rumors of buyout deal drove shares of Palm up nearly 40% from late January to mid-March, when the stock peaked at $19.50. Speculation began to cool following the company's earnings report for its third fiscal quarter. On a conference call, executives said they were running the business with the intention of remaining independent. On Monday, shares of Palm closed trading up more than 9% at $17.57. Under the terms of the deal, Elevation will invest $325 million into Palm. Using those funds plus another $440 million in debt, Palm will give shareholders a $9-per-share cash distribution. The deal values Palm shares at $17.50, when you add the cash distribution to the $8.50 conversion price for Elevation. Seeing opportunity in software Palm, which pioneered the PDA market with its self-named device, was also an early mover in the smartphone market with its Treo product line. But the company faces heavy competition in the space from large, deep-pocketed rivals such as Nokia and Motorola as well as upstart Research in Motion , whose BlackBerry wireless e-mail device has proved particularly popular with the corporate crowd. In addition, Apple will be launching its much-anticipated iPhone on June 29. The touch-screen smartphone will be available through an exclusive deal with AT&T. As a result of the competition, Wall Street has become lukewarm on Palm, waiting to see if it can update its product line to win over more customers. Reaction among investors was tepid last week after the company unveiled its latest product - a laptop-like e-mail device called Foleo that is designed for wireless e-mail users who need a larger screen. For its part, Elevation believes that smartphones will soon hit a limit on how small and thin they can be without sacrificing functionality. So the advantage in the future will come from the software side. "If the devices get any smaller they will be unusable," McNamee of Elevation said during the call. "Palm will close that gap, we believe, relatively soon. At which point, we think the game is all about software, and we think software is the place where this company truly excels." McNamee pointed out that this was the largest investment to date by Elevation, which was formed in 2005 and boasts the membership of several Silicon Valley heavyweights as well as Bono, lead singer of the popular rock band U2. Wall Street remains cautious Andrew Neff of Bear Stearns removed his bearish underperform rating on Palm, upgrading the stock to peer perform, on news of the deal. Though he conceded that the company still faces challenges in the market. "Fundamentally, Palm faces numerous challenges with intense competition in its phone business, a decline in its old handheld business and the lackluster response to the new product demo'd last week," Neff wrote in a note to clients. "We are raising our rating to reflect our view that the private equity involvement will shift the valuation focus away from some of those near-term concerns." A more bullish view came from Jonathan Hoopes of ThinkEquity, who rates the stock as a buy. In a note, Hoopes compared the company to Apple prior to the development of products such as the iMac and iPod, which reinvigorated the company's business. "Today's deal should quiet skeptics as these new investors in Palm have 'been around the block' and clearly understand the value of a global brand, of a foundation based on software, and of design acumen," Hoopes wrote. Tim Long of Banc of America Securities kept his neutral rating on the stock. "We believe adding new management is an encouraging sign, but the impact of any changes would not likely impact results until next year, at the earliest," he wrote in a note. Dan Gallagher is a reporter for MarketWatch in San Francisco. Related Blog Posts & Articles Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Sign up to receive the U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 U.S. stock futures drop with bond yield rise, China in focus Five little-known tips for getting better gas mileage Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Three safe havens to stash your cash Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Palm sells stake to Elevation; former Apple execs join ranks Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Three safe havens to stash your cash Who has the hot hand? Flextronics to acquire Solectron for $3.6 bln DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 Telecom firm Avaya reportedly close to private-equity deal Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 More equity hedge funds are shorting ETFs rather than stocks Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Get the Latest MarketWatch News >> Industry: Technology, Hardware and Equipment Company: Palm Inc New (PALM) Company: Apple Inc (AAPL) Company: Motorola, Inc (MOT) Company: Nokia Corp (NOK) Company: Research In Motion Ltd (RIMM) Research In Motion Ltd Dow Jones Licensing Services Dow Jones Online Network: Copyright &copy; 2007 MarketWatch, Inc. All rights reserved. By using this site, you agree to the Palm sells stake to Elevation; former Apple execs join ranks - MarketWatch Intraday data provided by , a division of Interactive Data Corp. and subject to . Historical and current end-of-day data provided by . More information on and t