http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-6&fd=R&url=http://biznes.onet.pl/5,1547858,wiadomosci.html&cid=1116966193&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg DJ US Stocks Drop After Shanghai Stumble - DowJonesNewswires - Onet.pl Biznes - 04.06.2007 DJ US Stocks Drop After Shanghai Stumble (DowJonesNewswires, pr/04.06.2007, godz. 17:12) U.S. stocks dropped on Monday, as investors took news of another overnight stumble in the Shanghai stock market in stride, but cautiously monitored rising bond yields, which challenged the appeal of risk-taking in stocks. The Dow Jones Industrial Average was recently off 32.25 points to 13635.76, with 22 of its 30 components retreating, led by Coca Cola Co. (KO), McDonald's Corp. (MCD) and Procter & Gamble Co. (PG). Bucking the trend among blue chips, Wal-Mart Stores Inc. (WMT) rose 3%. The stock was upgraded by JP Morgan, HSBC, Wachovia and Morgan Stanley following the retail giant's shareholder meeting, where it revealed plans to cut capital spending and return more cash to shareholders. General Electric Co. (GE) also rose 1.3% after a Barron's article outlined the case for breaking up the juggernaut multinational. The S&P 500 index fell 1.69 points to 1534.65, while the Nasdaq Composite eased 5.44 points to 2608.48. Deal-making news, including Flextronics International Ltd.'s (FLEX) agreement to buy Solectron Corp. (SLR) for $3.6 billion, provided some support for tech shares and the broad market in early action. Palm (PALM) jumped 7.2% after agreeing to sell 25% of the firm to a private-equity firm for $325 million. The mild dip in U.S. trading signaled that investors aren't overly worried about yet another stumble in the Shanghai stock market. In spite of an 8% battering in Shanghai, other Asian markets recovered, including the Hang Seng in Hong Kong and the Nikkei in Tokyo. A tumble in the Chinese stock market last week was followed by rally on Wall Street the next day. When Shanghai fell sharply in late February, the Dow industrials plunged 416 points. But since then, U.S. stocks have staged an impressive rally. Through May alone, the Dow gained 4.3%, the S&P advanced 3.2% and the Nasdaq gained 3.1%. Last week, a slew of better-than-expected data, including the May employment report, boosted confidence in the economy and helped the Dow gain 1.2%, the S&P 1.4% and the Nasdaq 2.2%. Yet, strong data also pressured bond prices, pushing their yields, which move inversely to price, much higher. The yield on the benchmark 10-year Treasury note surpassed 5%, its highest level since mid-August. On Monday, the 10-year note rose 1/32 to 96 16/32, while its yield fell to 4.95%, amid safe-haven buying from the Shanghai sell off. Should U.S. stocks finally halt their impressive rally this week, "it will either be that investors turn their attention to rocketing interest rates or it will have to come from Wednesday's economic release on productivity and unit labor costs," said Marc Pado, market strategist at Cantor Fitzgerald. There was limited reaction to news that factor orders rose 0.3% in April, below the 0.8% expected by economists surveyed by MarketWatch. Orders in March were revised up to 4.1% from 3.5% previously, putting the level of orders close to expectations. The government also said businesses boosted their capital spending in April at a faster pace than previously reported. After the data, the dollar remained weaker against rivals. Crude-oil prices rose 51 cents to $65.59 amid concerns that a tropical cyclone might enter the Persian Gulf on Wednesday. Gold prices also rose as crude oil advanced and the dollar fell. More deal-making developments might help the bulls push the market further into record territory later in the session. A meeting between the Bancroft family, which controls Dow Jones (DJ), and Rupert Murdoch, whose company News Corp. (NWS) made a $5 billion bid for Dow Jones, is scheduled to take place on Monday. Dominion (D) agreed to sell some U.S. gas and oil operations to Loews (LTR) for $4 billion and other operations to XTO Energy (XTO) for $2.5 billion. Avaya (AV) rose more than 3% after The Wall Street Journal reported it is close to a deal to be bought by TPG Capital and Silver Lake Partners for $17 a share, the newspaper added, citing people familiar with the matter. Health Care Properties (HCP) agreed to buy U.S. biotech real estate from Britain's Segro for $2.9 billion. Qiagen (QGEN) agreed to buy Digene (DIGE) for $1.6 billion in cash and stock. AXA (AXA) agreed to sell a Dutch unit for $2.35 billion to SNS Reaal of Holland. Subprime mortgage firm Accredited Home Lenders Holding Co. (LEND) said it agreed to be acquired by Lone Star Fund V L.P. for about $400 million, or $15.10 a share, in an all-cash deal. Investors in the pharmaceutical industry were paying close attention the American Society of Clinical Oncology meeting in Chicago. Roche (RHHBY), majority owner of Genentech (DNA), fell in Swiss trading on concerns about Avastin's colorectal cancer performance as well as that a lower-dose Avastin version showed improved survival in lung cancer. Bayer (BAY) rose in Germany after it and Onyx (ONXX) reported improved survival from patients taking a liver cancer drug. Early-stage trials from Arqule (ARQL) and Exelexis (EXEL) showed "impressive" response rates, according to analysts at Rodman & Renshaw. Copyright C2003, Dow Jones and Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved Nie ma jeszcze ¿adnych komentarzy Notowania opó¼nione o 15 min. Copyright 1996 - 2007 Grupa Onet.pl SA
