http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-0&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/dominion-sell-most-natural-gas-assets/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257B5D3F471B-34F6-46F6-8365-BB73BCAA2061%257D&cid=1116957983&ei=iIBkRpfiIaPkqQPqq_SfBg Dominion to sell most onshore gas assets; price tag disappoints - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Dominion to sell most onshore natural-gas assets Price tag of $6.5 billion 'a disappointment,' according to brokers Last Update: 4:41 PM ET Jun 4, 2007 SAN FRANCISCO (MarketWatch) -- Utility Dominion Resources Inc. said Monday that it signed two deals to sell most of its U.S. onshore natural-gas and oil operations for about $6.5 billion, extending its plans to quit the business of producing the fuel used to run its power plants. , whose holdings include the makers of Newport cigarettes and Bulova watches as well as oil and gas companies, will pay $4.03 billion in cash for Dominion's mostly natural-gas assets in the Permian Basin in West Texas, the Antrim Shale in Michigan and the Black Warrior Basin in Alabama. "We have a favorable long-term view of natural-gas pricing in the United States and believe natural gas will increasingly be the fuel of choice in the future," said Loews Chief Executive James Tisch in a statement. Natural-gas producer XTO Energy Inc. will pay $2.5 billion for Dominion's operations in the Rocky Mountains, Gulf Coast, San Juan Basin and southern Louisiana. XTO said that it is considering setting up a $500 million limited partnership to include its production properties, including the Dominion assets. XTO shares shot up to a record high of $62.25 and ended the day 5.6% higher at $61.61. Loews shares also hit a new all-time before closing 2.6% higher at $52.35. Dominion shares closed up 0.3% to $87.87. The sale, which was expected, continues Dominion's retrenchment from natural-gas production as it concentrates on its core natural-gas transport, storage and power operations. Previously, the Richmond, Va.-based company had agreed to sell nearly all its offshore Gulf of Mexico oil and gas operations for $4.76 billion, as well as its Canadian oil and gas reserves for $583 million. But several analysts said that they had expected Dominion would fetch more for its assets. Banc of America Securities analyst Shelby Tucker called the $6.5 billion in anticipated proceeds "disappointing," saying Monday that he had estimated Dominion would make about $8 billion on the operations. BMO Capital Markets lowered its rating on the company to market perform from outperform on the sale and cut its price target by $9 to $95. "It now appears that total [exploration and production] proceeds could total about $13 billion to $13.5 billion, below our $14 billion to $16 billion projection," BMO analyst Michael Worms wrote in a note to investors. In November, Dominion announced plans to sell all of its exploration and production operations, except its holdings in the Appalachian Basin, as it tried to make its risk profile more similar to those of other utilities. It said that it would use proceeds to pay down debt, buy shares, and acquire other assets to strengthen its remaining businesses. Monday's sale includes 3.51 trillion cubic feet equivalent of proved natural-gas and oil reserves as of Dec. 31. The company has now arranged to sell 85% of the reserves it plans to sell. HSBC Securities analyst Angie Storozynski said that she now expects Dominion will make about $13.7 billion from the entire sale, down from her previous estimate of $15.2 billion. She also cut her price target on the stock. After the divestures, Dominion said that it should be able to post at least $6 a share in 2008 operating earnings. Dominion Chief Executive Thomas Farrell added that the company's earnings per share should be able to increase at least 4% to 6% a year in the following years. Laura Mandaro is a reporter for MarketWatch in San Francisco. Related Blog Posts & Articles Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Sign up to receive the Weekend TV Show Preview U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 U.S. stock futures drop with bond yield rise, China in focus Five little-known tips for getting better gas mileage Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Three safe havens to stash your cash Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Palm sells stake to Elevation; former Apple execs join ranks Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Three safe havens to stash your cash Who has the hot hand? Flextronics to acquire Solectron for $3.6 bln DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 Telecom firm Avaya reportedly close to private-equity deal Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 More equity hedge funds are shorting ETFs rather than stocks Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Get the Latest MarketWatch News >> Industry: Oil and Gas Company: Loews Corporation (LTR) Company: XTO Energy Inc (XTO) Company: Dominion Resources Inc (D) Dow Jones Licensing Services Dow Jones Online Network: Copyright &copy; 2007 MarketWatch, Inc. All rights reserved. By using this site, you agree to the Dominion to sell most onshore gas assets; price tag disappoints - MarketWatch Intraday data provided by , a